h, especially the [[home counties]].\n\nToday there is no heavy manufacturing industry in which UK-based firms can be considered world leaders and no product in which a UK city or region is ''the'' world leader. {{citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nHowever, the [[English Midlands|Midlands]], in particular, remains a strong manufacturing centre, with around a fifth of employment dependent on manufacturing, and the [[East Midlands Development Agency]] has a policy to maintaining this characteristic.\n\nMore recently, high technology firms have concentrated largely along the [[M4 motorway]], partly because of access to [[London Heathrow Airport]], but also because of the [[economies of agglomeration]].  However, the general pattern remains that the south has lower, and falling, reliance on manufacturing.\n\n==Finance and services==\n[[File:Leeds CBD at night.jpg|thumb|350px|[[Leeds]]' Central Business District]]\n{{See also|Economy of London}}\n\nOnce, every great city had a [[stock exchange]]. Now, the UK financial industry is concentrated overwhelmingly in the [[City of London]] and [[Canary Wharf]], with back office and administrative operation often  dispersed around the south of England.\n\nLondon is one of the world's great [[financial centre]]s, which is one of the factors that is commonly considered to make it a [[world city]].  [[Central London]] contains some of the most expensive [[real estate|commercial property]] in the world because of this.\n\nFrom around the early 1990s London has been able to boast of having more U.S. banks than New York, as well as being host to branches of more than five hundred overseas banks.  It is the principal financial centre of the world, ranked alongside New York and Tokyo as one of three where any serious financial player ''must'' be represented.\n\nThe [[City of London]] has around 300,000 employees, largely concentrated in the financial and professional sectors.\n\nWithin London, the desire for banks to be there put pressure on the City of London's ability to accommodate them.  In the mid-1980s a crisis point was reached and, although the City was able to expand its stock of modern office space, this did not happen before [[Canary Wharf]] had been set up as a competitor.  The irony is that Canary Wharf was built in the [[London Docklands]] that had, until 1970, been among the largest docks in the world. All manner of goods had been shipped from the factories of east London to the world; between 1961 and 1993 manufacturing employment in London fell from 1.6&nbsp;million to 328,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Exploring 20th century London: Work|publisher=Museum of London|url=http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/Collections-Research/Research/Your-Research/X20L/themes/1376/1376|accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-90's, [[Leeds]] took advantage of the internet's arrival as part of the [[.com boom]].  It became the UK's first city to have full broadband and digital coverage, making it a very attractive place for corporations to expand, particularly when opening call centres.  During the changing 1990's, Leeds had better connections to London than any other UK city, being 2 hours from London by train.  As a result, it is now the UK's 2nd largest financial and legal centre,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leedslegal.co.uk/ |title=Quality of Law \u2013 Quality of Advice |publisher=Leeds Legal |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006223040/http://www.leedslegal.co.uk/ |archivedate=6 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[http://www.transatlanticbc.net/article/leeds-business-week.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209003810/http://www.transatlanticbc.net/article/leeds-business-week.html |date=9 December 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/az--of-universities--leeds-1233402.html |title=A-Z of universities: Leeds \u2013 Education News, Education |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=2 October 1997 |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshire-forward.com/our-wonderful-region/key-industries/financial-services |title=Invest in financial services in Yorkshire & Humber |publisher=Yorkshire Forward |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.leedsfinancial.co.uk/28_KeySectors.html ]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/media_centre/files2007/Leeds+key+to+the+UKs+lead+in+financial+services.htm |title=Leeds key to the UK's lead in financial services |publisher=Cityoflondon.gov.uk |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=17 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221235927/http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/media_centre/files2007/Leeds+key+to+the+UKs+lead+in+financial+services.htm |archivedate=21 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the UK's largest e-business sector with more than 1/3 of the UK's internet traffic passing through the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginmedia.com/jobs/features/best-cities-for-jobs.php?ssid=3 |title=Cable broadband, TV & phone plus mobile broadband & phone |publisher=Virgin Media |date=25 March 2010 |accessdate=17 October 2011 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn this respect, Canary Wharf and Leeds are arguably more [[symbol]]ic of the changed economic geography of the UK than any other place.\n\n[[File:Canary Wharf Skyline 2, London UK - Oct 2012.jpg|thumb|350px|[[Canary Wharf]], [[London]]]]\n\n==Regional disparity==\n{{Original research|section|date=February 2016}}The combined effects of changing economic fortunes, economic restructuring and the decline of the UK as an imperial power have created the so-called [[North-South divide in the United Kingdom|North\u2013South divide]], in which decaying industrial areas of the Midlands and north of England and Scotland contrast with the wealthy, finance-and-technology-led southern economy. This has led successive governments to develop [[regional policy|regional policies]] to try to rectify the imbalance.\n\nThe success has been, at best, patchy and the uneven distribution of economic wealth in the UK has led to migration from north to south, aggravating serious pressure on the southern housing market.\n\nAlthough, in 2004, house prices in the north of England and Scotland increased faster than those in the south, this happened at the same stage of the last property cycle and the rises are off of a lower value base \u2013 it is far too early{{When|date=February 2016}} to conclude whether the trend is reversing.  Either way, there were 113,000 transactions in London and the [[South east England|South East]] recorded by the UK [[HM Land Registry]] in the year to November 2004, compared with 83,000 in the [[Northern England|North]], [[North West England|North West]] and [[Yorkshire and the Humber]].\n\nThis is not to say that the south is uniformly wealthy; some of the worst pockets of deprivation can be found in London, especially inner London, while [[Hastings]] and [[Bexhill-on-Sea]], on the south coast, are also subject to urgent regeneration efforts.\n\n==Quotes==\n<center>''\"This island is made mainly of coal and surrounded by fish.  Only an organising genius could produce a shortage of coal and fish at the same time.\"''<br>\n[[Aneurin Bevan]], ''From a speech in [[Blackpool]], 25 May 1945''</center>\n\n==References and further reading==\n*''An Historical Geography of England and Wales'', Robert A. Dodgshon, R.A. Butlin, Academic Press, {{ISBN|0-12-219252-4}}\n* ''The Changing Geography of the United Kingdom'' Hugh Matthews, Vince Gardiner (eds), Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17901-7}}\n* ''Spatial Divisions of Labour'', Doreen Massey, Macmillan, {{ISBN|0-333-59494-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Geography of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Culture of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Politics of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of renewable resources produced and traded by the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041122191056/http://www.odpm.gov.uk/ Office of the Deputy Prime Minister] \u2013 controls regional policy\n*[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20070603164510/http://www.dti.gov.uk/ Department of Trade and Industry]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160819163543/http://www.ons.gov.uk/businessindustryandtrade/business/businessservices/bulletins/uknonfinancialbusinesseconomy/2014regionalresultsannualbusinesssurvey UK non-financial business economy: 2014 regional results (Annual Business Survey)]\n\n{{Economy of the United Kingdom}}\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economic Geography Of The United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:Geography of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Economic geography]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_geography_of_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "A Poem Is a Naked Person", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Poem Is a Naked Person\n| image          = A Poem is a Naked Person.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film poster\n| film name      = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)-->\n| director       = [[Les Blank]]\n| producer       = <!-- or: |producers = -->\n| writer         = <!-- or: |writers = -->\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| starring       = \n| narrator       = <!-- or: |narrators = -->\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = <!-- or: |production companies = -->\n| distributor    = [[Janus Films]]\n| released       = {{film date|2015|07|01|New York City|fy=1974}} \n| runtime        = \n| country        = \n| language       = \n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n'''''A Poem Is A Naked Person''''' is a film directed by [[Les Blank]], filmed in 1972-1974 but not publicly released until 2015, after Blank's death.  The film is a documentary about musician [[Leon Russell]], produced and financed largely by Russell and his then-business partner [[Denny Cordell]].  Blank spent a large portion of two years on the film, but then its release was delayed for forty years due to creative differences and music clearance problems.  Blank's son, [[Harrod Blank]] (who was a child when the movie was filmed), spent years working on the clearances, before it was finally shown publicly in 2015.<ref name=\"Eagan\">Daniel Eagan, [http://www.filmcomment.com/entry/back-home-les-blanks-a-poem-is-a-naked-person \"Back Home: Les Blank's A Poem Is A Naked Person\"], ''[[Film Comment]]'', March 16, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Production==\nBlank and his assistant Maureen Gosling spent extensive time with Russell at his recording studio on [[Grand Lake o' the Cherokees|Grand Lake]] in [[Oklahoma]].  Blank shot many hours of footage for the film, including the expected concerts, rehearsals, and interviews, but also atmospheric material intended to capture the mood and surroundings, later described by Harrod Blank as \"what he [Les] was attracted to: lake footage, sunsets, beautiful women, eccentric characters, Oklahoma folk.\" A portion of the film depicted underground artist [[Jim Franklin (artist)|Jim Franklin]] painting a mural in Russell's empty swimming pool.  The result was an untraditional film whose fate became even more uncertain after Russell and Cordell terminated their business relationship in 1976.<ref name=\"Eagan\"/><ref>Jerry Wofford, [http://www.tulsaworld.com/blogs/scene/offbeat/leon-russell-documentary-a-poem-is-a-naked-person-makes/article_2b0d751f-1190-514c-9038-8ded9040b7cd.html \"Leon Russell documentary 'A Poem is a Naked Person' makes debut at South by Southwest festival\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]'', March 23, 2015.</ref>\n\nFor many years, ''A Poem Is A Naked Person'' was shown only at special screenings with Les Blank in attendance.<ref name=\"Nilsen\">Lars Nilsen, [http://www.austinchronicle.com/screens/2015-03-13/counterculture-time-capsule/ \"Counterculture Time Capsule: Forty years later, Les Blank's Leon Russell rock doc sees the light of day\"], ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'', March 13, 2015.</ref><ref>Jonathan Marlow, [http://www.fandor.com/keyframe/the-art-of-filmmaking-les-blank \"The Art of Filmmaking: Les Blank\"], [[Fandor (film site)|Fandor]], December 2, 2014.</ref> In 2011 Russell told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' that he didn't like the film, and didn't intend to release it.<ref>Phil Gallo, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/472126/leon-russell-hits-the-road-after-union-success \"Leon Russell Hits the Road After 'Union' Success\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', April 11, 2011.</ref> Also in 2011, when the [[International Documentary Association]] honored Blank with a career achievement award, the film was described as \"perhaps the greatest film about rock 'n' roll and American music that you will likely never see\".<ref>Taylor Segrest, [http://www.documentary.org/feature/career-achievement-award-visionary-wayfarer-les-blank \"2011 Career Achievement Award--Visionary Wayfarer: Les Blank\"], ''Documentary Magazine'', Winter 2012.</ref>  The film finally received its public premiere (with Russell in the audience) in March 2015 at the [[South by Southwest]] festival in [[Austin, Texas]], prior to theatrical and DVD release.<ref name=\"Nilsen\"/> The movie was released on DVD and Blu-ray by [[The Criterion Collection]] on March 29, 2016.\n\n==Reception==\nIn 1979 [[Robert Christgau]] wrote a lengthy article about Les Blank that for the most part praised Blank's work in his food-oriented documentaries, but included sharp criticisms of this film.  Christgau derided it as an \"arty horror movie of a documentary\" that \"abandons subtlety for an overstated visual gadgetry that screams repulsion out of control.\"<ref name=\"Christgau\">[[Robert Christgau]], [http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/misc/blank-79.php \"Music, Food & the Idea of the 'Folk': Contra Les Blank\"], ''[[The Village Voice]]'', November 19, 1979.</ref>\n\nWhen the film was finally released, however, critical reception was positive.  Writing for ''[[Film Comment]]'', Daniel Eagan noted the \"extraordinary concert footage\" of \"intimate, sweaty, incantatory music shaped for the moment at hand\" as well as studio footage with \"a different sense of intimacy, of polished professionals displaying casual, almost effortless expertise.\"<ref name=\"Eagan\"/>  Carson Lund of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' praised it as \"a free-floating portrait of the eccentric neo-Gospel Oklahoman frying pan that is Russell's mini-universe\".<ref>Carson Lund, [http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/sxsw-2015-the-boy-6-years-a-poem-is-a-naked-person \"SXSW 2015: The Boy, 6 Years, & A Poem Is a Naked Person\"], ''[[Slant Magazine]]'',  March 17, 2015.</ref> Alex Pappademas of ''[[Grantland]]'' said it was \"one of the greatest rock documentaries I\u2019ve ever seen, as eloquent an evocation of the reality-distortion field around rock stars as [[D.A. Pennebaker]]\u2019s ''[[Dont Look Back]]'' or [[Robert Frank]]\u2019s ''[[Cocksucker Blues]]'', but funnier and stranger than either.\"<ref>Alex Pappademas, [http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/sxsw-film-fest-superlatives-rock-docs-yuppie-nightmares-and-a-ghost-in-your-iphone/ \"SXSW Film Fest Superlatives: Rock Docs, Yuppie Nightmares, and a Ghost in Your iPhone\"], ''[[Grantland]]'', March 23, 2015.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1974]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0424359}}\n*[http://www.lesblank.com/?portfolio=a-poem-is-a-naked-person-1974 ''A Poem Is A Naked Person''] at Les Blank Films\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/3987-a-poem-is-a-naked-person-i-shall-be-released ''A Poem Is a Naked Person: I Shall Be Released''] an essay by Kent Jones at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n{{Les Blank}}\n{{Leon Russell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poem Is A Naked Person}}\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Les Blank]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1970s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films set in Oklahoma]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Poem Is a Naked Person\n| image          = A Poem is a Naked Person.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film poster\n| film name      = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)-->\n| director       = [[Les Blank]]\n| producer       = <!-- or: |producers = -->\n| writer         = <!-- or: |writers = -->\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| starring       = \n| narrator       = <!-- or: |narrators = -->\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = <!-- or: |production companies = -->\n| distributor    = [[Janus Films]]\n| released       = {{film date|2015|07|01|New York City}} \n| runtime        = \n| country        = \n| language       = \n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n'''''A Poem Is A Naked Person''''' is a film directed by [[Les Blank]], filmed in 1972-1974 but not publicly released until 2015, after Blank's death.  The film is a documentary about musician [[Leon Russell]], produced and financed largely by Russell and his then-business partner [[Denny Cordell]].  Blank spent a large portion of two years on the film, but then its release was delayed for forty years due to creative differences and music clearance problems.  Blank's son, [[Harrod Blank]] (who was a child when the movie was filmed), spent years working on the clearances, before it was finally shown publicly in 2015.<ref name=\"Eagan\">Daniel Eagan, [http://www.filmcomment.com/entry/back-home-les-blanks-a-poem-is-a-naked-person \"Back Home: Les Blank's A Poem Is A Naked Person\"], ''[[Film Comment]]'', March 16, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Production==\nBlank and his assistant Maureen Gosling spent extensive time with Russell at his recording studio on [[Grand Lake o' the Cherokees|Grand Lake]] in [[Oklahoma]].  Blank shot many hours of footage for the film, including the expected concerts, rehearsals, and interviews, but also atmospheric material intended to capture the mood and surroundings, later described by Harrod Blank as \"what he [Les] was attracted to: lake footage, sunsets, beautiful women, eccentric characters, Oklahoma folk.\" A portion of the film depicted underground artist [[Jim Franklin (artist)|Jim Franklin]] painting a mural in Russell's empty swimming pool.  The result was an untraditional film whose fate became even more uncertain after Russell and Cordell terminated their business relationship in 1976.<ref name=\"Eagan\"/><ref>Jerry Wofford, [http://www.tulsaworld.com/blogs/scene/offbeat/leon-russell-documentary-a-poem-is-a-naked-person-makes/article_2b0d751f-1190-514c-9038-8ded9040b7cd.html \"Leon Russell documentary 'A Poem is a Naked Person' makes debut at South by Southwest festival\"], ''[[Tulsa World]]'', March 23, 2015.</ref>\n\nFor many years, ''A Poem Is A Naked Person'' was shown only at special screenings with Les Blank in attendance.<ref name=\"Nilsen\">Lars Nilsen, [http://www.austinchronicle.com/screens/2015-03-13/counterculture-time-capsule/ \"Counterculture Time Capsule: Forty years later, Les Blank's Leon Russell rock doc sees the light of day\"], ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'', March 13, 2015.</ref><ref>Jonathan Marlow, [http://www.fandor.com/keyframe/the-art-of-filmmaking-les-blank \"The Art of Filmmaking: Les Blank\"], [[Fandor (film site)|Fandor]], December 2, 2014.</ref> In 2011 Russell told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' that he didn't like the film, and didn't intend to release it.<ref>Phil Gallo, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/472126/leon-russell-hits-the-road-after-union-success \"Leon Russell Hits the Road After 'Union' Success\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', April 11, 2011.</ref> Also in 2011, when the [[International Documentary Association]] honored Blank with a career achievement award, the film was described as \"perhaps the greatest film about rock 'n' roll and American music that you will likely never see\".<ref>Taylor Segrest, [http://www.documentary.org/feature/career-achievement-award-visionary-wayfarer-les-blank \"2011 Career Achievement Award--Visionary Wayfarer: Les Blank\"], ''Documentary Magazine'', Winter 2012.</ref>  The film finally received its public premiere (with Russell in the audience) in March 2015 at the [[South by Southwest]] festival in [[Austin, Texas]], prior to theatrical and DVD release.<ref name=\"Nilsen\"/> The movie was released on DVD and Blu-ray by [[The Criterion Collection]] on March 29, 2016.\n\n==Reception==\nIn 1979 [[Robert Christgau]] wrote a lengthy article about Les Blank that for the most part praised Blank's work in his food-oriented documentaries, but included sharp criticisms of this film.  Christgau derided it as an \"arty horror movie of a documentary\" that \"abandons subtlety for an overstated visual gadgetry that screams repulsion out of control.\"<ref name=\"Christgau\">[[Robert Christgau]], [http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/misc/blank-79.php \"Music, Food & the Idea of the 'Folk': Contra Les Blank\"], ''[[The Village Voice]]'', November 19, 1979.</ref>\n\nWhen the film was finally released, however, critical reception was positive.  Writing for ''[[Film Comment]]'', Daniel Eagan noted the \"extraordinary concert footage\" of \"intimate, sweaty, incantatory music shaped for the moment at hand\" as well as studio footage with \"a different sense of intimacy, of polished professionals displaying casual, almost effortless expertise.\"<ref name=\"Eagan\"/>  Carson Lund of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' praised it as \"a free-floating portrait of the eccentric neo-Gospel Oklahoman frying pan that is Russell's mini-universe\".<ref>Carson Lund, [http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/sxsw-2015-the-boy-6-years-a-poem-is-a-naked-person \"SXSW 2015: The Boy, 6 Years, & A Poem Is a Naked Person\"], ''[[Slant Magazine]]'',  March 17, 2015.</ref> Alex Pappademas of ''[[Grantland]]'' said it was \"one of the greatest rock documentaries I\u2019ve ever seen, as eloquent an evocation of the reality-distortion field around rock stars as [[D.A. Pennebaker]]\u2019s ''[[Dont Look Back]]'' or [[Robert Frank]]\u2019s ''[[Cocksucker Blues]]'', but funnier and stranger than either.\"<ref>Alex Pappademas, [http://grantland.