{"title_page": "Mariya Livytska", "text_new": "{{short description|Wife of the first Ukrainian president}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Mariya Livytska <br> \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0456\u044f \u0412\u0430\u0440\u0444\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0457\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0430\n| image = \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0456\u044f_\u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0430_\u0437_\u0434\u043e\u043d\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e_\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043a\u043e\u044e.jpg\n| birth_name    = Mariya Varpholomiivna Tkachenko\n| birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1879|4|9}}|\n| birth_place = [[Zhmerynka]], [[Ukraine]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1971|8|16|1879|4|9|mf=y}}\n| death_place=[[Yonkers, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation = Former [[First Lady of Ukraine]]\n| order1= [[First Lady of Ukraine]]|\n| term_start1=1926|\n| term_end1=1954|\n| president1 = [[Andriy Livytskyi]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Olha Petliura]]|\n| successor1 = [[Melaniya Vytvytska]]|\n| alma_mater = \n| spouse = [[Andriy Livytskyi]] \n| children = [[Mykola Livytskyi]] <br>[[Hatalia Livytska-Kholodna]]\n| relations = \n}}\n'''Mariya Varpholomiivna Livytska''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'': Tkachenko; April 9, 1879 - August 16, 1971) was a [[Ukrainians|ukrainian]] writer, memoirist, and public figure. She was an Activist in the Ukrainian women's movement and headed the Union of Ukrainian Women in Poland. She was married to the president of the [[Ukrainian People's Republic]] in the exile of [[Andriy Livytskyi]].<ref>[https://blog.liga.net/user/ogorobets/article/32267 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0446\u044c \u00ab\u0417\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0456\u043b\u043b\u044f\u00bb \u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456\u0439 \u0433\u043b\u0438\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0456]</ref>\n\nIn 1897 she graduated from the Fundukleivka Women's Gymnasium in [[Kyiv]] and worked as a private teacher in and 1898-1899), while engaging in public and party activities. She became a member of the [[Revolutionary Ukrainian Party]], the [[Ukrainian Social Democratic Labour Party]], and became acquainted with its activists [[Mykola Mikhnovsky]], [[Mykola Porsh]]. She was a member of the Kyiv student community, which included [[Dmytro Antonovych]], [[Volodymyr Vynnychenko]], Olexander Scoropis-Yoltukhivsky, [[Andriy Livytskyi]], [[Liudmyla Starytska-Cherniakhivska]], [[Maria Hrinchenko]].\n\nMaria Livytska took an active part in the activities of the Ukrainian Women's Society in the revolutionary events of 1905-07. In 1920 she moved to [[Warsaw]], where she headed the Union of Ukrainian emigrants in Poland. At the end of the Second World War, she moved to Germany and lived in [[Karlsruhe]]. In 1957 she moved to the United States.\n\nShe died on August 16, 1971 in [[Yonkers, New York]].<ref>[http://www.svoboda-news.com/arxiv/pdf/1971/Svoboda-1971-152.pdf \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0421\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u0430\u00bb (\u0421\u0428\u0410) \u0437 \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f\u043c \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c \u041c. \u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457]</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* \"On the edge of two epochs\" (1972).<ref>[http://diasporiana.org.ua/memuari/2177-livitska-m-na-grani-dvoh-epoh/ \u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u041c. \u041d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0456 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0445 \u0435\u043f\u043e\u0445.&nbsp;\u2014 \u041d\u044c\u044e-\u0419\u043e\u0440\u043a, 1972.&nbsp;\u2014 355 \u0441.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box | title=[[First Lady of Ukraine]] | before= [[Olha Petliura]]| after= [[Melaniya Vytvytska]]| years=1926-1954}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{First Ladies of Ukraine}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Livytska, Mariya}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:First Ladies of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:19th-century educators]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian translators]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Ukrainian Orthodox Church Cemetery, South Bound Brook]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wife of the first Ukrainian president}}\n{{Infobox First Lady\n| name = Mariya Livytska <br> \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0456\u044f \u0412\u0430\u0440\u0444\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0457\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0430\n| image = \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0456\u044f_\u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0430_\u0437_\u0434\u043e\u043d\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e_\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043a\u043e\u044e.jpg\n| birth_name    = Mariya Varpholomiivna Tkachenko\n| birth_date = {{birth date|mf=yes|1879|4|9}}|\n| birth_place = [[Zhmerynka]], [[Ukraine]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1971|8|16|1879|4|9|mf=y}}\n| death_place=[[Yonkers, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation = Former [[First Lady of Ukraine]]\n| order1= [[First Lady of Ukraine]]|\n| term_start1=1926|\n| term_end1=1954|\n| president1 = [[Andriy Livytskyi]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Olha Petliura]]|\n| successor1 = [[Melaniya Vytvytska]]|\n| alma_mater = \n| spouse = [[Andriy Livytskyi]] \n| children = [[Mykola Livytskyi]] <br>[[Hatalia Livytska-Kholodna]]\n| relations = \n}}\n'''Mariya Varpholomiivna Livytska''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'': Tkachenko; April 9, 1879 - August 16, 1971) was a [[Ukrainians|ukrainian]] writer, memoirist, and public figure. She was an Activist in the Ukrainian women's movement and headed the Union of Ukrainian Women in Poland. She was married to the president of the [[Ukrainian People's Republic]] in the exile of [[Andriy Livytskyi]]<ref>[https://blog.liga.net/user/ogorobets/article/32267 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0446\u044c \u00ab\u0417\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0456\u043b\u043b\u044f\u00bb \u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456\u0439 \u0433\u043b\u0438\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0456]</ref>.\n\nIn 1897 she graduated from the Fundukleivka Women's Gymnasium in [[Kyiv]] and worked as a private teacher in and 1898-1899), while engaging in public and party activities. She became a member of the [[Revolutionary Ukrainian Party]], the [[Ukrainian Social Democratic Labour Party]], and became acquainted with its activists [[Mykola Mikhnovsky]], [[Mykola Porsh]]. She was a member of the Kyiv student community, which included [[Dmytro Antonovych]], [[Volodymyr Vynnychenko]], Olexander Scoropis-Yoltukhivsky, [[Andriy Livytskyi]], [[Liudmyla Starytska-Cherniakhivska]], [[Maria Hrinchenko]].\n\nMaria Livytska took an active part in the activities of the Ukrainian Women's Society in the revolutionary events of 1905-07. In 1920 she moved to [[Warsaw]], where she headed the Union of Ukrainian emigrants in Poland. At the end of the Second World War, she moved to Germany and lived in [[Karlsruhe]]. In 1957 she moved to the United States.\n\nShe died on August 16, 1971 in [[Yonkers, New York]]<ref>[http://www.svoboda-news.com/arxiv/pdf/1971/Svoboda-1971-152.pdf \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0421\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u0430\u00bb (\u0421\u0428\u0410) \u0437 \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f\u043c \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c \u041c. \u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457]</ref>.\n\n==Publications==\n* \"On the edge of two epochs\" (1972)<ref>[http://diasporiana.org.ua/memuari/2177-livitska-m-na-grani-dvoh-epoh/ \u041b\u0456\u0432\u0438\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u041c. \u041d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0456 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0445 \u0435\u043f\u043e\u0445.&nbsp;\u2014 \u041d\u044c\u044e-\u0419\u043e\u0440\u043a, 1972.&nbsp;\u2014 355 \u0441.]</ref>.\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n\n{