ailway accidents in 2013]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents and incidents in Canada]]\n[[Category:Runaway train disasters]]\n[[Category:2013 industrial disasters]]\n[[Category:2013 in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Derailments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway]]\n[[Category:Explosions in Canada]]\n[[Category:July 2013 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Train and subway fires]]\n[[Category:Estrie]]\n", "text_old": "{{Very long|rps=over 100|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = Lac megantic burning.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = Police helicopter view of Lac-M\u00e9gantic, the day of the derailment\n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = Canada Quebec\n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|45|34|40|N|70|53|6|W|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = {{Start date|2013|07|06}}\n| time                = 01:15 EDT (05:15 UTC)\n| location            = [[Lac-M\u00e9gantic, Quebec]]\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = \n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = [[Canada]]\n| line                = \n| operator            = [[Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| type                = [[Derailment]] of a [[runaway train]], [[explosion]]\n| cause               = Combination of neglect, defective locomotive, poor maintenance, driver error, flawed operating procedures, weak regulatory oversight, lack of safety redundancy\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 1\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = \n| crew                = \n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 47 (42 confirmed, 5 presumed)\n| injuries            = \n| damage              = More than 30 buildings destroyed, 36 to be demolished due to contamination\n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = \n| route_map_state     = \n| route_map_name      = \n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster''' occurred in the town of [[Lac-M\u00e9gantic]], in the [[Eastern Townships]] region of [[Quebec]], Canada, at approximately 01:15 [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]],<ref name=MMA /><ref name=rc /> on July 6, 2013, when an unattended 74-car [[freight train]] carrying [[Bakken Formation]] [[crude oil]] rolled down a 1.2% grade from [[Nantes, Quebec|Nantes]] and [[derailment|derailed]] downtown, resulting in the fire and explosion of multiple [[tank car]]s. Forty-two people were confirmed dead, with five more missing and presumed dead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Search resumes in Lac-M\u00e9gantic for 5 still missing |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/07/21/montreal-lac-megantic-quebec-identifying-dead-red-zone.html |date=July 21, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref> More than 30 buildings in the town's centre, roughly half of the downtown area, were destroyed,<ref name=rc /> and all but three of the thirty-nine remaining downtown buildings had to be demolished due to petroleum contamination of the townsite.<ref name=\"ici.radio-canada.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/12/06/001-megantic-marche-ville.shtml|title=Une derni\u00e8re marche au centre-ville pour les r\u00e9sidents de Lac-M\u00e9gantic|work=Radio-Canada Estrie}}</ref> Initial newspaper reports described a {{convert|1|km|adj=on|1}} blast radius.<ref name=\"npgraphic\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/07/graphic-timeline-of-key-events-in-quebec-train-disaster/|title=Timeline of Key Events in Lac-Megantic, Quebec Train Disaster|author=Richard Johnson|date=July 8, 2013|work=National Post}}</ref>\n\nThe death toll of 47 makes it the fourth-deadliest rail accident in Canadian history,<ref name=macleans /> and the deadliest involving a [[Tank car|non-passenger train]]. It is also the deadliest rail accident since [[Canadian Confederation|Canada's confederation in 1867]]; the last Canadian rail accident to have a higher death toll was the [[St-Hilaire train disaster]] in 1864.<ref name=\"associatedpress\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\n===The route===\nThe railway passing through Lac-M\u00e9gantic was owned by the United States-based [[Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway]] (MMA). The MMA has owned and operated a former [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] (CPR) main line since January 2003, between [[Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu]], Quebec, in the west and [[Brownville Junction, Maine]], in the east.<ref name=bdnmap>{{cite web|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/07/17/news/penobscot/railroad-union-negotiating-with-montreal-maine-and-atlantic-says-one-man-train-crews-unsafe/|title=One-man train crews are unsafe, says union negotiating with Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway|work=The Bangor Daily News}}</ref>\n\nThe rail line through Lac-M\u00e9gantic and across Maine was built in the late 1880s as part of the final link in CPR's transcontinental system between [[Montreal]], Quebec, and [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], [[New Brunswick]], with the section east of Lac-M\u00e9gantic known as the [[International Railway of Maine]]. Until December 1994 the line hosted [[VIA Rail]]'s [[Atlantic (train)|''Atlantic'']] passenger train as well as CPR freight service.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} A 1970s proposal to reroute the line to bypass downtown Lac-M\u00e9gantic was never implemented because of cost.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echodefrontenac.com/tragediedelacmegantic2.asp?IdNouv=2761 |title=Le p\u00e9trole \"va\" rouler \u00e0 nouveau en ville! |author=R\u00e9mi Tremblay |date=February 20, 2014 |publisher=\u00c9cho de Frontenac |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> The rail line was owned by CPR until sold in segments in January 1995. VIA Rail discontinued passenger service on the route in December 1994 owing to the pending change in ownership as VIA regulations then prohibited its passenger trains from operating on tracks that were not owned by either of Canada's two national railway companies. The eastern half of the line between Brownville Junction and Saint John was sold to the industrial conglomerate [[J.&nbsp;D. Irving]], which established two subsidiaries: the [[Eastern Maine Railway (1995)|Eastern Maine Railway]] and [[New Brunswick Southern Railway]]. The western half of the line between Brownville Junction toward Montreal was sold to [[Iron Road Railways]], a U.S.-based company, which established a subsidiary called [[Canadian American Railroad]].\n\nIron Road Railways filed for bankruptcy for its subsidiary company in fall 2002. The former CPR main line from Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu to Brownville Junction was sold to [[Rail World|Rail World Inc.]] in January 2003. Rail World formed the MMA as a subsidiary and engaged in aggressive cost cutting<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.bangordailynews.com/2003/03/14/rail-chief-discusses-impact-of-gnp-paper-mills-problems-forced-layoffs-wage-cuts-by-mma/ |title=Rail chief discusses impact of GNP: Paper mill's problems forced layoffs, wage cuts by MM&A |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |date=March 14, 2003 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/11/lac_megantic_railways_history_of_costcutting.html |title=Lac Megantic: Railway's history of cost-cutting |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref> for freight train operations and continued to defer maintenance on the tracks to the point where much of the track is now in marginal condition.<ref>In [http://www.echodefrontenac.com/tragediedelacmegantic2.asp?IdNouv=2814 Le futur propri\u00e9taire de MMA veut maintenir un lien de confiance], R\u00e9mi Tremblay, L'Echo de Frontenac (March 20, 2014), the subsequent owner of the [[Central Maine and Quebec Railway]] estimates at $10\u201320 million dollars the investment required over three years to repair the damaged track.</ref>\n\n[[Transport Canada]] permits a railway to remain in service with as few as five solid [[railroad tie|ties]] and fourteen damaged ties in a {{convert|39|ft|m}} section of track,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/railsafety/rules-tce54-835.htm |title=Rail Safety Rules - Subpart D - Track Structure |publisher=Transport Canada |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref> provided trains are limited to {{convert|10|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} on straight flat track.<ref>{{cite news|author=Les Perreaux |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/journey-to-the-end-of-the-line/article13467471/?page=all |title=Journey to the end of the MM&A Railway line |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=July 27, 2013 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref> MMA failed to take advantage of millions of dollars of available federal/provincial 2:1 matching infrastructure grants under a 2007 program as track conditions on the MMA line in Quebec continued to deteriorate. By 2013, speed reductions were required on 23 portions of the line, including a {{convert|5|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} limit at Sherbrooke yard and {{convert|10|mph|km/h}} on an {{convert|11|mi|km}} stretch east of Magog.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kim Mackrael |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/mma-issued-warnings-to-operators-to-slow-down/article13592387/ |title=MM&A issued warnings to operators to slow down due to track conditions |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===The train===\nThe freight train, designated \"MMA 2\", was {{convert|4701|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and weighed {{convert|10287|MT}}.<ref name=tsb0813 /><ref name=tsb0913 /> The train was composed of\n\nMMA [[GE C30-7|C30-7]] #5017,\n\nOne remote-control \"VB\" car (a former [[caboose]]) used to house the [[Locotrol]] equipment necessary for MMA's single-engineer train operation,\n\nMMA C30-7 #5026,\n\nCITX [[EMD SD40-2|SD40-2]] #3053,\n\nMMA C30-7 #5023,\n\nCEFX SD40-2 3166,\n\nA loaded box car used as a [[barrier vehicle|buffer car]] followed by 72 non-pressure dangerous goods [[DOT-111 tank car|DOT-111]] tank cars{{hsp}}<ref name=\"rc2\" /> loaded with petroleum crude oil (Class 3, UN 1267). Each tank car carried {{convert|113,000|L|impgal USgal}} of crude oil.<ref name=\"thegazette5\" /><ref name=\"stuff\" /><ref name=\"G&M20130714\">{{cite news | title=The equation of a disaster: what went wrong in Lac-M\u00e9gantic | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/the-equation-of-a-disaster-what-went-wrong-in-lac-megantic/article13214911 | work=The Globe & Mail | date=July 14, 2013 | accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe oil, shipped by [[World Fuel Services]] subsidiary Dakota Plains Holdings, Inc., from [[New Town, North Dakota]],<ref name=star-trib/> originated from the [[Bakken Formation]].<ref name=reuters /> The destination was the [[Irving Oil Refinery]] in [[Saint John, New Brunswick]].<ref name=reuters2 /> Shipment of the oil was contracted to Canadian Pacific Railway, which transported it on CPR tracks from North Dakota to the CPR yard in [[C\u00f4te-Saint-Luc]], a [[Montreal]] suburb.<ref name=affaires09 /><ref name=thestar3 /> CPR sub-contracted MMA to transport the oil from the CPR yard in C\u00f4te-Saint-Luc to the MMA yard in Brownville Junction. CPR also sub-contracted [[New Brunswick Southern Railway]] to transport it from the MMA yard in Brownville Junction to the final destination at the Saint John refinery. Ministry of Transport senior inspector Marc Grignon opined that \u201cWhen the shipper is based outside Canada, the importer becomes the shipper.\u201d Irving Oil Commercial G.P. is the shipper in this case.<ref name=dec17cbc>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-probe-docs-note-irving-oil-s-growing-rail-use-1.2466985|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic probe docs note Irving Oil's growing rail use|date=December 17, 2013|work=CBC News}}</ref> 3,830 rail cars of Bakken crude were shipped by 67 trains in the 9-month period preceding the derailment.<ref name=dec17cbc/>\n\nIn 2009, in the United States, 69% of the tank car fleet were [[DOT-111]]A cars. In Canada, the same car (under the designation CTC-111A) represents close to 80% of the fleet.<ref name=cbc5/> The [[National Transportation Safety Board]] noted that the cars \"have a high incidence of tank failures during accidents\",<ref name=ntsb /> citing in 2009 their \"inadequate design\" as a factor in a fatal rail collision outside [[Rockford, Illinois]].<ref name=ph-obamadelay>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/Obama-administration-delays-oil-train-safety-rules.html?pagenum=full |title=Obama administration delays oil train safety rules |newspaper=Portland Press Herald |accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref> Even before the Lac-M\u00e9gantic accident, attempts were made to require redesign or replacement of existing cars in the U.S.; these were delayed amidst fierce lobbying from rail and petroleum industry groups concerned about the cost.<ref name=ph-obamadelay/> Since 2011, the [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]] has required tank cars with a thicker shell, though older models are still allowed to operate.<ref name=lapresse3 />\n\nFreight trains operated by MMA were allowed (not \"permitted\", see below) by regulators in Canada ([[Transport Canada]]) and the [[United States]] ([[Federal Railroad Administration]]) to have Single Person Train Operation ([[One-man operation|SPTO, alternately OPTO]]) status (1 operator). The \"permit\" process, which requires public input, was not followed. The Canadian regulator and the MMA entered into a negotiation process at the culmination of which, sometime before the second week of July 2012, the government allowed MMA to reduce their manpower to SPTO. An average of 80 tankcars per train was carried on this route<ref name=dec17cbc/> under the supervision of one person only. The Maine regulator had already allowed SPTO status before the first week of April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/08/08/business/in-the-wake-of-bankruptcy-keeping-maines-rail-network-intact-strategically-critical/?ref=inline|title=In the wake of bankruptcy, keeping Maine's rail network intact 'strategically critical'|work=The Bangor Daily News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2013/08/09/business/owner-of-mma-railway-says-maine-is-not-a-growth-state/|title=Owner of MMA railway says 'Maine is not a growth state'|work=The Bangor Daily News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/07/17/news/penobscot/railroad-union-negotiating-with-montreal-maine-and-atlantic-says-one-man-train-crews-unsafe/?ref=relatedBox|title=One-man train crews are unsafe, says union negotiating with Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway|work=The Bangor Daily News}}</ref> The use of SPTO for MMA freight trains was a cost-cutting move for which the railway company has received much criticism. In May 2010, former MMA engineer Jarod Briggs of [[Millinocket, Maine]] explained to the ''[[Bangor Daily News]]'' that \u201cso much could happen in a 12-hour shift on one of these trains, such as a washed-out track, downed trees or mechanical failure. What if the engineer onboard were to encounter a medical problem? Who is going to know about it? If there is a fire engine or an ambulance needing to get by a train or a crossing when that happens, it could take hours.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last=Sambides |first=Nick |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2010/05/28/news/mma-railway-using-remote-control/ |title=MMA Railway using remote control \u2014 Penobscot |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Briggs left MMA to work for another railway in 2007; while he described the lone crew member involved in the Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment as \"a very good engineer, one of the better on the property\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323740804578599961742685072 |title=Union Defends Quebec Train Engineer's Safety Record |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> he has long expressed safety concerns about the company's overall train operations because \u201cif you have two people watching you can catch a mistake. It was all about cutting, cutting, cutting.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/07/13/lacmgantic_became_an_episode_of_breaking_bad.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic became an episode of Breaking Bad |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=July 13, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Transportation Safety Board of Canada]] (TSB) looked at whether single-person train operations played a role in the accident. After looking at the circumstances that night, the investigation was not able to conclude whether having another crew member would have prevented the accident.<ref name=TSB_Summary />\n\nAir brakes on the train are supplied with air from a compressor on each locomotive. When a locomotive is shut off, the compressor no longer supplies the brake system with air. An air brake pipe connects to each car and locomotive on the train. When air leaks from the various components, the air pressure drops. If the system is not recharged with air, the locomotive air brakes will become ineffective and provide no braking force. When the air brake control valves sense a drop in pressure in the brake pipe, they are designed to activate the brakes on each car. However, if the rate of leakage is slow and steady, the automatic brakes may not be applied as in the case of the Lac-M\u00e9gantic accident.<ref name=TSB_Summary /> However, it is the usual practice for an engineer parking a train, once the train is stopped, to apply the brakes on the cars in the train by releasing air from the train line, and allowing the air in the cars' reservoirs to apply the cars' brakes. Therefore, it would not matter if the automatic brakes applied themselves or not, as the car brakes would already be in the applied position. The train had locomotives that could automatically restart the air-brake system in the event of a brake failure, provided that these locomotives were not shut down as they would be. Also, the TSB found that the \u201creset safety control\u201d on the lead locomotive was not wired to set the entire train's brakes in the event of an engine failure.<ref name=\"G&M20129764\">{{cite news|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment: Anatomy of a disaster|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/lac-megantic-derailment-anatomy-of-a-disaster/article20129764 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=August 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"G&M20110506\">{{cite news|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic report: 18 things that went wrong|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/lac-megantic-report-18-things-that-went-wrong/article20110506/?from=20129764|newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to air brake systems, all locomotives and rail cars are equipped with at least one hand brake. This is a mechanical device that applies brake shoes to the wheels to prevent them from moving. The effectiveness of hand brakes depends on several factors, including their age, their maintained condition, their application in conjunction with air brakes, and the force exerted by the person applying the brake, which can vary widely. The TSB estimated that somewhere between 17 and 26 hand brakes would have been needed to secure the train. Had there been a two-man crew, they would have been able to perform a stabilization test, by releasing  all air brakes  and ensuring just the hand brakes would hold the train. Since there was only a one-man crew this test was not possible.<ref name=TSB_Summary />\n\n==Chronology==\n\n===Eight months before the derailment===\n\nIn October 2012, the lead locomotive, a [[GE C30-7]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Canadian police seek to block sale of ill-fated MM&A locomotive | website=Railway Age | date=2014-07-24 | url=https://www.railwayage.com/news/canadian-police-seek-to-block-sale-of-ill-fated-mma-locomotive/ }}</ref> #5017 was sent to MMA's repair shop following an engine failure. Because of the time and cost for a standard repair and the pressure to return the locomotive to service, the engine was repaired with an [[epoxy]]-like material that lacked the required strength and durability. This material failed in service, leading to [[Compressor stall|engine surges]] and excessive black and white smoke. Eventually, oil began to accumulate in the body of the turbocharger, where it overheated and caught fire on the night of the derailment.<ref name=TSB_Summary />\n\n===Events shortly before the derailment===\nThe freight train \"MMA 2\" departed the CPR yard in [[C\u00f4te-Saint-Luc]]<ref name=affaires09 /><ref name=rtl /> early in the day of July 5 and changed crews at the MMA yard in [[Farnham, Quebec|Farnham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/07/07/quebec-lac-megantic-questions-raised-environmental-safety-concerns.html|title=Leaking oil from Lac-M\u00e9gantic disaster affects nearby towns; Critics ask why trains are carrying oil through populated areas|author=CBC|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013|author-link=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> After departing Farnham, it stopped at about 23:00 at the designated MMA crew change point in [[Nantes, Quebec|Nantes]], which is {{convert|11|km}} west of Lac-M\u00e9gantic.\n\nThe engineer, Tom Harding, parked the train on the main line by setting the brakes and followed standard procedure by shutting down four of the five locomotives.<ref name=thestar2 /> Harding, who was the lone crew member under the MMA's work rules, which had been discussed with [[Transport Canada]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.trains.com/trn/b/fred-frailey/archive/2013/07/13/the-wages-of-lac-megantic.aspx|title=The wages of Lac Megantic|author=Fred W. Frailey|publisher=Trains Magazine Online|date=July 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=August 2013}} could not park the train on the adjacent [[Siding (rail)|siding]] because MMA used it routinely to store empty boxcars for [[Tafisa Canada|Tafisa]], a particleboard factory in Lac-M\u00e9gantic's industrial park.<ref name=np-jul12>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/12/lac-megantic-may-well-be-the-most-devastating-rail-accident-in-canadian-history/ |title=Lac M\u00e9gantic 'may well be the most devastating rail accident in Canadian history'|newspaper=National Post |date=July 12, 2013 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=MM&A regularly left loaded trains unsupervised, using siding track for storage| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/mma-regularly-left-loaded-trains-unsupervised-on-main-track/article13411395 | work=The Globe and Mail| date=July 24, 2013| accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref> The Nantes siding has a [[derail (railroad)|derail]] that could have stopped the train from accidentally departing.<ref name=devoir1/> According to Transport Canada, it is unusual to leave an unattended train parked on a main line,<ref name=devoir2/> but there were no regulations against it.<ref name=tsbackgrounder>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/29/lacmegantic_train_explosion_a_regulatory_failure.html|title=Lac-Megantic train explosion: a regulatory failure?|work=Toronto Star|date=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHarding left the lead locomotive No.&nbsp;5017 running to keep air pressure supplied to the train's air brakes and also applied a number of hand brakes.<ref name=jm-engineer/> Yves Bourdon, a member of MMA's board of directors, stated that the air brakes of all locomotives and freight cars had been activated, as well as hand brakes on 5 locomotives and 10 of the 72 freight cars.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la compagnie \u00e9voque le syst\u00e8me de freinage \u00e0 air|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/07/07/007-hypothese-accident-megantic.shtml|work=Radio Canada |language=French |date=July 7, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref> However, the TSB agrees with a July 6 statement to police by the train's engineer that he set hand brakes on just the five locomotive engines, a buffer car, and a car housing the remote control apparatus.<ref name=TSB_Summary>{{cite news|url=http://www.tsb.gc.ca/eng/rapports-reports/rail/2013/r13d0054/r13d0054-r-es.asp |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic runaway train and derailment investigation summary |publisher=Transportation Safety Board of Canada |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc7brakes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-unsealed-documents-say-train-engineer-didn-t-follow-mm-a-rules-1.2675443 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic unsealed documents say train engineer didn't follow MM&A rules |publisher=CBC Montreal |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> The engineer also attempted a brake test but incorrectly left the locomotive air brakes on; this gave the false impression that the hand brakes alone would hold the train.<ref name=TSB_Summary />\n\nHarding contacted the rail traffic controller in Farnham to advise them that the train was secure. Next, he contacted the rail traffic controller in Bangor, Maine, to report that the lead locomotive had experienced mechanical difficulties throughout the trip and that excessive black and white smoke was coming from its smoke stack. Expecting the smoke to settle, they agreed to deal with the situation the following morning.<ref name=TSB_Summary />\n\nSection 112 of the [[Canadian Rail Operating Rules]] states \"when equipment is left at any point a sufficient number of hand brakes must be applied to prevent it from moving\" and \"the effectiveness of the hand brakes must be tested\u201d before relying on their retarding force.<ref name=gazette-runaway/> The engineer tests the hand brakes by seeing if the train budges when trying to push and pull the train with locomotive power.<ref name=G&M20130714 /> If a train is left on an incline, the number of handbrakes needed to hold the train increases. It takes 2\u20133 minutes per car to set the hand brakes.<ref name=G&M20130714 /> The track from Nantes to Lac-M\u00e9gantic is downhill on a 1.2% grade.<ref name=thegazette5 /> Nantes is {{convert|515|m}} above sea level, Lac M\u00e9gantic is {{convert|108|m|abbr=on}} lower at {{convert|407|m|abbr=on}}. The MMA claimed that its braking policy required the activation of hand brakes on the five locomotives and 11 freight cars, or 20.5% of the total train.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quebec crash puts hand brakes on rail cars under scrutiny |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/quebec-crash-puts-hand-brakes-on-rail-cars-under-scrutiny/article13133227 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> However, the TSB confirmed evidence in the criminal charges citing MMA procedures requiring nine brakes to hold a 70\u201379 car train.<ref name=TSB_Summary /><ref name=\"cbc7brakes\"/> The TSB concluded that a minimum of 17 and possibly as many as 26 hand brakes would have been needed to secure the train, depending on the amount of force with which they had been applied.<ref name=TSB_Summary /> Transport Canada does not validate the special instructions of a railway company or give any specific guidance on how many brakes must be applied for parked freight trains.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/07/19/lac-megantic-train-derailment-victims-tsb.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic investigators seek urgent rail safety review |publisher=[[CBM-FM|CBC Montreal]] |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> While Transport Canada had repeatedly reprimanded MMA from 2004 to 2009 and in 2011 and 2012 for violations of CROR Section 112 handbrake requirements on parked trains in Nantes, no fines had been issued for the infractions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2014/02/12/002-mma-infractions-sanctions-reglements-transports-canada.shtml |title=MMA et la r\u00e8gle 112 : des infractions \u00e0 r\u00e9p\u00e9tition, aucune sanction |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=February 12, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe TSB found that MMA's operating plan was to leave the train parked on the main line, unattended, with an unlocked locomotive cab, alongside a public highway where it was accessible to the general public, with no additional protection.<ref name=TSB20130719A >{{cite web| title=Safety advisory letter to Transport Canada on the securement of unattended locomotives, July 19, 2013| url=http://www.tsb.gc.ca/eng/medias-media/sur-safe/letter/rail/2013/r13d0054/r13d0054-617-08-13.asp |work=Transportation Safety Board| date=July 19, 2013| accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> However, there were no rules against leaving a train unlocked, running and unattended, even if it contained dangerous materials and was stopped on the main line, on a slope, in the vicinity of a residential area.<ref name=wfp-unattended>{{cite news|last=Cheadle |first=Bruce |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/no-rules-against-leaving-unattended-trains-on-main-tracks-transport-canada-214807051.html |title=No rules against leaving unattended trains on main tracks: Transport Canada |newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press |date=April 16, 2010 |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing his work, Harding departed by taxi for a local hotel, l'Eau Berge in downtown Lac-M\u00e9gantic,<ref name=thestar7/> for the night.<ref name=thegazette4 /> En route, the engineer told the taxi driver that he felt unsafe leaving a locomotive running while it was spitting oil and thick, black smoke. He said he wanted to call the U.S. office of MMA (in [[Hermon, Maine]]) as they would be able to give him other directives.<ref name=journaldemontreal130708 /> Taxi driver Andr\u00e9 Turcotte described the engineer as covered in droplets of oil, which also covered the taxi's windscreen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/06/13/010-lac-megantic-conducteur-regles-pas-respectees-mma.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : le conducteur n'aurait pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles de la MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=May 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Trajectory of runaway train from Nantes to Lac-Megantic.png|thumb|left|The train traveled {{convert|11|km}} down a descending grade from Nantes to Lac-M\u00e9gantic.]]\n\nWitnesses recall seeing the train seemingly unattended and in distress around 22:45 that night.<ref name=quatrevingtdixhuit01 /> People driving on the road that parallels the rail line near Nantes recall seeing the train and having to slow down as they passed the locomotives where there was a thick dark blue cloud of diesel smoke being emitted as well as sparks coming out of a locomotive's exhaust,<ref name=quatrevingtdixhuit01 /> due to a broken piston in its [[diesel engine]].<ref name=UPI>{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2013/09/13/Broken-piston-led-to-trains-crash-into-Canadian-town-probe-finds/UPI-38411379090810/ |title=Broken piston led to train's crash into Canadian town, probe finds |publisher=UPI.com |date=September 13, 2013 |accessdate=September 14, 2013}}</ref> According to the TSB, the MMA's [[rail traffic controller]] was warned of the train having technical difficulties while the train was still in Nantes<!-- what technical difficulties and sufficiently early for what? --> on the evening of Friday, July 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la lumi\u00e8re se fait lentement |url=https://www.ledevoir.com/societe/actualites-en-societe/382609/lac-megantic-la-lumiere-se-fait-lentement |work=Le Devoir|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref> After the engineer had departed, the Nantes Fire Department as well as a police officer from the [[S\u00fbret\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]]'s Lac-M\u00e9gantic detachment responded to a 911 call from a citizen at 23:50 who reported a fire on the first locomotive;<ref name=tsb0813 /> according to Nantes Fire Chief Patrick Lambert, \"We shut down the engine before fighting the fire. Our protocol calls for us to shut down an engine because it is the only way to stop the fuel from circulating into the fire.\"<ref name=thestar6/> The fire department extinguished the blaze and notified the [[Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway]]'s [[rail traffic controller]] in Farnham. MMA did not grant permission to the engineer to return to the scene, instead summoning a track maintenance foreman unfamiliar with the operation of railway air brakes.<ref name=\"cbc7brakes\"/> By 00:13 two MMA track maintenance employees had arrived from Lac-M\u00e9gantic; the Nantes firefighters left the scene as the MMA employees confirmed to the police officer and to the Farnham rail traffic controller that the train was safe.<ref name=oc-nantes-fd/>\n\nThe MMA has alleged that the lead locomotive was tampered with after Harding had left; that the diesel engine was shut down, thereby disabling the compressor powering the air brakes, which allowed the train to roll downhill from Nantes into Lac-M\u00e9gantic once the air pressure dropped in the reservoirs on the cars.<ref name=thestar2 /> [[Teamsters Canada]] Rail Conference vice-president Doug Finnson disputed this theory, stating that the key braking system on a stopped, unsupervised train are the hand brakes, which are completely independent from the motor-powered compressor that feeds the air brakes.<ref name=ccot>{{cite news |language=French |last=C\u00f4t\u00e9 |first=Charles |title=Cause du d\u00e9sastre: le pr\u00e9sident de MMA contredit cat\u00e9goriquement |trans-title=MMA President Utterly Contradicted on Disaster's Causes |url= http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/09/01-4669054-cause-du-desastre-le-president-de-mma-contredit-categoriquement.php |newspaper=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]] |accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Derailment and explosion===\n[[File:Lac megantic affected area.png|thumbnail|Area affected by the fires]]\nWith all the locomotives shut down, the air compressor no longer supplied air to the air brake system. As air leaked from the brake system, the main air reservoirs were slowly depleted, gradually reducing the effectiveness of the locomotive air brakes. At 00:56, the air pressure had dropped to a point at which the combination of locomotive air brakes and hand brakes could no longer hold the train, and it began to roll downhill toward Lac-M\u00e9gantic, just over seven miles away.<ref name=TSB_Summary /><ref name=rc3 /> A witness recalled watching the train moving slowly toward Lac-M\u00e9gantic without the locomotive lights on.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reuters|title=Lac Megantic explosion: Fire was doused on train and engine shut down before it smashed into Quebec town: Witness describes train moving shortly after fire crew left and shut off an engine |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/08/fire_was_doused_on_train_and_engine_shut_down_before_it_smashes_into_quebec_town.html |newspaper=Toronto Star|date=July 8, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref> The track was not equipped with [[track circuit]]s to alert the [[rail traffic controller]] to the presence of a runaway train.<ref name=np-jul12/> About ten minutes before the derailment occurred, firefighter Jean-Luc Montminy who was heading home after helping put out the fire on the original locomotive of the train, was stopped at a grade crossing located on Quebec Route 161, located just south-east of where the train began to roll. He stated that the crossing had activated and was warning of an oncoming train, but after waiting for some time, he heard no horn or any signal that a train was approaching. Thinking that the crossing was malfunctioning, he proceeded over the intersection when just as he had finished crossing, a train without its headlights or horn passed through at a very fast speed. Montminy recognized that it was the same train he had responded to hours earlier, and quickly returned to Nantes to inform other firefighters about what he had just witnessed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/jean-montminy-ghost-train-lac-megantic-trial-1.4397744 |title=Firefighter watched ghost train barrel past him moments before Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment |date=Nov 10, 2017 |newspaper=cbc.ca}}</ref> Gathering momentum on the long downhill slope, the train entered the town of Lac-M\u00e9gantic at high speed.<ref name=bbc /><ref name=thestar2 /><ref name=NationalPost>{{cite web|title=Police launch 'unprecedented criminal investigation' into Lac-M\u00e9gantic train disaster|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/09/police-launch-unprecedented-criminal-investigation-into-lac-megantic-train-disaster/|work=National Post|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref> The TSB's final report concluded that the train was travelling at {{convert|105|km/h}}, more than triple the typical speed for that location.<ref name=\"G&M20129764\" /> The rail line in this area is on a curve and has a speed limit for trains of {{convert|16|km/h|sigfig=1}}<ref name=NationalPost/> as it is located at the west end of the M\u00e9gantic rail yard.\n\nJust before the derailment, witnesses recalled observing the train passing through the crossing at an excessive speed with no locomotive lights, \"infernal\" noise and sparks being emitted from the wheels.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/12/lac-megantic-may-well-be-the-most-devastating-rail-accident-in-canadian-history/ |title=Lac M\u00e9gantic 'may well be the most devastating rail accident in Canadian history' |newspaper=National Post |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref> It was also stated by witnesses that since the train was going so fast, the flashing lights or bells on the crossing signals did not activate. Gilles Fluet, a Musi-Caf\u00e9 patron who was leaving the site just before the derailment, said the wheels were smoking lots of white smoke. The runaway train passed {{convert|50|m|ft}} behind him moving at highway speed. Travelling with no signals, the train jumped the track, sending a river of burning oil into the lake.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robillard |first=Alexandre |url=http://journalmetro.com/actualites/national/340148/lincendie-a-lac-megantic-a-fait-au-moins-un-mort/ |title=L'incendie \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic a fait au moins un mort |publisher=La Presse Canadienne |via=journalmetro.com |date=2013-07-06 |language=fr}}</ref> \"It was moving at a hellish speed ... no lights, no signals, nothing at all. There was no warning. It was a black blob that came out of nowhere. I realized they were oil tankers and they were going to blow up, so I yelled that to my friends and I got out of there. If we had stayed where we were, we would have been roasted.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kjonline.com/news/Lac-Megantics-resilience-tested-after-le-train-denfer.html?pagenum=full |title=Lac-Megantic's resilience tested after 'le train d'enfer' |publisher=The Kennebec Journal, Augusta, ME Kjonline.com |date=July 14, 2013 |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe unmanned train derailed in downtown Lac-M\u00e9gantic at 01:14,<ref name=MMA /><ref name=wlbz2 /> in an area near the [[Level crossing|grade crossing]] where the rail line crosses [[Quebec Route 161|Frontenac Street]], the town's main street. This location is approximately {{convert|600|m}} northwest of the railway bridge over the [[Chaudi\u00e8re River]] and is also immediately north of the town's central business district.<ref name=MMA />\n\nPeople on the terrace at Musi-Caf\u00e9\u2014a bar located next to the centre of the explosions\u2014saw the tank cars leave the track and fled as a blanket of oil generated a ball of fire three times the height of the downtown buildings.<ref name=fryahoo1/> Between four and six explosions were reported initially<ref name=cbc /> as tank cars ruptured and crude oil escaped along the train's trajectory. Heat from the fires was felt as far as {{convert|2|km}} away.<ref name=thestar /> People jumped from the third floor of buildings in the central business district to escape the fire. As the blazing oil flowed over the ground, it entered the town's [[storm sewer]] and emerged as huge fires towering from other storm sewer drains, [[manhole]]s, and even chimneys and basements of buildings in the area.<ref name=fryahoo1>{{cite news |url=http://fr-ca.actualites.yahoo.com/important-incendie-lac-m%C3%A9gantic-063914764.html |title=Explosions et incendie \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic : un mort |publisher=Yahoo! Actualit\u00e9s Qu\u00e9bec |language=French |accessdate=July 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710012107/http://fr-ca.actualites.yahoo.com/important-incendie-lac-m%C3%A9gantic-063914764.html |archivedate=July 10, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Musi-Caf\u00e9 owner says that some employees and patrons felt the tremors of the train and thought it was an earthquake. They went out and started running. Other patrons and employees told some survivors that the tremors were an earthquake and that it would be better to stay under a table. Of those that went out, not all survived. Some were not able to outrun a \"tsunami of fire\".<ref>[http://montreal.radiox.com/?ACT=100&aRmsId=127893&aRmsContext= ''montreal.radiox.com''].</ref>\n\nThe locomotives and the VB car were found intact, separated from the rest of the train approximately {{convert|800|m|miles}} east of the derailment site.<ref>{{cite news |last=DiManno |first=Rosie |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/10/lac_megantic_explosion_controversies_and_contradictions_amid_the_despair_dimanno.html|title=Lac Megantic explosion: Controversies and contradictions amid the despair; Focus shifts to other locomotives in deadly derailment|work=Toronto Star|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> The equipment that derailed included 63 of the 72 tank cars as well as the buffer car. Nine tank cars at the rear of the train remained on the track and were pulled away from the derailment site and did not explode. Almost all of the derailed tank cars were damaged, many having large breaches. About six million litres of petroleum crude oil were quickly released; the fire began almost immediately.<ref name=TSB_Summary />\n\n===Emergency response===\n[[Image:Lac-Megantic derailment from space.jpg|thumb|Infrared image taken by [[NASA]]'s [[Suomi NPP]] satellite shows the fire that followed the derailment: on the left, taken two days before; on the right, taken about two hours after the explosions.<ref name=nasa>{{cite web|url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/view.php?id=81581 |title=Train Derailment and Fire, Lac M\u00e9gantic, Quebec : Natural Hazards |publisher=NASA Earth Observatory |date=July 4, 2013 |accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>]]\nAround 150 firefighters were deployed to the scene, described as looking like a \"war zone\".<ref name=ctv /> Some were called in from as far away as the city of [[Sherbrooke, Quebec]],<ref name=cbc /> and as many as eight trucks carrying 30 firefighters were dispatched from [[Franklin County, Maine]], United States ([[Chesterville, Maine|Chesterville]], [[Eustis, Maine|Eustis]], [[Farmington, Maine|Farmington]], [[New Vineyard, Maine|New Vineyard]], [[Phillips, Maine|Phillips]], [[Rangeley, Maine|Rangeley]] and [[Strong, Maine|Strong]]).<ref name=bdn /> The fire was contained and prevented from spreading further in the early afternoon.<ref name=thegazette4 />\n\nThe local hospital went to [[Hospital emergency codes#Mass-casualty incident .2F External Disaster|Code Orange]], anticipating a high number of casualties and requesting reinforcements from other medical centres, but they received no seriously injured patients. A [[Canadian Red Cross]] volunteer said there were \"no wounded. They're all dead\".<ref name=\"rc\" /> One off-duty Musi-Caf\u00e9 cook, Bernard Th\u00e9berge, was on the terrace at the time of the derailment and was treated for second-degree burns to one arm.<ref name=cbc-cook/> The hospital was later used to shelter dozens of seniors who had been evacuated.<ref name=thestar4 /> Approximately 1,000 people were evacuated initially after the derailment, explosions, and fires. Another 1,000 people were evacuated later during the day because of toxic fumes. Some took refuge in an emergency shelter established by the Red Cross in a local high school.<ref name=thegazette2 />\n\nAccording to initial claims made by the railway, the engineer who left the train unattended went to the explosion zone and uncoupled the last 9 undamaged tank cars that were still on the tracks at the end of the derailment. After uncoupling the tank cars, he used a [[rail car mover]] to pull them away from the derailment site.<ref name=vancouversun09 /> This version of events has been disputed by Lac-M\u00e9gantic's fire chief, who indicated that a volunteer firefighter had used a rail car mover borrowed from a local factory to remove these cars from danger.<ref>{{cite news|author=Les Whittington |author2=Liam Casey GTA |author3=Jessica McDiarmid |author4=Bruce Campion-Smith |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/09/ottawa_okayed_having_only_one_engineer_on_illfated_train.html |title=Lac Megantic explosion: Ottawa approved having only one engineer on ill-fated train |newspaper=The Toronto Star |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> It was later revealed that two employees of [[Tafisa Canada|Tafisa]] (Serge Morin, Sylvain Gr\u00e9goire), a firefighter (Beno\u00eet H\u00e9on), the MMA engineer (Tom Harding) and a member of the family-owned excavation company Lafontaine and Son (Pascal Lafontaine) had worked to move 9 tank cars away from the fire. Tafisa, a local [[particleboard]] industry that moves much of its product by rail, has a rail car mover which has the capability to deactivate the brakes on the cars it tows. Morin, aided by his colleague Gr\u00e9goire, used the rail car mover to move the first 5 tank cars away from the fire. When they could not find a level crossing to move the rail car mover back to the disaster site, they used a loader to remove another 4 tank cars, 2 at a time. Because the loader lacked equipment to deactivate railcar brakes, Harding told the men to use the loader to break the air lines on cars to release the air brakes on each of these four cars.<ref>{{cite web |title=Le conducteur Harding aurait permis d'\u00e9loigner des wagons du brasier |url=https://www.ledevoir.com/environnement/actualites-sur-l-environnement/382896/le-conducteur-harding-aurait-permis-d-eloigner-des-wagons-du-brasier |work=Le Devoir |date=July 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Andy Blatchford |agency=Canadian Press |url=https://windsorstar.com/news/national/Witnesses+describe+train+driver+raced+disaster+scene/8653801/story.html |title=The frantic moment when the train driver in Lac-Megantic raced to the scene |newspaper=Windsor Star |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Lafontaine's workers hauled gravel to the site, created [[firebreak]]s and blocked manholes as burning oil spread into the town's [[storm sewer]] system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/10/01-4669313-plusieurs-travailleurs-ont-risque-leur-vie-sur-la-ligne-de-feu.php |title=Plusieurs travailleurs ont risqu\u00e9 leur vie sur la ligne de feu |author=CHRISTIANE DESJARDINS, DAVID SANTERRE et Gabrielle Duchaine |newspaper=La Presse |language=French |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter 20 hours, the centre of the fire was still inaccessible to firefighters<ref name=ctv /> and five pools of fuel were still burning. A special fire-retardant foam was brought from an [[Ultramar]] refinery in [[L\u00e9vis, Quebec|L\u00e9vis]], aiding progress by firefighters on the Saturday night.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/07/we-know-there-will-be-more-deaths-death-toll-climbs-to-three-in-quebec-train-explosion/ |title=Lac Megantic, Que. train crash: Death toll climbs to five |newspaper=National Post |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Five of the unexploded cars were doused with high-pressure water to prevent further explosions,<ref name=thestar /> and two were still burning and at risk of exploding 36 hours later.<ref name=cbc2 /> The train's [[Train event recorder|event recorder]] was recovered at around 15:00 the next day<ref name=thegazette2 /> and the fire was finally extinguished in the evening, after burning for nearly two days.<ref name=bbc2/>\n\nA red zone was declared in which evacuees could not return to their homes because of the ongoing investigation.<ref name=cbc-google-redzone>{{cite web|url=https://maps.google.ca/maps/ms?msa=0&msid=209868932436080386156.0004e114da3128a934f38&ie=UTF8&t=m&ll=45.576832,-70.883703&spn=0.010514,0.019741&z=15&source=embed |title=Lac-Megantic (map with police red zone) |publisher=Google Maps |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties and damage==\nForty-two bodies were found and transported to [[Montreal]] to be identified.<ref>{{cite news|author=Justin Giovannetti, Grant Robertson And Jacquie Mcnish |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/investigators-urge-ottawa-to-make-changes-to-problematic-railway-safety-rules/article13320031/ |title=As Lac-M\u00e9gantic death toll reaches 47, safety board calls for immediate rail-safety changes |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> 39 of those were identified by investigators by late August 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/29/quebec-lac-megantic-alyssa-charest-begnoche-identified.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic victim identified as 4-year-old girl |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=August 29, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> and the 40th in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/04/09/002-identification-victimes-lac-megantic.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : une 40e victime identifi\u00e9e |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=April 9, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> Identification of additional victims became increasingly difficult after the August 1 end of the on-site search and family members were asked to provide [[DNA profiling|DNA samples]] of those missing, as well as dental records.<ref name=thestar5 /> The bodies of five presumed victims were never found.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/01/002-lac-megantic-sq-enquete-bureau-coroner.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la SQ met fin \u00e0 ses recherches |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 1, 2013 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>\"[http://coroner.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?id=149 Quebec coroner page.]\" ''Quebec Coroner page.'' July 16, 2013.</ref> It is possible that some of the missing people were vaporized by the explosions.<ref name=thegazette3 /> As two of the three local [[civil law notary|notary]] offices were destroyed by fire (and only one of the [[bank vault|document vaults]] survived the blaze), the [[will and testament|last will and testament]] of some victims of the disaster was lost.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/13/01-4670446-des-milliers-de-testaments-detruits-a-lac-megantic.php |title=Des milliers de testaments d\u00e9truits \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic |author=Philippe Teisceira-Lessard |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |date=July 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/07/19/003-voute-lac-megantic-actes-notaires.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : des milliers d'actes notari\u00e9s ont \u00e9t\u00e9 sauv\u00e9s |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt least 30 buildings were destroyed in the centre of town, including the town's library, a historic former bank, and other businesses and houses.<ref name=ctv /> 115 businesses were destroyed, displaced, or rendered inaccessible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/29/001-relocalisation-commerce-lac-megantic.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la relocalisation des commerces se fait pressante |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 29, 2013 |accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.echodefrontenac.com/Relocalisation.asp List of displaced businesses] currently open, l'Echo de Frontenac (local newspaper, en fran\u00e7ais)</ref> The Musi-Caf\u00e9 was destroyed and three of its employees are among the dead or missing.<ref name=oc /><ref name=lapresse4 /><ref name=CBC45>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/02/lac-megantic-residents-return-home.html |title=Popular bar, Musi-Caf\u00e9, reopens after being destroyed in explosion |publisher=CBC News |date=August 2, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref> While the town intends to build new infrastructure and commercial space, many of the historic buildings lost are irreplaceable.\n{{quote|\u201cWe will rebuild our town. But at the same time, we have to accept that it won\u2019t be the one we knew. Very old buildings, heritage and architecture all disappeared and at the beginning, no one realized the magnitude and now we are starting to understand the consequences.\u201d|[[Colette Roy-Laroche]], mayor of Lac-M\u00e9gantic<ref>{{cite news|last=Montgomery |first=Sue |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/M%C3%A9gantic+Colette+Laroche+more+m%C3%A8re+than+mayor/8803833/story.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic's Colette Roy-Laroche is more m\u00e8re than mayor |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]] |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nA number of businesses had to operate from temporary locations outside the downtown,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cem.crealinkmedia.ca/employeurs_detail.php?id=1 |title=Crise des entreprises de Lac-M\u00e9gantic &ndash; Employeurs (list of relocated businesses) |publisher=Cellule \u00e9conomique M\u00e9gantic |date=July 2013 |language=French |accessdate=August 1, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728043054/http://cem.crealinkmedia.ca/employeurs_detail.php?id=1 |archivedate=July 28, 2013}}</ref> with reduced facilities<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/29/01-4674955-les-commercants-de-lac-megantic-sinquietent.php |title=Les commer\u00e7ants de Lac-M\u00e9gantic s'inqui\u00e8tent |author=Marie-Mich\u00e8le Sioui |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |language=French |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref> until new buildings could be constructed elsewhere, as cleanup efforts were expected to take a year or more.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/la-tribune/estrie-et-regions/201308/09/01-4678494-lactivite-commerciale-de-lac-megantic-sera-relocalisee.php |title=L'activit\u00e9 commerciale de Lac-M\u00e9gantic sera relocalis\u00e9e |author=Camille Dauphinais-Pelletier |publisher=La Tribune (Sherbrooke) |language=French |date=August 9, 2013 |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref> The municipal water supply for Lac-M\u00e9gantic was shut down on the evening of the explosion because of a leak inside the blast zone,<ref name=cbc2 /> requiring trucks carrying [[drinking water]], though the leak was repaired overnight and a precautionary [[boil-water advisory]] issued.<ref name=cbc2 /> The industrial park lost access to rail service in both directions as the line remained severed until December 2013. Claims to local insurers were estimated at $25 million for [[Intact Financial]], $18 million for [[:fr:Promutuel|Promutuel]] and $7 million for [[Desjardins Group]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201308/19/01-4681052-lac-megantic-des-annees-de-travail-pour-les-avocats.php |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: des ann\u00e9es de travail pour les avocats |author=Isabelle Ducas |newspaper=La Presse |date=August 19, 2013 |accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== List of victims ===\n<div style=\"clear:both;width:100%;\" class=\"NavFrame\">\n<div class=\"NavHead\" style=\"background:#fffaf0; text-align:center; font-size:larger;\">List of victims and their ages<ref>{{cite web | title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic \u2014 Bureau du coroner | website=coroner.gouv.qc.ca | url=http://www.coroner.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?id=149 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821232248/http://www.coroner.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?id=149 | archive-date=2013-08-21 | url-status=unfit | language=fr | access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref></div>\n<div class=\"NavContent\" style=\"text-align:left;display:none;\">\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:580px;\"\n|-\n!Name!!Age\n|-\n|{{sortname|\u00c9liane|Parenteau|nolink=1}}||93\n|-\n|{{sortname|Jimmy|Sirois|nolink=1}}||30\n|-\n|{{sortname|Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|Boutin|nolink=1}}||19\n|-\n|{{sortname|Kathy|Clusiault|nolink=1}}||24\n|-\n|{{sortname|\u00c9lodie|Turcotte|nolink=1}}||18\n|-\n|{{sortname|Yannick|Bouchard|nolink=1}}||36\n|-\n|{{sortname|Karine|Lafontaine|nolink=1}}||35\n|-\n|{{sortname|Maxime|Dubois|nolink=1}}||27\n|-\n|{{sortname|M\u00e9lissa|Roy|nolink=1}}||29\n|-\n|{{sortname|Yves|Boulet|nolink=1}}||51\n|-\n|{{sortname|Karine|Champagne|nolink=1}}||36\n|-\n|{{sortname|Ga\u00e9tan|Lafontaine|nolink=1}}||33\n|-\n|{{sortname|Joanie|Turmel|nolink=1}}||29\n|-\n|{{sortname|Roger|Paquet|nolink=1}}||61\n|-\n|{{sortname|Jo-Annie|Lapointe|nolink=1}}||20\n|-\n|{{sortname|Guy|Bolduc|nolink=1}}||43\n|-\n|{{sortname|Andr\u00e9e-Anne|S\u00e9vigny|nolink=1}}||26\n|-\n|{{sortname|Diane|Bizier|nolink=1}}||46\n|-\n|{{sortname|David|Lacroix-Beaudoin|nolink=1}}||27\n|-\n|{{sortname|St\u00e9phane|Bolduc|nolink=1}}||37\n|-\n|{{sortname|Marianne|Poulin|nolink=1}}||23\n|-\n|{{sortname|Genevi\u00e8ve|Breton|nolink=1}}||28\n|-\n|{{sortname|Mathieu|Pelletier|nolink=1}}||29\n|-\n|{{sortname|Sylvie|Charron|nolink=1}}||50\n|-\n|{{sortname|Henriette|Latulippe|nolink=1}}||61\n|-\n|{{sortname|David|Martin|nolink=1}}||36\n|-\n|{{sortname|Jean-Pierre|Roy|nolink=1}}||56\n|-\n|{{sortname|Jean-Guy|Veilleux|nolink=1}}||32\n|-\n|{{sortname|Lucie|Vadnais|nolink=1}}||49\n|-\n|{{sortname|Michel Junior|Guertin|nolink=1}}||33 \n|-\n|{{sortname|Natachat|Gaudreau|nolink=1}}||41\n|-\n|{{sortname|Kevin|Roy|nolink=1}}||29\n|-\n|{{sortname|\u00c9ric|P\u00e9pin-Lajeunesse||Pepin|nolink=1}}||28\n|-\n|{{sortname|Talitha Coumi|B\u00e9gnoche||Begnoche|nolink=1}}||30\n|-\n|{{sortname|St\u00e9phane|Lapierre|nolink=1}}||45\n|-\n|{{sortname|Marie-No\u00eblle|Faucher|nolink=1}}||36\n|-\n|{{sortname|Martin|Rodrigue|nolink=1}}||48\n|-\n|{{sortname|R\u00e9al|Custeau|nolink=1}}||57\n|-\n|{{sortname|Marie-S\u00e9mie|Alliance|nolink=1}}||22\n|-\n|{{sortname|Alyssa Charest|B\u00e9gnoche||Begnoche|nolink=1}}||&nbsp;&nbsp;4\n|-\n|{{sortname|Bianka Charest|B\u00e9gnoche||Begnoche|nolink=1}}||&nbsp;&nbsp;9\n|}\n</div>\n</div>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Assembl\u00e9e nationale - Drapeaux en berne-4.JPG|thumb|left|The [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec|Lieutenant Governor]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]] ordered all [[Flag of Quebec|provincial flags]] to be flown at [[half mast]] on public buildings for 7 days following the derailment.<ref>{{cite web|author=Quebec |title=Regulation respecting the flag of Qu\u00e9bec, RSQ, chap. D-12.1, r. 2, section 10 |work=Publications du Qu\u00e9bec |date=July 1, 2013 |accessdate=July 10, 2013 |url=http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=3&file=/D_12_1/D12_1R2_A.HTM#s10}}</ref>]]\n\nAll but 800 of the evacuated residents were allowed to return to their homes in the afternoon of the third day;<ref name=ctv2 /> all but 200 were able to return by the sixth day.<ref name=rc-etat-urgence>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/11/007-lac-megantic-etat-urgence-retour-secteur-cousineau.shtml |title=\u00c9tat d'urgence et retour \u00e0 la maison \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> At least twenty had no home to which to return.<ref name=rc-eglise/> Some homes had reportedly been broken into during their vacancies,<ref name=tribune-burglars/><ref name=lp-voleurs>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/11/01-4669712-lac-megantic-serie-de-vols-dans-les-maisons-desertees.php |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: s\u00e9rie de vols dans les maisons d\u00e9sert\u00e9es |author=J\u00e9r\u00f4me Gaudreau |newspaper=La Presse |language=French |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> although police deny that homes were looted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/Page-dinformation-sinistr%C3%A9s-de-Lac-M%C3%A9gantic/529692030413118 |title=Page d'information : sinistr\u00e9s de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=RCMP (Facebook) |language=French |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRail World's president and CEO [[Edward Burkhardt]] visited the town on July 10, 2013, and was heckled by residents. After the accident, the railway's safety record was called into question: over the previous decade the firm recorded a higher accident rate than the rest of the U.S. rail fleet, according to data from the Federal Railroad Administration. In the previous year, the railroad had 36.1 accidents per million miles travelled, in comparison to a national average of 14.6 accidents.<ref>{{cite news|author=David Willis |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-23264397 |title=Lac-Megantic disaster: Engineer blamed for Canada blast, July 10, 2013 |work=BBC News |accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://safetydata.fra.dot.gov/officeofsafety/publicsite/Query/statsSas.aspx |title=1.01 Accident/Incident Overview |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration: Office of Safety Analysis |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref><ref group=nb>Data is derived from a comparison of two reports&mdash;one for all railroads and one for the individual railroad. Data is for incidents occurring in the United States only.</ref> Burkhardt's historical involvement with a [[Weyauwega, Wisconsin derailment|1996 derailment on the Wisconsin Central]] in which hazardous materials burned for over two weeks also drew renewed scrutiny.<ref>{{cite news|author=Karl Plume, P.J. Huffstutter And Ernest Scheyder |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/lac-megantic-train-disaster-a-dark-turn-for-rail-veteran/article13333361/?page=all |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic train disaster a dark turn for rail veteran |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=July 21, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref> While the actual cause of the disaster was still under provincial ([[S\u00fbret\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]]) and federal ([[Transportation Safety Board of Canada|Transportation Safety Board]]) investigation, Burkhardt announced the railway had suspended the engineer for allegedly improperly setting the handbrakes on the rail cars.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lac Megantic explosion: MMA railway boss Ed Burkhardt: 'I'm devastated' |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/10/lac_megantic_explosion_mma_railway_boss_ed_burkhardt_tours_town.html |work=The Toronto Star|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref> The engineer was made unavailable at the suggestion of his lawyer<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/07/16/lac-megantic-train-disaster-mma-burkhardt-employee-safety.html |title=Train engineer in Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment is 'very down' |publisher=CBC News |date=July 16, 2013 |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> and MMA instructed its employees not to answer questions from police without first consulting the company's lawyers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/19/01-4672460-les-employes-de-la-mma-sommes-de-se-taire.php |title=Les employ\u00e9s de la MMA somm\u00e9s de se taire |author=Hugo Pilon-Larose |newspaper=La Presse |language=French |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> A former colleague established an [[Albany, New York|Albany]]-based [[legal defence fund]] for the engineer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/website-launched-to-support-lac-m%C3%A9gantic-train-engineer-1.1958475 |title=Website launched to support Lac-M\u00e9gantic train engineer |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=October 10, 2013 |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/10/09/lac_megantic_website_launched_to_help_rail_engineer_pay_legal_fees.html |title=Lac Megantic: Website launched to help rail engineer pay legal fees |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=October 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref> The S\u00fbret\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec raided MMA offices in Farnham on July 25 as part of a criminal investigation into the Lac-M\u00e9gantic fatalities;<ref>{{cite news|last=Muise |first=Monique |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/montreal/LacM%C3%A9gantic+investigation+raiding+offices+Farnham/8707266/story.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic investigation: SQ raids MMA offices in Farnham |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |date=July 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref> the Transportation Safety Board conducted its own search backed by RCMP on August 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/08/01/005-transports-canada-grc-bureaux-mma-farnham.shtml |title=Transports Canada et la GRC dans les bureaux de la MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 1, 2013 |accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRaymond Lafontaine, a local contractor who lost a son, two daughters-in-law and an employee,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/11/town-rallies-around-local-businessman-vowing-to-make-sure-crude-never-passes-through-ravaged-lac-megantic-again/ |title=Raymond Lafontaine vowing to make sure crude never passes through Lac-M\u00e9gantic again |newspaper=National Post |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> raised concerns about the poor condition of MMA-owned track and about the increasing quantity of dangerous goods being transported through downtown areas by rail, not only in Lac-M\u00e9gantic but in cities such as Sherbrooke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/07/survivors_of_lacmegantic_explosion_devastated_enraged.html |title=Survivors of Lac-Megantic explosion devastated, enraged |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref> He asked that the tracks be repaired and rerouted to bypass the town's core.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgDndRHIGQg |title=Derni\u00e8re Heure (interview with entrepreneur Raymond Lafontaine) |format=video |language=French |publisher=RDI (Radio-Canada) |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLac-M\u00e9gantic mayor [[Colette Roy-Laroche]] sought assistance from federal and provincial governments to move the trains away from the downtown,<ref name=\"tribune-plusjamais\" /> a proposal opposed by the railway due to cost,<ref name=\"gm-path\" /> and asked tourists not to abandon the region.<ref name=\"tribune-tourisme\" /> MMA announced that it intends to make future crew changes in [[Sherbrooke]] so that trains are no longer left unattended; that city's mayor [[Bernard S\u00e9vigny]] expressed concern that this merely shifts the hazard into the centre of Quebec's sixth-largest city.<ref name=\"rc4\" />\n\n===Changes to operations and procedures===\nThe two major [[Class I rail carrier|Class&nbsp;I]] Canadian railways, [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Canadian National Railway]], indicated that they would not be leaving unattended locomotives unlocked outside a terminal or yard, and that CPR tank car trains containing regulated commodities would no longer be left unattended on a main line.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2013/07/18/business-cp-cn-rules.html |title=CN and CP tighten safety rules after Lac-M\u00e9gantic disaster |publisher=CBC News |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, 2013, Burkhardt stated that MMA has no further plans to carry oil by rail.<ref name=rc-aug6>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/06/001-burkhardt-petrole-train-mma.shtml |title=Fini le p\u00e9trole dans les trains de la MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 6, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> On August 7, 2013, the company filed for bankruptcy protection in both the [[Quebec Superior Court]] in Montreal (under the [[Companies Creditors Arrangement Act]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2013/08/07/business-megantic-mma.html |title=Lac M\u00e9gantic rail disaster company MM&A files for bankruptcy |publisher=CBC News |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> and the [[United States Bankruptcy Court]] in [[Bangor, Maine]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/08/07/business/railway-involved-in-quebec-crash-that-killed-47-files-for-bankruptcy/ |title=Maine-based railway involved in Quebec crash that killed 47 files for bankruptcy |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> (under [[Chapter 11]]).<ref name=gam-mma-bankrupt>{{cite news |author=Kim Mackrael |url=http://www3.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/rail-company-involved-in-megantic-disaster-files-for-bankruptcy/article13644535/ |title=MM&A files for bankruptcy after Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808095635/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/rail-company-involved-in-megantic-disaster-files-for-bankruptcy/article13644535/ |archivedate=August 8, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn August 13, 2013, the [[Canadian Transportation Agency]] suspended the railway's Certificate of Fitness<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/publication/guide-certificates-fitness|title=Guide to Certificates of Fitness|work=Canadian Transportation Agency|date=May 6, 2008}}</ref> effective August 20 because of its failure to obtain adequate insurance coverage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/2013-r-266 |title=Order No. 2013-R-266 |publisher=Canadian Transportation Authority |accessdate=August 15, 2013|date=August 13, 2013 }}</ref> shutting down the line.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/railway-in-lac-megantic-tragedy-has-its-canadian-licence-suspended/article13726588/|title=Railway in Lac-M\u00e9gantic tragedy has its Canadian licence suspended|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=\"licencepulled\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/13/quebec-lac-megantic-disaster-mma-railway-licence-pulled-certificate-fitness-bankrupt.html|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic disaster railway can no longer operate in Canada|date=August 13, 2013|work=CBC News}}</ref> It later extended this deadline to conditionally allow operation until October 18.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Reuters |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/aug/17/quebec-rail-crash-firm-repreieve |title=Quebec rail crash firm gets reprieve |publisher=Guardian (UK) |date=August 17, 2013 |accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/montreal-maine-atlantic-s-canadian-operations-extended-again-1.1869678 |title=Montreal, Maine & Atlantic's Canadian operations extended again |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref> While the amount of [[liability insurance]] is not listed on the federal Certificate of Fitness for reasons unknown, MMA's bankruptcy petition disclosed an insurance policy valued at $25 million<ref name=cbcaug7>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2013/08/07/business-megantic-mma.html|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster company MM&A files for bankruptcy|date=August 8, 2013|work=CBC News}}</ref> and an estimated cleanup cost, which excludes damages in [[tort]], of $200 million.<ref name=cbcaug7/> MMA's Certificate of Fitness was last modified in 2005, to reflect the use of the line by [[Orford Express]] (an independently owned passenger service between Magog and Sherbrooke).<ref name=\"ctacof2005\">{{cite web|url=https://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/561-r-2005|title=Decision No. 561-R-2005|work=Canadian Transport Agency|date=September 9, 2005}}</ref> It is unclear whether notice was given of the oil-by-rail shipments which began in 2012 despite a requirement to \"notify the Agency in writing without delay if&nbsp;... the&nbsp;... operation has changed so that the liability insurance coverage may no longer be adequate.\"<ref name=\"ctacof2005\"/>\n\nIn Maine, state transportation authorities have contacted all rival freight operators in-state to establish a contingency plan; if MMA ceases operation, U.S. federal law requires a trustee keep the line operating until a buyer is found because of the MMA's status as a [[monopoly]] in many communities.<ref name=PPH071413>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/maine-economy-tied-to-rail-lines-fate_2013-07-14.html|title=Maine economy tied to rail line's fate|work=The Portland Press Herald|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref> The U.S. has no requirement that privately owned railways carry liability insurance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/Montreal-Maine--Atlantic-Railway-loses-Canadian-license-.html |title=Maine railroad in crash shut out of Canada |newspaper=Portland Press Herald |accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, 2013, the Canadian Transportation Agency ordered [[Canadian Pacific Railway|CPR]] to reinstate delivery to MMA,<ref name=globeaug22>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/cp-rail-ordered-to-reinstate-rail-car-delivery-to-embattled-mma/article13912041/|title=CP reluctantly agrees to lift embargo against MM&A|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> a move CPR (as one of multiple firms ordered by Quebec's government to pay for the costly cleanup of oil spilled by MMA at Lac-M\u00e9gantic)<ref>{{cite news|agency=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/14/quebec-lac-megantic-cleanup-cpr-canadian-pacific-railway.html |title=Quebec seeks Lac-M\u00e9gantic cleanup cash from CP Railway |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=August 14, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> considered an unacceptable safety risk.{{Citation needed|date = October 2013}} Canadian Pacific chief executive officer Hunter Harrison stated that, \"While we disagree with this order, we have taken immediate steps to comply. The CTA, as federal regulator, has satisfied itself that MMA is fit to operate and has adequate insurance to do so. We will review our legal options.\"<ref name=cprharrison>[http://www.cpr.ca/en/news-and-media/news/Pages/cta-orders-CP-to-interchange-traffic-with-MMA.aspx CPR statement on CTA order to furnish tankers to MMA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826033652/http://www.cpr.ca/en/news-and-media/news/Pages/cta-orders-CP-to-interchange-traffic-with-MMA.aspx |date=August 26, 2013}}</ref> The CTA also found that \"the balance of inconvenience clearly favours MMA as the refusal to grant the interim order would result in the virtual cessation of MMA's operations.\"<ref name=\"marowits\">{{cite web | last=Marowits | first=Ross | title=Transportation agency orders CP Rail to end embargo of cargo to MMA | website=www.vancouversun.com | date=2013-08-21 | url=https://vancouversun.com/business/Quebec+sending+bankruptcy+proceedings+railway/8820836/story.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826034434/https://vancouversun.com/business/Quebec+sending+bankruptcy+proceedings+railway/8820836/story.html | archive-date=2013-08-26 | url-status=unfit}}</ref> The CTA also held that issues regarding public safety were none of its concern.<ref name=marowits/>\n\nIn separate developments also occurring on August 22, 2013, the [[NB&M Railways|New Brunswick and Maine Railway]] company, a division of the [[J.&nbsp;D. Irving]] conglomerate, indicated its interest to acquire the troubled MMA railway,<ref name=globeaug22/> and the Canadian Transportation Agency indicated it would review insurance coverage of federally chartered railways at some point \"in the fall\".<ref name=\"thesun22aug\">{{cite web | title=Senate wants tougher rules for oil transport in wake of Lac-Megantic disaster | website=Toronto Sun | date=2013-08-22 | url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/08/22/senate-wants-tougher-rules-for-oil-transport-in-wake-of-lac-megantic-disaster}}</ref> The same day, the Quebec government hired Paul Hastings, a Quebec bankruptcy specialist firm with standing in New York State, to represent it in American proceedings.<ref name=\"marowits\" />\n\nFederal Railroad Administration administrator [[Joseph&nbsp;C. Szabo]] wrote to the MMA the following day, stating that \"I was shocked to see that you changed your operating procedures to use two-person crews on trains in Canada, but not in the United States. Because the risk associated with this accident also exists in the United States, it is my expectation that the same safety procedures will apply to your operations.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/US-railway-chief-shocked-at-Maine-companys-one-person-crews.html |title=U.S. railroad chief 'shocked' at Maine company's single-person train crews |newspaper=Portland Press Herald |date=August 22, 2013 |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 18, 2013, the MMA was again allowed to operate between Sherbrooke and Lac-M\u00e9gantic, including going through Lac-M\u00e9gantic itself, as before the derailment. However, operations within Lac-M\u00e9gantic were subject to numerous restrictions, such as a prohibition on transport of dangerous cargo; a train's manifest being released no less than four hours ahead; no parking on tracks within {{convert|4|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} of the town centre; a conductor and engineer must be on board; and a train's speed must not exceed {{convert|16|km/h|0|abbr=on}}. On that date, a test train carrying [[particle board]] from the local [[Sonae Ind\u00fastria|Tafisa]] factory to Sherbrooke rolled through the town centre. There are plans to reroute the tracks outside the town by changing the track's route between Nantes and [[Frontenac, Quebec|Frontenac]], but no time table has been set.<ref>{{cite news|last=Magder |first=Jason |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/montreal/Rail+traffic+resumes+M%C3%A9gantic/9301107/story.html|title=Rail traffic resumes in Lac-M\u00e9gantic|work=Montreal Gazette |date=December 18, 2013 |accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref> The railway's assets were sold in a January 21, 2014 [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] bankruptcy auction to [[Railroad Acquisition Holdings]], a subsidiary of [[Fortress Investment Group]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-disaster-s-mm-a-sold-to-florida-great-lakes-partners-1.2504711 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic disaster's MM&A sold to Florida Great Lakes Partners |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=January 21, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> as [[Central Maine and Quebec Railway]] ([[reporting mark]] CMQR).<ref>{{cite news|last=Richardson |first=Whit |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2014/02/14/business/new-owner-new-name-mma-to-become-the-central-maine-and-quebec-railway/ |title=New owner, new name: MMA to become the Central Maine and Quebec Railway |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |date=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> In July 2016, it was announced that all DOT-111 tank cars would be withdrawn from transporting crude oil on railways in Canada by November 1, 2016, although their use for transporting other flammable liquids will be allowed until 2025. A new design of tank car, the [[TC-117]] is the new standard.<ref name=CTV250716>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/phase-out-of-lac-megantic-rail-car-model-coming-months-ahead-of-schedule-1.3000714 |title=Phase-out of Lac-Megantic rail car model coming months ahead of schedule |publisher=Bell Media |work=CTV |accessdate=July 25, 2016|date=July 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nOn July 6, 2013, [[Premier of Quebec|Quebec Premier]] [[Pauline Marois]] surveyed the scene, expressing profound sadness in response to the devastation in Lac-M\u00e9gantic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/national/Timeline+tragedy+events+unfolded+M%C3%A9gantic/8627742/story.html |title=Timeline of a tragedy: How events unfolded in Lac M\u00e9gantic |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref> The following day, [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] offered his prayers and condolences to those affected.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/news-video/video-pm-condolences-to-train-crash-victims/article13052128/ |title=Video: Harper offers condolences to train crash victims |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=July 7, 2013|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> On July 8, 2013, [[Monarchy of Canada|Canada's monarch]], Queen [[Elizabeth II]], issued a message expressing her and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]'s \"profound sadness [over the] tragic events that have befallen the town of Lac-M\u00e9gantic\" and hope \"that in time it will be possible to rebuild both the property and the lives of those who have been affected.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://globalnews.ca/news/701760/queen-expresses-profound-sadness-over-lac-megantic-disaster/| last=The Canadian Press| title=Queen expresses profound sadness over Lac Megantic disaster| date=July 8, 2013| publisher=Global News| accessdate=July 8, 2013}}</ref> The Queen's federal representative, [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[David Johnston]], released a similar message on the same day,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=15222| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Message from the Governor General Following the Tragedy in Lac-M\u00e9gantic| date=July 8, 2013| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref> as did her provincial representative, [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Pierre Duchesne]], on July 6,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lieutenant-gouverneur.qc.ca/index-en.html| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Quebec| title=Message from the Honourable Pierre Duchesne, Lieutenant-Governor of Quebec| date=July 6, 2013| publisher=\u00c9diteur officiel du Qu\u00e9bec| accessdate=July 12, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807042335/http://lieutenant-gouverneur.qc.ca/index-en.html| archivedate=August 7, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the Queen's son, [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|his wife]] on July 9.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=15223&lan=eng| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Message from Their Royal Highnesses The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall| date=July 9, 2013| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter to Harper, U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] expressed condolences for the \"devastating loss of life\" and offered American help, if needed.<ref>{{cite news |author=CA |url=http://www.lechodemaskinonge.com/Actualit%C3%A9s/2013-07-19/article-3321521/Barack-Obama-compatit-avec-LacMegantic/1 |title=Barack Obama compatit avec Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=L'\u00c9cho de Maskinong\u00e9 |language=French |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130720121027/http://www.lechodemaskinonge.com/Actualit%C3%A9s/2013-07-19/article-3321521/Barack-Obama-compatit-avec-LacMegantic/1 |archivedate=July 20, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/726993/obama-offers-u-s-help-over-lac-megantic-disaster/ |title=Obama offers U.S. help over Lac-Megantic disaster |publisher=Globalnews.ca |date=July 16, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] issued a statement expressing France's solidarity with victims and authorities.<ref>{{cite press release |language=French |author=French Republic |title=Catastrophe de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |work=Elysee Palace |date=July 7, 2013 |url=http://www.elysee.fr/communiques-de-presse/article/catastrophe-de-lac-megantic/ |accessdate=July 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130711005714/http://www.elysee.fr/communiques-de-presse/article/catastrophe-de-lac-megantic |archive-date=July 11, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Pope Francis]] sent a special apostolic blessing from the [[Vatican City|Vatican]] to those touched by the tragedy, along with his sympathy to victims, their families, and emergency workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/09/investigators-refuse-to-lay-blame-over-runaway-train-as-rail-company-and-fire-crews-dispute-cause/ |title=Lac-Megantic explosion: Speed, tankers cited as possible factors |newspaper=National Post |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref> The [[Maine Legislature]] passed a resolution on July 10 in support of the people of Lac-M\u00e9gantic;<ref>{{cite news|author=Richard Deschamps |url=http://www.cjad.com/CJADLocalNews/entry.aspx?BlogEntryID=10566610 |title=Maine legislature passes resolution in support of Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=[[CJAD]] (AM) 800 Montreal |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> speaking in [[French language|French]], House majority leader [[Seth Berry]] said \"''Aujourd'hui, nous sommes tous des citoyens de Lac-M\u00e9gantic''\"<ref>{{cite news| author=Agence QMI| url=http://www.journaldemontreal.com/2013/07/11/les-elus-du-maine-votent-une-resolution| title=Les \u00e9lus du Maine votent une r\u00e9solution| date=July 11, 2013| newspaper=Le Journal de Montr\u00e9al |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> (\"Today, we are all citizens of Lac-M\u00e9gantic\").\n\nKeith Stewart, Climate and Energy Campaign Coordinator with [[Greenpeace]] Canada, criticized [[Energy policy of Canada|Canada's energy policy]] within hours of the tragedy, saying that \"whether it's pipelines or rail, we have a safety problem in this country. This is more evidence that the federal government continues to put oil profits ahead of public safety.\"<ref name=\"greenpeace\" />\n\n==Technical investigation==\n{{Main|Technical investigation of the Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster}}\n\nThe [[Transportation Safety Board of Canada]] (TSB) launched an investigation into the accident. In its August 2014 report, the TSB identified 18 distinct causes and contributing factors, which included leaving the train unattended on a main line, failure to set enough hand brakes, the lack of a backup safety mechanism, poor maintenance on the locomotive and several failures of training and oversight.\n\n==Criminal investigation==\nThe provincial police organisation, the [[S\u00fbret\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]] (SQ), has led the recovery of the deceased in Lac-M\u00e9gantic, alongside the [[Coroner#Canada|Bureau du Coroner]] du Qu\u00e9bec.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/22/001-megantic-bilan-recherche-depouilles.shtml|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : six nouvelles victimes identifi\u00e9es|work=Radio-Canada}}</ref>\n\nThe SQ investigated the MMA railway offices in Farnham, Quebec, on July 25, with a [[Search warrant|warrant]] and planned to seize evidence about the fatal event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2013/07/25/quebec-lac-megantic-surete-du-quebec-mma-railway-offices.html|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment investigators search railway's offices|date=July 25, 2013|work=CBC News}}</ref> It is unknown{{when|date=May 2014}} whether the SQ has plans to broaden the scope of their investigation to include, for example, the broker at [[World Fuel Services]] who chose to employ deficient [[DOT-111 tank car]]s.<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/liable+M%C3%A9gantic+disaster/8775349/story.html Kovac and Sparks, in Montreal Gazette and Ottawa Citizen, August 11, 2013]</ref>\n\nOn May 12, 2014, the [[Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway]] was charged with 47 counts of criminal negligence; [[railroad engineer|engineer]] Thomas Harding, manager of train operations Jean DeMa\u00eetre and [[rail traffic controller]] Richard Labrie were arrested and appeared in Lac-M\u00e9gantic's court.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/train-conductor-company-face-charges-in-connection-with-deadly-lac-megantic-derailment-1.1818602 |title=Train conductor, company face charges in connection with deadly Lac-Megantic derailment |publisher=CTV |date=May 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-27387287 |title=BBC News - Lac-Megantic train explosion: Three charged in Quebec |work=BBC News |date=May 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> Of the 79 railcars only 7 brakes had been applied, where MMA guidelines indicate 9 as a minimum and experts advise 15 brakes should have been used for the slope the train was on. No hand brakes had been applied on 72 of the cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-unsealed-documents-say-train-engineer-didn-t-follow-mm-a-rules-1.2675443|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic unsealed documents say train engineer didn't follow MM&A rules|date=June 14, 2014|work=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Steelworkers]] union in Quebec, which represents the engineer and controller, has denounced the failure to lay charges against CEO Ed Burkhardt,<ref>[http://www.justicemetallosdurail.org/index.php/en Justice for USW Rail Workers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527215358/http://www.justicemetallosdurail.org/index.php/en |date=May 27, 2014}} (union website)</ref> and is raising funds for the legal defence of unionised workers whom it identifies as scapegoats.<ref>{{cite news|last=Muise |first=Monique |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/Union+sets+defence+fund+rail+workers+charged+M%C3%A9gantic/9878800/story.html |title=Union sets up defence fund for rail workers charged in Lac-M\u00e9gantic tragedy |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]] |date=May 26, 2014 |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe defective locomotive MMA 5017, a key piece of evidence in the criminal enquiry, inexplicably turned up at the former MMA Derby Yard in [[Milo, Maine]], as part of a collection of equipment destined to an August 2014 auction on behalf of the Bangor Savings Bank, a creditor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/08/02/001-lac-megantic-polemique-locomotive-vente-enchere-avocat-inquiet-procedures-judiciaires.shtml|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : pol\u00e9mique autour du passage en sol am\u00e9ricain de la locomotive|work=Radio-Canada}}</ref> The engine was removed from the auction in response to Sur\u00eat\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec objections.\n\nMMA's train engineer Thomas Harding, manager of train operations Jean Dema\u00eetre and railway traffic controller Richard Labrie were charged with 47 counts of criminal negligence causing death.<ref name=\"CBC_2015_06\" />\n\nOn June 22, 2015, new charges under the Canadian Railway Safety Act and the Fisheries Act \"of failing to ensure the train was properly braked before it was left unmanned for the night\" were laid against Maine & Atlantic Railway Corp (MMA)'s Dema\u00eetre, Harding, then-chief executive officer and president Robert C. Grindrod, Lynne Labont\u00e9, general manager of transportation, Kenneth Strout, director of operating practices and Mike Horan, assistant director.<ref name=\"CBC_2015_06\">{{citation |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-charges-laid-for-brake-failure-in-train-disaster-1.3122732 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: Charges laid for brake failure in train disaster: 6 people, 2 companies face new charges after 47 deaths in July 2013 derailment and explosion |work=CBC News |date=June 22, 2015 |accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> If convicted the charges carry \"a maximum fine of $50,000, a maximum jail term of six months.\"<ref name=\"CBC_2015_06\" />\n\n===Trial===\nFollowing a jury selection process that lasted three weeks, the trial of three people in connection with the disaster began on October 2, 2017. The [[railroad engineer|locomotive engineer]], [[rail traffic controller]], and [[operations manager]] were each charged with 47 counts of criminal negligence causing death and faced a sentence of life imprisonment if convicted.<ref name=Globalnews3778892>{{cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3778892/lac-megantic-criminal-negligence-trial-to-begin-monday-as-residents-seek-to-move-forward/ |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic criminal negligence trial to begin Monday, as residents seek to move forward |first=Annabelle |last=Olivier |publisher=Global News |accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref> The trial took place in [[Sherbrooke, Quebec]]. The prosecution called a total of 36 witnesses and the trial was scheduled to finish in December 2017.<ref name=Spec7588974>{{cite news |url=https://www.thespec.com/news-story/7588974-trial-underway-for-ex-railway-employees-charged-in-lac-megantic-train-disaster/ |title=Trial underway for ex-railway employees charged in Lac-Megantic train disaster |publisher=Metroland Media Group |newspaper=Hamilton Spectator |accessdate=October 3, 2017|date=October 2, 2017 }}</ref> On December 12, the defence announced that they would not be calling any witnesses as they believed the Crown had not met the necessary burden of proof. The trial was adjourned until January 3, 2018.<ref name=CTV3718419>{{cite web |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/the-three-accused-in-lac-megantic-disaster-won-t-testify-at-their-trial-1.3718419 |title=The three accused in Lac-Megantic disaster won't testify at their trial |publisher=CTV News |date=December 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}\n</ref> Jurors acquitted the three former Montreal, Maine and Atlantic (MMA) railway employees on January 19, 2018, after nine days of deliberations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-megantic-criminal-negligence-verdict-1.4474848|author=Alison Brunette|title=3 former MMA rail workers acquitted in Lac-M\u00e9gantic disaster trial|publisher=CBC News|date=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental impact==\n{{update section|date=October 2014|cat=Rail transport articles in need of updating}}\nThe city prohibited all access to the downtown (including Frontenac, Thibodeau, Durand Streets and the boulevard des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans) until June 2014 to permit a massive decontamination effort.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/628330/fermeture-centre-ville-lac-megantic |title=Le centre-ville de Lac-M\u00e9gantic ferm\u00e9 pour un an |author=Genevi\u00e8ve Proulx |publisher=ICI Estrie (Radio Canada) |date=August 20, 2013 |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> Soil decontamination was expected to take until December 2014 to complete, although the water table appeared to be uncontaminated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/01/29/001-decontamination-lac-megantic-blanchet-environnement.shtml |title=La d\u00e9contamination de Lac-M\u00e9gantic prendra encore un an |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=January 29, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> Some buildings that were still standing, such as the [[Canada Post|local post office]] in Lac-M\u00e9gantic, were a total loss due to oil contamination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/affaires/actualite-economique/201307/15/01-4671028-lac-megantic-le-service-postal-reprend-son-cours-normal.php |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: le service postal reprend son cours normal |author=Olivier Parent &#124; Actualit\u00e9 \u00e9conomique |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref> It may take up to five years to decontaminate some sites where homes formerly stood, forcing householders to rebuild elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/17/01-4671511-tout-le-centre-ville-de-lac-megantic-est-a-refaire.php |title=Tout le centre-ville de Lac-M\u00e9gantic est \u00e0 refaire |author=David Santerre |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMMA's Labrie, Dema\u00eetre, Harding, Grindrod, Labont\u00e9, Strout and Horan faced a Canadian federal Fisheries Act charge, with a potential maximum penalty of $1-million fine, for \"the crude oil that flowed into Lac-M\u00e9gantic and the Chaudi\u00e8re River after the accident.\"<ref name=\"CBC_2015_06\" />\n\n===Contamination of land===\nThe disaster site was so heavily contaminated with [[benzene]] that firefighters and investigators in the first month worked in fifteen-minute shifts due to heat and toxic conditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/07/17/quebec-lac-megantic-transportation-minister-raitt-mayors-train-mma.html |title=5 more victims identified in Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=[[CBM-FM|CBC Montreal]] |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> The waterfront at Veteran's Park and the town [[marina]] were contaminated by [[hydrocarbon]]s, which were contained by a series of booms. This rendered vessels and docks inaccessible until they can be removed from the water and decontaminated,<ref>{{cite news |author=Manon Bisson |url=http://www.cjitfm.com/decontamination-de-la-marina-de-lac-megantic/ |title=D\u00e9contamination de la marina de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=[[CJIT-FM]] |language=French |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723022216/http://www.cjitfm.com/decontamination-de-la-marina-de-lac-megantic/ |archivedate=July 23, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> a process which was to take until late August 2013 to complete.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.ville.lac-megantic.qc.ca/publications/publication/article/debut-des-operations-de-decontamination-des-embarcations/ |title=D\u00e9but des op\u00e9rations de d\u00e9contamination des embarcations |publisher=Ville Lac-M\u00e9gantic |language=French |date=August 2, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130804120133/http://www2.ville.lac-megantic.qc.ca/publications/publication/article/debut-des-operations-de-decontamination-des-embarcations/ |archivedate=August 4, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA hundred residents were not expected to return home until mid-2014{{update after|2014|07||Rail transport articles in need of updating}} as the ground beneath their still-standing houses was contaminated with oil;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/08/06/009-retour-sinistres-lac-megantic.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : pas de retour \u00e0 la maison avant un an |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 6, 2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> some homes in the most-contaminated areas might never be habitable.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2013/08/07/some-evacuees-in-lac-megantic-may-never-be-able-to-return-to-their-homes/ |title=Some evacuees in Lac-Megantic may never be able to return to their homes |magazine=Macleans |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828072211/http://www2.macleans.ca/2013/08/07/some-evacuees-in-lac-megantic-may-never-be-able-to-return-to-their-homes/ |archive-date=August 28, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBecause the cleanup of the derailment area could take 5 years, about 115 businesses were planning to relocate. 40 buildings have already been destroyed but another 160 may need to be expropriated for demolition because they sit on several metres of contaminated soil which must be removed and replaced with clean fill. Subsequent reconstruction on the site may initially be impractical as new buildings would require deeper foundations until the new fill settles. The town was considering making a memorial park in the damaged area<ref name=G&M20130729>{{cite news\n |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic businesses plan exodus amid fears downtown can't be saved\n |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/businesses-plan-exodus-from-downtown-lac-megantic/article13476014\n |work=The Globe and Mail\n |date=July 29, 2013\n |accessdate=July 29, 2013\n}}</ref> and relocating displaced businesses to a proposed Papineau Street extension to cross the Chaudi\u00e8re River to L\u00e9vis Street.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/08/08/006-lacmegantic-relocalisation-centre-ville.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la strat\u00e9gie de relocalisation des commerces d\u00e9voil\u00e9e |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 8, 2013 |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref> The new road was to be constructed in October 2013{{update after|2013|10||Rail transport articles in need of updating}} using federal and provincial infrastructure funding, although insurance coverage for local companies to abandon contaminated sites remained uncertain. For 125 businesses, the move was expected to be permanent.<ref>{{cite news|author=Justin Giovannetti |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/plan-to-reshape-lac-megantic-gathers-momentum-as-town-rebuilds-after-train-explosion/article13749551/ |title=Plan to reshape Lac-M\u00e9gantic gathers momentum as town rebuilds |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWorkers at the downtown site expressed concern that cleanup efforts were being delayed by management, leaving workers often idle on-site and allowing work to proceed only at a snail's pace.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/10/23/007-megantic-travaux-employes.shtml |title=Reconstruction de Lac-M\u00e9gantic : des travailleurs critiquent la gestion des travaux |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=October 23, 2013 |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref> The downtown was most affected; over thirty buildings destroyed by the disaster itself, with thirty-six of the thirty-nine remaining buildings slated for demolition due to contamination of the underlying soil. In December 2014, local residents were given one last chance to tour what remained of the downtown before demolition.<ref name=\"ici.radio-canada.ca\"/>\n\n===Contamination of waterways===\nThe [[Chaudi\u00e8re River]] was [[oil spill|contaminated]] by an estimated {{convert|100000|L}} of oil. The spill travelled down the river and reached the town of [[Saint-Georges, Quebec|Saint-Georges]] {{convert|80|km}} to the northeast, forcing local authorities to draw water from a nearby lake and install floating barriers to prevent contamination. Residents were asked to limit their water consumption as the lake was not able to supply the daily needs of the town.<ref name=cbc3 /> Swimming and fishing were prohibited in the Chaudi\u00e8re River, as was the use of scarce municipal water to fill swimming pools or water flower beds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/justice-et-faits-divers/201307/09/01-4669241-la-ville-de-levis-securise-lalimentation-en-eau-potable-de-50-000-residants.php |title=La Ville de L\u00e9vis s\u00e9curise l'alimentation en eau potable de 50 000 r\u00e9sidants |author=St\u00e9phanie Martin |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref> Restrictions on drawing potable water from the river remained in effect two months later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/M%C3%A9gantic+disaster+Good+test+results+from+Chaudi%C3%A8re+River/8874721/story.html |title=Chaudi\u00e8re River test results are encouraging |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]] |date=September 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> A temporary system of aboveground pipes feeding water to L\u00e9vis from the [[Beaurivage River]] was expected to cost $2 million, not including any measures to protect the line against freezing in winter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/21/quebec-levis-water-river-cost-contamination.html |title=L\u00e9vis needs clean water source before winter |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEnvironmentalists have reported heavy contamination from [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons]] and believe [[arsenic]] levels to be well above legal limits.<ref>{{cite news|author=Melanie Marquis |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/study-shows-high-pollution-at-lac-megantic-one-carcinogen-394444-times-above-limit/article13749318/ |title=Study shows high pollution at Lac-M\u00e9gantic: one carcinogen 394,444 times above limit |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Cleanup and environmental costs===\nMMA contractors responsible for removing oil and damaged rail cars from downtown Lac-M\u00e9gantic stopped work on July 17, 2013, as the railway had not paid them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/17/01-4671720-un-arret-de-travail-a-paralyse-le-nettoyage-du-site.php |title=Un arr\u00eat de travail a paralys\u00e9 le nettoyage du site |author=David Santerre |agency=La Presse Canadienne |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref> Work soon resumed under municipal (and later provincial) funding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2013/07/23/lacmegantic_residents_allowed_brief_visit_home.html |title=Lac Megantic: Mayor says town stuck with $4 million in unpaid bills for cleanup |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref> As of July 30, 2013, the municipality was demanding MMA reimburse $7.6 million in cleanup costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/30/005-lac-megantic-mairesse-securite-civile-sq.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la Ville a envoy\u00e9 une deuxi\u00e8me mise en demeure \u00e0 la MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 30, 2013 |accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> Rail World CEO Ed Burkhardt indicated \"we\u2019re unable to fund that out of our own cash, so we\u2019re waiting for the insurance company to come forward\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.northcountrypublicradio.org/news/story/22447/20130730/railway-exec-speaks-about-lac-magantic-disaster |title= Railway Exec speaks about Lac Magantic disaster |author=Brian Mann |publisher=[[North Country Public Radio]] |date=July 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProvincial environment minister [[Yves-Fran\u00e7ois Blanchet]] issued a July 29, 2013, order under the Quality of the Environment Act<ref>[http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=2&file=/Q_2/Q2.htm official French text of \"Loi sur la qualit\u00e9 de l'environnement\"] RSQ Ch. Q-2</ref> requiring MMA, Western Petroleum Company and its parent [[World Fuel Services]] pay the full cost of clean-up and damage assessment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/environnement/2013/07/29/001-blanchet-decontamination-lac-megantic.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : Qu\u00e9bec ordonne \u00e0 la MMA de remettre le site en \u00e9tat |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 29, 2013 |accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] was added on August 14<ref name=\"targetcpr\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/quebec-targets-cp-railway-for-lac-megantic-cleanup-costs/article13768911/|title=Quebec targets CP Railway for Lac-M\u00e9gantic cleanup costs|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> after World Fuel Services, as shipper of the crude oil, claimed its only contractual relationship is to the CPR with MMA (as CP's subcontractor)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Economie/2013/07/31/011-world-fuel-services-resultats-megantic-informations.shtml |title=Trag\u00e9die de Lac-M\u00e9gantic : World Fuel Services prend ses distances |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref> exercising sole control of the site.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/30/002-lac-megantic-mma-mise-demeure-reponse.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : World Fuel Services doute de la l\u00e9galit\u00e9 de l'ordonnance de Qu\u00e9bec |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 30, 2013 |accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> The claim that MMA was contracted by CP (and not WFS) was later drawn into question.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Economie/2013/08/29/012-lac-megantic-canadien-pacific-pas-sous-traitance-petrole-mma.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : le Canadien Pacifique n'aurait pas sous-trait\u00e9 le contrat \u00e0 la MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=August 29, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> Blanchet stated \u201cI will leave it up to lawyers, but let\u2019s be clear: under the law on environmental quality, the minister does not ask for, or suggest, compensation ... he orders it.\"<ref name=\"aug15g+m\"/> CP intends to appeal the order.<ref name=\"aug15g+m\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/canadian-pacific-refuses-order-to-pay-for-lac-megantic-cleanup/article13787461/|title=Canadian Pacific rejects order to pay for Lac-M\u00e9gantic cleanup|work=Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/15/lac-megantic-quebec-disaster-cp-rail-order-cleanup.html |title=CP Rail refuses to pay for Lac-M\u00e9gantic cleanup |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Politique/2013/07/31/003-megantic-ordonnace-reponse.shtml |title=Ordonnance \u00e0 la MMA : la r\u00e9ponse n'est pas satisfaisante, dit Qu\u00e9bec |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/15/lac-megantic-quebec-disaster-cp-rail-order-cleanup.html|title=CP Rail refuses to pay for Lac-M\u00e9gantic cleanup|date=August 15, 2013|work=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/08/15/quebec-demands-cp-rail-help-pay-for-multi-million-dollar-cleanup-after-tragic-train-disaster-in-lac-megantic/|title=Quebec demands CP Rail help pay for multi-million dollar cleanup after tragic train disaster in Lac-Megantic|author=Canadian Press|date=August 15, 2013|work=National Post}}</ref>\n\n==Political impact==\n<!-- This section has been split into four subsections: municipal, provincial, US and Canadian federal political impacts are treated below. -->\n\nFollowing the accident, the MMA temporarily ceased operations on its lines between Lac-M\u00e9gantic and [[Jackman, Maine]],<ref name=PPH071413/> effectively severing rail transport on its lines between Maine and Quebec, though rail traffic continued outside the affected area. In Quebec, MMA continued operation from Farnham with a skeleton staff after the derailment, having laid off 19 of its 75 workers without notice on July 19<ref>{{cite news|author=Daniel Roy |url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/17/002-mma-train-perte-emplois-farnham-19.shtml |title=La MMA fournit la preuve d'une assurance responsabilit\u00e9 |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref> and an additional five on July 30;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/30/003-mma-farnham-mises-a-pied.shtml |title=Au moins cinq autres employ\u00e9s de la MMA sont mis \u00e0 pied \u00e0 Farnham |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 30, 2013 |accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> these workers have not received severance and vacation pay owed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/07/001-mma-syndicat-metallos-employes-voles.shtml |title=Le Syndicat des M\u00e9tallos accuse la MMA de voler ses employ\u00e9s |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> In Maine, 64 MMA employees were laid off as a result of the derailment.<ref name=rc-aug6/>\n\n===Municipal reaction===\nLocal governments in various communities across Canada have expressed concern not only that railways are exempted from all local regulations (as they are under federal jurisdiction) but that information on the content of dangerous goods shipments is being deliberately, systematically withheld from municipal leaders whose duties include disaster planning and [[9-1-1]] emergency response.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ren\u00e9 Bruemmer |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/Rail+firms+keep+Montreal+officials+dark+reveal+freight/8632114/story.html |title=Rail firms keep Montreal officials in the dark, won't reveal freight details |newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]] |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.660news.com/2013/07/09/quebec-train-derailment-tragedy-raises-safety-concerns-in-alberta/ |title=Quebec train derailment tragedy raises safety concerns in Alberta |publisher=[[CFFR|660News]] Calgary |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/story/2013/07/09/mb-ste-anne-rail-lac-megantic-winnipeg.html |title=Manitoba town wants to know what rail cars are carrying |publisher=CBC News |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2013, the [[Federation of Canadian Municipalities]] rail safety working group urged the Federal government to act swiftly on rail safety. The FCM working group had three recommendations:<ref name=fcm23aug>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/story/2013/08/23/montreal-railway-safety-federation-canadian-municipalities-.html|title=Mayors urge Ottawa to act swiftly on rail safety|date=August 23, 2013|work=CBC News}}</ref>\n* Help equip and support municipal first responders, and keep them informed of the type of dangerous goods being transported by rail through their communities in order to help plan for emergencies.\n* Ensure federal and industry policies and regulations address municipalities' rail safety concerns and include those concerns in risk assessment and policy development on rail safety.\n* Solidify the regulation of third-party liability insurance for rail companies so the costs of rail disasters are not borne by local taxpayers.\n\nIn [[Montmagny, Quebec|Montmagny]], a community on the [[Canadian National|CN]] line through [[L\u00e9vis, Quebec|L\u00e9vis]], mayor Jean-Guy Desrosiers has expressed concern about the {{convert|60|mph|km/h|adj = on}} dangerous materials trains which have appeared increasingly frequently now that the former CP line through Lac-M\u00e9gantic is inoperable; neither the city nor police and fire responders are informed of the content of these shipments, leaving questions as to the readiness of the municipality to respond to further derailments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/quebec/2013/08/15/013-croissance-transport-ferroviaire.shtml |title=Forte croissance du transport par rail de mati\u00e8res dangereuses |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=August 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Magog, Quebec|Magog]] mayor Vicky May Hamm made an ''[[Access to Information Act]]'' enquiry for track inspection data, train scheduling information and products transported. The federal response acknowledged that inspections found three problematic track sections, but provided no further information.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/22/004-securite-ferroviaire-mairesse-magog-demande-acces.shtml |title=S\u00e9curit\u00e9 ferroviaire : pas facile d'avoir de l'information... m\u00eame lorsqu'on est mairesse |publisher=Radio-Canada.ca |date=August 22, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> Sherbrooke has made similar demands. While US authorities have made Maine track inspection data available quickly, the Canadian government is expected to take eight months to a year to comply with the ''Access to Information Act'' enquiries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/national/201309/17/01-4690079-ottawa-mettra-plus-dun-an-a-fournir-des-informations-sur-mma.php |title=Ottawa mettra plus d'un an \u00e0 fournir des informations sur MMA |author=Martin Croteau |newspaper=La Presse |language=French |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Brandon Sun]]'', the [[Brandon, Manitoba|Brandon]] Police Service and Brandon Fire Department indicate they are not provided dangerous goods lists by rail companies.<ref name=brandon>{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/railways-refuse-to-reveal-toxic-cargo-218196472.html|title=Railways refuse to reveal toxic cargo|work=Winnipeg Free Press}}</ref> [[C\u00f4te-Saint-Luc, Quebec]] mayor [[Anthony Housefather]] expressed concern in a recent council meeting about the lack of data: \u201cI\u2019m not the federal government, I didn\u2019t determine if the railways have an obligation to provide [the information] to the municipalities or anyone else,\u201d the mayor added. \u201cThe federal government should be doing that. I had one opportunity to get it for our city to work on our emergency measures plan and make sure that we\u2019re prepared, and I prefer to have the information than not have it.... Until such time as the federal government adopts more stringent requirements on the railways, anything we receive as information as a city comes from the sufferance of the railway, meaning we need to have a good relationship with the railway to get anything because they have no legal obligation under federal law to provide it to us,\u201d<ref name=goldenberg14aug>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesuburban.com/article.php?id=1893&title=CSL-Now-Knows-What-Is-Transported-Through-CP-Yards|title=CSL Now Knows What Is Transported Through CP Yards|author=Joel Goldenberg|date=August 14, 2013|work=The Suburban Newspaper|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130823144201/http://www.thesuburban.com/article.php?id=1893&title=CSL-Now-Knows-What-Is-Transported-Through-CP-Yards|archivedate=August 23, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Farnham, Quebec|Farnham]]'s town council passed a resolution asking that the operation of a rail line that cuts the town in two be suspended until [[Transport Canada]] conducts a full inspection of the rails; Farnham mayor Josef H\u00fcsler has also requested subsidies to move the rail yard outside the town and replace a level crossing at [[Quebec Route 104]] with an [[overpass]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/07/11/002-farnham-suspension-activites-mma.shtml |title=Farnham suspend temporairement les activit\u00e9s de MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Quebec City]] mayor [[R\u00e9gis Labeaume]] has offered that city's continued support for the reconstruction effort (the city already has emergency workers on-site)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/societe/201307/26/01-4674587-lac-megantic-quelques-demandes-pour-harper.php |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: quelques demandes pour Harper |author=Ian Bussi\u00e8res |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |language=French |date=July 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref> and called for the immediate construction of 1\u20132&nbsp;km of new track to reconnect Lac-M\u00e9gantic's industrial park to the rails, bypassing the damaged downtown. He praised local mayor Colette Roy-Laroche unequivocally while denouncing Rail World CEO Burkhardt as a \"corporate bum\" whose modus operandi of taking large dividends in profit while leaving company coffers nearly empty would allow the railway to declare bankruptcy, leaving taxpayers to foot the huge cost of rebuilding Lac-M\u00e9gantic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/la-capitale/201307/26/01-4674528-lac-megantic-labeaume-tire-a-boulets-rouges-sur-mma.php |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: Labeaume tire \u00e0 boulets rouges sur MMA |author=Ian Bussi\u00e8res |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |language=French |date=July 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/26/01-4674524-burkhardt-le-visage-le-plus-laid-du-capitalisme-selon-labeaume.php |title=Burkhardt, le \"visage le plus laid du capitalisme\", selon Labeaume |author=M\u00e9lanie Marquis |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |date=July 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref> Quebec City has also sent an expert from its [[Mus\u00e9e de la civilisation|museum of civilisation]] to identify artefacts in the wreckage which should be preserved for inclusion in a future monument, memorial park or exhibit.<ref>[http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/societe/201308/07/01-4677959-un-conservateur-du-musee-de-la-civilisation-depeche-a-lac-megantic.php Un conservateur du Mus\u00e9e de la civilisation d\u00e9p\u00each\u00e9 \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic] at ''[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]]''; by Baptiste Ricard-Ch\u00e2telain; published August 8, 2013; retrieved August 11, 2013</ref>\n\n[[Vaudreuil-Dorion]] mayor Guy Pilon has asked that municipalities be permitted to limit the speed of trains in populated areas, as homes and schools built fifty years ago near rail lines then carrying wood, grain and cereals are now endangered by high-speed hazardous goods trains.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogues.radio-canada.ca/rive-sud/2013/07/25/train-vaudreuil-dorion-pancartes/ |title=Des pancartes pour interpeller les conducteurs de train qui traversent Vaudreuil-Dorion |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Dourdan]], [[France]] mayor Olivier Leglois has offered condolences to the mayor of Lac-M\u00e9gantic<ref name=parisien-dourdan>{{cite news|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/espace-premium/essonne-91/la-ville-se-mobilise-pour-sa-jumelle-du-quebec-09-07-2013-2966165.php |title=La ville se mobilise pour sa jumelle du Qu\u00e9bec |newspaper=Le Parisien |language=French |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref> at the request of Le Ch\u00eane et l'\u00c9rable, a Dourdan local organisation supporting the [[sister city]] link between the two towns.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mairie-dourdan.fr/vie-associative-et-sportive/jumelage |title=Jumelage |publisher=City Hall, Dourdan, France |language=French |accessdate=July 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119083053/http://www.mairie-dourdan.fr/vie-associative-et-sportive/jumelage |archive-date=January 19, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While Dourdan has provided no immediate aid, its local government intends to support secondary efforts such as reconstruction of the town's library,<ref name=parisien-dourdan/> which suffered nearly two and a half million dollars in damage and is a complete loss.<ref name=\"libraryjournal1\">{{cite magazine|url=http://lj.libraryjournal.com/2013/07/industry-news/fire-destroys-canadian-library-archive/ |title=Fire Destroys Canadian Library, Archive |magazine=Library Journal |date=July 29, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> While the local archives cannot be replaced,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/dossiers/tragedie-a-lac-megantic/201307/08/01-4668818-patrimoine-detruit-a-lac-megantic-une-page-dhistoire-partie-en-fumee.php |title=Patrimoine d\u00e9truit \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic: une page d'histoire partie en fum\u00e9e |author=Caroline d'Astous |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |language=French |date=July 8, 2013 |accessdate=July 8, 2013}}</ref> various universities and local groups in Quebec have collected books for a new Biblioth\u00e8que M\u00e9gantic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/est-quebec/2013/07/18/009-livres-lac-megantic.shtml |title=Des livres pour relancer la collection de la biblioth\u00e8que de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSister city [[Farmington, Maine]] sent firefighters to fight the blaze,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailybulldog.com/db/features/selectmen-give-establish-donation-account-for-sister-city-lac-megantic/ |title=Selectmen establish donation account for sister city Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Daily Bulldog |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> raised over $6000 in local donations in the first few days after the derailment and had local officials meet with their M\u00e9ganticois counterparts to offer aid and support.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailybulldog.com/db/features/very-humbling-local-officals-visit-lac-megantic/ |title='Very humbling': Local officials visit Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Daily Bulldog |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> Both the municipality<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.town.falmouth.me.us/pages/Lac_Megantic.pdf |title=Recovery Aid for Lac-Megantic, Quebec |work=a message from the Town of Farmington to other municipalities in Maine |author=Richard P. Davis, town manager, Farmingham |publisher= |date=July 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> and the Farmington library<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wmtw.com/news/maine/maine-group-visits-devastated-lacmegantic/-/8792012/21033020/-/jqy6b/-/index.html |title=Maine group visits devastated Lac-Megantic |publisher=[[WMTW]] |date=July 18, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812034823/http://www.wmtw.com/news/maine/maine-group-visits-devastated-lacmegantic/-/8792012/21033020/-/jqy6b/-/index.html |archivedate=August 12, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> have contacted their direct counterparts in other Maine municipalities to enlist their aid.\n\n===Provincial reaction===\n\nDuring a July 11 visit Premier Marois criticized the rail company's response, while announcing a $60-million fund for survivor assistance and rebuilding.<ref>{{cite news|author=Justin Giovannetti |author2=Sean Silcoff |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/rcmp-in-lac-megantic-focus-on-remaining-oil-tankers/article13140357/ |title=As RCMP shifts focus, Marois calls rail chairman's behaviour 'deplorable' |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> Ten days later, the federal government had yet to commit to any specific aid for the stricken community, despite requests from the municipality for help to rebuild damaged infrastructure and reroute the rails outside the stricken downtown.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/07/17/lac-megantics-patience-wearing-thin-as-ottawa-fails-to-announce-any-aid-funding/ |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic's patience wearing thin as Ottawa fails to announce any aid funding after deadly rail disaster |newspaper=National Post |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring an annual premiers' conference, the Council of the Federation, provincial leaders called for stricter requirements for [[liability insurance]] for rail carriers, real-time information on content and location of dangerous goods trains for officials at all levels of government and a federally supported national emergency response program.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Politique/2013/07/26/002-conseil-federation-vendredi.shtml |title=Ottawa doit mieux surveiller le transport des mati\u00e8res dangereuses, dit le Conseil de la f\u00e9d\u00e9ration |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2013/07/24/pol-premiers-meeting-issues-list.html |title=5 hot issues at the premiers' meeting |publisher=CBC News |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe premiers of Quebec and all four Atlantic provinces, as well as all six [[New England]] governors, have called for stricter federal regulation of dangerous goods by rail in both nations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/politique/politique-canadienne/201309/09/01-4687635-transport-ferroviaire-la-pression-saccroit-sur-ottawa.php |title=Transport ferroviaire: la pression s'accro\u00eet sur Ottawa |author=Jocelyne Richer |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |date=September 9, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA 2001 Quebec law (Article 8 of the [[Loi sur la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 civile]]) for which the corresponding regulations were never enacted was cited on August 19, 2013, by [[Vision Montr\u00e9al]], a municipal political party. Under that law, a company conducting activities or holding materials which could cause a major disaster would be required to disclose these risks to municipalities, indicating the potential damage and any contingency plans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/19/005-harel-transport-train-municipalites.shtml |title=Transport de mati\u00e8res dangereuses par train : les municipalit\u00e9s doivent savoir, dit Harel |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 19, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Maine and United States===\nIn Maine, where oil-by-rail has attracted environmental protests,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.onlinesentinel.com/news/Protestors-from-350-Maine-protest-Quebec-crash-at-rail-lines-Hermon-office.html |title=Quebec train wreck spotlights oil transportation debate on national stage |publisher=The Morning Sentinel, ([[Waterville, Maine]]) |date=July 8, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> the state legislature voted 91\u201352 for a study on transportation of crude oil through the state. The proposed study was vetoed by the state's governor<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/story/2013/07/10/nb-oil-maine-train-quebec.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic train disaster shifting views in Maine |publisher=CBC News |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> and the [[Maine Department of Transportation]] (Maine DOT) has no plans to review movements of crude oil through Maine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherwood |first=Dave |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2013/07/09/us-train-maine-idUKBRE9670PU20130709 |title=Maine has no plans to halt oil rail shipments after Quebec tragedy |work=Reuters |date=July 9, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Maine governor [[Paul Lepage]] has advocated federal review of all procedures affecting rail safety on both sides of the border.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/societe/201307/27/01-4674766-lac-megantic-le-gouverneur-du-maine-en-colere.php |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: le gouverneur du Maine en col\u00e8re |author=Ian Bussi\u00e8res |publisher=La Presse (Montr\u00e9al) |language=French |date=July 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMaine's [[United States House of Representatives|US representatives]] [[Mike Michaud|Michaud]] and [[Chellie Pingree|Pingree]] proposed The Safe Freight Act, a federal bill requiring two-person crews on freight trains, and are demanding the older [[DOT-111]] design be replaced by sturdier cars for dangerous goods shipments.<ref name=\"maine23aug\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/US-railway-chief-shocked-at-Maine-companys-one-person-crews.html|title=U.S. railroad chief 'shocked' at Maine company's single-person train crews|work=Portland Press Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sambides |first=Nick |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2013/08/02/politics/michaud-pingree-submit-bill-requiring-2-person-crews-on-freight-trains |title=Michaud, Pingree submit bill requiring 2-person crews on freight trains |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |date=August 2, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Federal Railroad Administration has launched a full re-inspection of the {{convert|275|mi|km}} of the Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway's track in Maine.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/Federal-railroad-safety-inspectors-coming-to-Maine.html |title=After Quebec disaster, railroad inspectors coming to Maine |publisher=Portland Press Herald (ME) |date=July 16, 2013 |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> A committee of local mayors representing the Quebec municipalities along the line ([[Sutton, Quebec|Sutton]], [[Magog, Quebec|Magog]], [[Sherbrooke]], [[Farnham, Quebec|Farnham]], [[Lac-M\u00e9gantic, Quebec|Lac-M\u00e9gantic]], [[Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu]] and [[Cowansville, Quebec|Cowansville]]) have called for a similar investigation by the [[government of Canada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/07/17/001-raitt-visite-lac-megantic.shtml |title=L'UMQ a remis un dipl\u00f4me du courage \u00e0 la mairesse de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref> The FRA also established an \"Emergency Order establishing additional requirements for attendance and securement of certain freight trains and vehicles on mainline track or mainline siding outside of a yard or terminal\" on August 2, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Emergency Order Establishing Additional Requirements for Attendance and Securement of Certain Freight Trains and Vehicles on Mainline Track or Mainline Siding Outside of a Yard or Terminal|url=http://www.fra.dot.gov/eLib/details/L04719|publisher=Federal Railroad Administration |date=August 2, 2013 |accessdate=November 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maine Department of Transportation]] is working to establish contingency plans for local industry which uses MMA's rail lines. The state has contacted every Maine freight rail operator, seeking a trustee who could keep the line running should MMA cease operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwayage.com/index.php/freight/short-lines/maine-weighs-options-for-mma-traffic.html|title=Maine weighs options for MM&A traffic|author=Douglas John Bowen|work=Railway Age}}</ref><ref>[http://www.mpbn.net/News/MaineNewsArchive/tabid/181/ctl/ViewItem/mid/3475/ItemId/29184/Default.aspx MPBN News: \"Maine Prepares for Possible Shutdown of MMA Railway\", July 30, 2013.]</ref>\n\n===Canadian federal impact===\nOn July 7, PM [[Stephen Harper]] described the area as a \"war zone\" and claimed the [[Cabinet of Canada|federal Cabinet]] would have the proper authorities \"conduct a very complete investigation and act on the recommendations\".<ref name=vansun /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/news-video/video-pm-condolences-to-train-crash-victims/article13052128/ |title=Video: Harper offers condolences to train crash victims |date=July 7, 2013 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe disaster has drawn criticisms of federal [[deregulation]] of the rail industry in Canada. The [[Public Service Alliance of Canada]], which represents inspectors at [[Transport Canada]], has objected to a pattern of fewer inspections, [[deferred maintenance]] of rail lines already in poor condition and an increasing number of cars on each train, going as far as to label the [[Government of Canada]] as \"complicit\" in the disaster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Politique/2013/07/15/005-lac-megantic-conservateurs-complices.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : les conservateurs montr\u00e9s du doigt par un syndicat f\u00e9d\u00e9ral |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Leaders of two federal opposition parties, the [[New Democratic Party of Canada]] and the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]], have called for the [[Parliament of Canada]] to examine rail safety in Canada with possible implementation of stricter regulation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2013/07/08/pol-train-political-reaction.html |title=Train disaster triggers political debate on rail safety |publisher=CBC News |date=July 8, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.680news.com/2013/07/12/ndp-calls-for-commons-committee-to-sit-this-summer-on-rail-safety/ |title=Political repercussions of deadly train crash grow amid calls to back off |publisher=[[CFTR (AM)|680News]] Toronto |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> The [[Conservative Party of Canada]] has opposed a critical review of [[Transport Canada]]'s oversight of the railways,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/national/Tory+dismisses+need+review+critical+audit+Transport/8654008/story.html |title=Tories dismiss need for review of critical audit of Transport Canada following Lac-Megantic disaster |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]] |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Millions of dollars budgeted to Transport Canada for rail safety in [[fiscal year]]s 2011\u201312 and 2012\u201313 remain unspent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.canada.com/news/Auditor+General+denies+giving+Transport+Canada+extensions+safety+oversight+commitments/8645940/story.html |title=Watchdogs contradict Transport Canada safety oversight claims following Lac-Megantic disaster |publisher=[[Postmedia]] |date=July 12, 2013 |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, federal regulation requires rail carriers carry adequate third-party liability insurance but does not legislate a specific dollar minimum in coverage.<ref>{{cite news|last=Egan |first=Louise |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/08/07/us-train-montrealmaineatlantic-idUSBRE97614E20130807 |title=Railway in deadly Quebec explosion files for bankruptcy |work=Reuters |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> The amount of coverage is not disclosed to the public nor to municipalities along the line. MMA was insured for $25 million in liability;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2013/08/07/business-megantic-mma.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster company MM&A files for bankruptcy |publisher=CBC News |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> a second policy exists but only covers damage to MMA equipment and rolling stock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/railways-insurance-far-short-of-damage_2013-08-09.html |title=Maine railway's insurance far short of damage |newspaper=Portland Press Herald |date=August 9, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe federal government had been subject to intense [[lobbying]] by the [[Railway Association of Canada]] and the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] prior to the disaster, with railway association lobbyists meeting with multiple federal officials \u201cto inform about the movement of dangerous goods, including voluntary and regulatory requirements, volumes, customers and safety measures to assure them that current regulations for dangerous goods transportation are sufficient.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last=Gyulai |first=Linda |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/Railways+have+been+lobbying+against+more+stringent+safety+regulations/8654175/story.html |title=Railways have been lobbying against more stringent safety regulations |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |date=July 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref> A similar situation exists in the US, with nearly $47 million/year in lobbying to delay safety measures such as [[positive train control]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Joan Lowy |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/international-business/us-business/how-the-rail-industry-lobbies-to-delay-safety-technology/article14091823/ |title=Rail industry lobbies to delay safety technology |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=September 3, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Environmental Petitions<ref name=petitions>{{cite web|url=http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/internet/English/pet_fs_e_919.html|title=Environmental Petitions|work=Office of the Auditor General}}</ref> process of the federal Commissioner of the Environment and Sustainable Development is one avenue for citizen redress, whereby the Minister is required to answer within 120 days.<ref name=petitions/>\n\nIn December 2011, the Commissioner on Environment and Sustainable Development, a branch of the [[Auditor General of Canada]], recommended<ref name=\"agreport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/internet/english/parl_cesd_201112_01_e_36029.html|title=Chapter 1\u2014Transportation of Dangerous Products|work=Office of the Auditor General}}</ref> to address weaknesses in the oversight of the transportation of dangerous goods. Deficiencies identified by the [[Auditor General of Canada|AGC]] in 2011 included:<ref name=\"agreport\"/>\n*There is a lack of follow-up by Transport Canada on identified deficiencies\n*Transport Canada does not know the extent to which organizations transporting dangerous goods are complying with regulations\n*Transport Canada does not conduct an adequate, timely review when approving emergency response assistance plans\n*Management has not acted on long-standing concerns regarding inspection and emergency plan review practices\nAt the time of the release of the AGC report, [[Transport Canada]] agreed to review its procedures and enhance all of its practices by April 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Minsky |first=Amy |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/710646/ag-refutes-granting-transport-canada-extensions-on-addressing-safety-weaknesses/ |title=AG refutes granting Transport Canada extensions on addressing safety weaknesses |publisher=Globalnews.ca |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMarie France Dagenais, director-general of the Transportation of Dangerous Goods division of [[Transport Canada]],<ref>[http://ca.linkedin.com/pub/marie-france-dagenais/69/a69/804 'linked-in' page of Dagenais] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130817170014/http://ca.linkedin.com/pub/marie-france-dagenais/69/a69/804 |date=August 17, 2013 }}</ref> prioritizes her job as follows: \"naturally we do it in cooperation with the industry and also representatives with the U.S. government because we want uniform standards in Canada and the United States\u201d and thus explains the five-year delay to develop standards in her department.<ref name=\"postmedia9july\">{{cite web|url=http://o.canada.com/news/national/transport-canada-vowed-to-fix-inadequate-oversight-of-dangerous-goods-transportation-in-2011/|title=Safety oversight plagued Transport Canada for years: audit|work=Postmedia}}</ref> Meanwhile, some representatives with the U.S. government were participating in drug use and sexual activity with employees from the very energy firms they were to be regulating.<ref name=wapo529>{{cite news |author=Juliet Eilperin |author2=Madonna Lebling\n |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/28/AR2010052804599.html?hpid=topnews\n |title=MMS's troubled past |date=May 29, 2010 |newspaper=Washington Post |accessdate=May 30, 2010}}</ref><!--is this sentence necessary?-->\n\nHowever, it would appear that many of the issues raised by the audit are not new. \u201cAn internal audit identified these same concerns over five years ago. The department has yet to correct some of the key weaknesses in its regulatory oversight practices,\u201d stated former environment commissioner Scott Vaughan in July 2013.<ref name=\"postmedia9july\"/>\n\nOn August 22, 2013, a committee of the [[Senate of Canada]] reported its findings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sencanada.ca/content/sen/committee/411/enev/dpk/22aug13/home-e.htm|title=The Standing Senate Committee on Energy, the Environment and Natural Resources - NOW OR NEVER: Canada Must Act Urgently to Seize its Place in the New Energy World Order|work=parl.gc.ca}}</ref> The Energy, Environment and Natural Resources (ENEV) committee<ref name=enev>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/sencommitteebusiness/CommitteeHome.aspx?parl=39&ses=1&Language=E&comm_id=5|title=Home - Energy, the Environment and Natural Resources|work=Parliament of Canada}}</ref> decided in November 2012 to report on energy safety issues and had input from more than 50 individuals or groups as it crossed Canada. The chair of the committee, Sen. [[Richard Neufeld]], said that the entire committee was supportive of minimum insurance coverage: \u201cIf they can\u2019t afford their liability coverage, maybe they shouldn\u2019t be in the business.\u201d<ref name=postmedia22aug>[http://www.canada.com/news/Senate+committee+proposes+mandatory+minimum+insurance+rail+companies+after+Megantic/8822399/story.html Postmedia: \"Senate committee proposes mandatory minimum...\" August 22, 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116160319/http://www.canada.com/news/Senate+committee+proposes+mandatory+minimum+insurance+rail+companies+after+Megantic/8822399/story.html |date=November 16, 2013 }}</ref> The committee noted that \"pipeline companies are subject to a minimum of $1 billion available in bonds, lines of credit, third-party guarantees and liability insurance.\",<ref name=\"postmedia22aug\"/> and that in 2012 alone there were 118 railway accidents involving dangerous goods.<ref name=postmedia22aug/> The 13 recommendations of the committee include:<ref name=\"cbcaug23\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/08/22/pol-senate-report-railway-systems-dangerous-goods.html|title=Senate seeks railway overhaul in wake of Lac-M\u00e9gantic|date=August 22, 2013|work=CBC Montr\u00e9al}}</ref>\n* The federal government should launch an arm's-length review of the railway regulatory framework, standards and industry practices.\n* Transport Canada should apply appropriate minimum liability coverage thresholds to ensure rail companies have the financial capacity to cover damages caused by a major incident.\n* The National Energy Board and Transport Canada should create a web portal that includes interactive maps indicating detailed information on spills and incidents for pipelines, tankers and railcars. It should include the types of product released and the cause of the incident.\n\nStricter safety requirements, including two-person crews and additional requirements for hand brakes, were announced in October 2014.<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-lisa-raitt-announces-rail-safety-rules-based-on-crash-findings-1.2816680</ref> In February 2015, the federal Minister of Transport announced a two-year phase-in of stricter liability for rail carriers, in which a [[Class I railway]] handling hazardous material could be required to carry a billion dollars in liability insurance.<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/proposed-rail-safety-laws-to-make-oil-carriers-responsible-for-accidents-1.2964879</ref>\n\n==Litigation==\n\nIn Canada, a [[class action]] lawsuit was filed by Daniel Larochelle (a Lac-M\u00e9gantic attorney whose office was destroyed by the derailment and fire) and a group of Canadian and US law firms on behalf of Musi-Caf\u00e9 proprietor Yannick Gagn\u00e9 and one of the [[widow]]ers from the disaster, Guy Ouellet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/07/15/003-lac-megantic-recours-collectif-mma.shtml |title=Trag\u00e9die \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic : une demande de recours collectif est d\u00e9pos\u00e9e |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Afterwards, two more petitioners were added to the suit, Serges Jacques and Louis-Serge Parent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.clg.org/pdf/2/8/6/Third%20Amended%20Motion%20for%20Authorization.pdf|title=Third Amended Motion for Authorization}}</ref> The suit names a long list of rail and oil companies, including Western Petroleum Company and Irving Oil:<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/19/006-recours-collectif-cp-megantic.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : de nouvelles entreprises vis\u00e9es par le recours collectif \n|language=French \n|publisher=Radio-Canada \n|date=August 19, 2013 \n|accessdate=August 19, 2013\n}}</ref><ref name=marowits19aug/>\n* [[Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway|MMA]]\n* [[Western Petroleum Company]] (lessee)\n* [[Irving Oil]]\n* [[Canadian Pacific Railway]]\n* [[Union Tank Car Company]]\n* [[Trinity Industries]]\n* [[GE Capital Rail Services]] (lessors)\nIt alleged [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] \"entrusted the transport of highly explosive shale liquids to a carrier with one of the poorest safety records in the industry which was operating on poorly maintained '[[Rail regulations in Canada#Tracks|excepted track]]' that did not permit the transport of flammable or dangerous goods\" and claims CP knew that MMA was insolvent and underinsured. It also targeted [[Union Tank Car Company]], [[Trinity Industries]] and [[GE Capital Rail Services]], claiming \"non-reinforced older model [[DOT-111 tank car|DOT-111 tankers]] were wholly unsuitable for the transport of these highly explosive shale liquids\".<ref>{{cite press release\n|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1211681/cp-rail-union-tank-trinity-industries-ge-railcar-services-and-western-petroleum-implicated-in-the-lac-megantic-class-proceeding \n|title=Rochon Genova LLP &#124; CP Rail, Union Tank, Trinity Industries, GE Railcar Services and Western Petroleum Implicated in the Lac-M\u00e9gantic Class Proceeding \n|publisher=Newswire.ca \n|accessdate=August 18, 2013\n}}</ref> The lawsuit stated that the transportation of flammable and dangerous goods is limited to 10&nbsp;km/hour.<ref name=marowits19aug>[https://theprovince.com/business/Irving+subsidiary+considering+acquisition+insolvent+rail+line/8807089/story.html The Province: \"Irving subsidiary considering acquisition of insolvent MM&A rail line\" August 19, 2013].</ref> Canadian courts can award plaintiffs a maximum of $326,000 as compensation for non-economic damages like emotional distress.<ref name=mgsuit/>\n\nIn the US, multiple individual lawsuits were filed in [[Rail World]]'s home jurisdiction of [[Cook County, Illinois]] on behalf of various groups of next of kin.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/07/23/004-lac-megantic-famille-poursuit-mma-mort-injustifiee.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : la famille d'une des victimes poursuit la compagnie MMA |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref> One such lawsuit filed in Cook County by Lac-M\u00e9gantic lawyer Gloriane Blais with two US lawyers (Edward Jazlowiecki in Connecticut and Mitchell Toups in Texas) listed eleven defendants, mostly North Dakota oil companies directly responsible for the train and its contents.<ref name=mgsuit>{{cite news|last=Sparks |first=Riley |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/M%C3%A9gantic+lawsuit+targets+companies/8744327/story.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic lawsuit targets 11 companies |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |date=August 2, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref> Jazlowiecki stated that Illinois has no limit on compensation for non-economic damage like emotional distress, and that he foresaw the verdict in 24 to 36 months.<ref name=mgsuit/> Another lawsuit filed in [[Chicago, Illinois]] on behalf of ten victims is asking for over $50 million in damages.<ref name=mgsuit/>\n\n[[Tafisa Canada]], [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and Western Petroleum Company also announced intent to seek damages.<ref>{{cite news|last=Delean |first=Paul |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/Montreal+Maine+Atlantic+files+bankruptcy+protection/8759563/story.html |title=Montreal, Maine and Atlantic files for bankruptcy protection |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-July, Burkhardt indicated \u201cWhether we can survive is a complex question. We\u2019re trying to analyze that right now.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|author=Marley DelDuchetto Kayden |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-19/railway-weighing-viability-after-quebec-crash-chairman-says-1-.html |title=Railway Weighing Viability After Quebec Crash, Chairman Says |publisher=Bloomberg |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2013}}</ref> On August 7, hours after Quebec health minister [[R\u00e9jean H\u00e9bert]] stated that the province may sue to recover costs of its aid to victims,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2013/08/07/001-hebert-mma-recours.shtml |title=Qu\u00e9bec n'\u00e9carte pas \" les recours juridiques \" contre MMA, dit le ministre R\u00e9jean H\u00e9bert |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> MMA filed for [[bankruptcy]] protection under US [[Chapter 11]] and Canada's [[Companies Creditors Arrangement Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Economie/2013/08/07/008-mma-se-place-sous-la-protection-des-tribunaux.shtml |title=La MMA sous la protection des tribunaux |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> As many of the suits name multiple defendants, typically oil companies including [[World Fuel Services]], the cases continued to progress despite MMA's bankruptcy filings.<ref name=mgsuit/>\n\nA $200 million legal settlement was proposed in January 2015, but remains subject to government approval in both nations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-rail-disaster-200m-settlement-reached-1.2896250|title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic rail disaster: $200M proposed settlement reached|date=January 10, 2015|work=CBC Montr\u00e9al}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, the [[government of Quebec]] sued Canadian Pacific Railway alleging it was negligent in transferring the oil train to the Montreal, Maine, and Atlantic and that it failed to take precautions that would have prevented the disaster. \u201cCP intends to fully defend itself in court,\u201d was the company's response.<ref>{{cite news |last=Atkins |first=Eric |date=November 30, 2015 |title=CP says it will fight $409-million Lac-M\u00e9gantic lawsuit |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/cp-says-it-will-fight-409-million-lac-megantic-lawsuit/article27533958/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Canada |access-date=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2016, Lac-M\u00e9gantic Town Council decided not to pursue legal action against Canadian Pacific, citing the costs involved in doing so and that there was no guarantee of a successful outcome.<ref name=CBC3646707>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-megantic-town-council-disaster-canadian-pacific-1.3646707 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic will not pursue Canadian Pacific Railway |publisher=CBC News |date=June 21, 2016 |accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Regulatory impact ==\n\nOn July 23, 2013, Transport Canada issued an emergency directive<ref name=directive>[http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/mediaroom/backgrounders-safety-locomotives-7292.html Text of \"Emergency Directive Pursuant to Section 33 of the Railway Safety Act\" July 23, 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905213245/http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/mediaroom/backgrounders-safety-locomotives-7292.html |date=September 5, 2013}}</ref> requiring at least two persons operate trains carrying tank cars of dangerous materials, prohibiting dangerous material trains left on the mainline unattended, requiring locomotive cabs on unattended trains be locked and [[reverser handle]]s removed to prevent the train being put into gear, imposing requirements for setting hand brakes on trains unattended for more than an hour and requiring both the automatic brake (train brake) and independent brake (locomotive brake) be applied at their maximum force for trains unattended for an hour or less.<ref name=cbcmtl23jul>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2013/07/23/quebec-canada-transport-lac-megantic-new-train-rules.html |title=New rail safety rules issued after Lac-Megantic disaster |publisher=CBC Montreal |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref> A ministerial emergency directive remains in effect for six months, although it can be renewed.<ref name=rsareview>{{cite web|url=http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/tcss/RSA_review/chapter4-374.htm|title=Chapter 4: Regulatory Framework|work=Transport Canada}}</ref>\n\nThe United States Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) issued a number of emergency orders on August 2, 2013, to all railroad operating companies in the country. The orders include a requirement for railroad companies to develop and submit to the FRA a plan to notify the agency when trains carrying hazardous materials will be left unattended as well as processes to secure the trains in their positions and to ensure that the locomotive doors are locked.<ref name=\"WSJ-130802\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324635904578644561741905382|title=Runaway Train in Quebec Sparks New U.S. Rail-Safety Rules|last=Morris|first=Betsey|date=August 2, 2013|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 3, 2013}}</ref> Before leaving a train unattended, railroad crews will need to notify dispatchers of the number of hand brakes that are being applied on the train along with the number of cars, the train length, the grade of the track on which the train is parked and the current weather conditions.<ref name=WSJ-130802 />\n\nThe Federal Railroad Administration is investigating multiple safety issues with crude oil shipments, which are the fastest-growing hazardous material shipments by rail. On July 29, the FRA requested [[American Petroleum Institute]] members provide data on content of their crude shipments and crude oil loading practices and proposed to do its own testing if the data were not made available.<ref name=np-fra>{{cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/08/09/in-wake-of-lac-megantic-tragedy-u-s-railroad-administration-says-crude-being-shipped-in-unsafe-rail-cars/ |title=In wake of Lac M\u00e9gantic tragedy, U.S. Railroad Administration says crude being shipped in unsafe rail cars |newspaper=National Post |date=August 9, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> The U.S. Department of Transportation's [[Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration]] launched a 'Bakken blitz' of inspections of [[North Dakota]] oil trains in August 2013, citing ongoing concerns about improper identification of the chemical composition and [[flash point]] of flammable cargo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/Feds-launch-Bakken-blitz-on-crude-carrying-rail-cars.html |title='Blitz' on to inspect oil-train contents |newspaper=Portland Press Herald |date=August 29, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the FRA, chemical composition of the oil is not being properly identified on shipping manifests, despite the use of corrosive or volatile chemicals in the [[fracking]] process. Content of blended crude from multiple wells is not tested before loading, even though FRA indicates that \u201cit is critical that shippers determine the proper classification of the crude oil\u201d as a tanker with a higher safety classification (and not the standard DOT-111A car) is required for corrosive or explosive materials. The information is needed for provision to first responders and emergency services during a disaster.\n\nIn an increasing number of incidents, chemicals such as [[hydrochloric acid]] (used to release crude from oil well rock formations) have corroded tanks, covers, valves and fittings. As unit trains of tanker cars do not pass over weigh-in-motion scales in classification yards, many are overloaded, increasing risks of leakage as oil expands with temperature. The result has been twice the number of leaks from crude oil shipments as from alcohol shipments, the next highest hazardous material, even though comparable volumes of each travel by rail.<ref name=np-fra/>\n\nIn January 2014, Canada's Transportation Safety Board recommended that DOT-111 / CTC-111A oil-by-rail cars built before October 2011 be replaced with the newer, reinforced design. It also recommended carriers perform route planning and analysis and advocated mandated emergency response plans. While TSB set no clear deadlines, [[Irving Oil]] plans to replace the remainder of its own fleet of DOT-111's by the end of April 2014 and ask its suppliers to modernise by the year's end.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/irving-oil-to-convert-tank-railcars-to-meet-higher-standards-1.2540802 |title=Irving Oil to convert tank railcars to meet higher standards |publisher=CBC New Brunswick |date=February 17, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, the US Federal Railroad Administration placed crude oil under the most protective two sets of hazardous materials shipping requirements and issued an order requiring tests of crude oil before shipment by rail.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/crude-oil-must-be-tested-before-shipped-by-rail-u-s-regulators-say-1.2551227 |title=Crude oil must be tested before shipped by rail, U.S. regulators say |publisher=CBC News |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, the Canadian government required a phaseout or retrofit of the older DOT-111 oil-by-rail cars on a three-year deadline and mandated emergency response plans for all oil shipments by rail.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/lisa-raitt-to-enhance-rail-safety-measures-in-wake-of-lac-m%C3%A9gantic-1.2618788 |title=Lisa Raitt to enhance rail safety measures in wake of Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=CBC News |date=April 19, 2014 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Rebuilding efforts==\n\nA new group of four {{convert|15000|sqft|m2}} commercial buildings<ref name=\"lapresse1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/la-tribune/actualites/201308/21/01-4681878-le-centre-ville-ferme-pour-un-an.php |title=Le centre-ville ferm\u00e9 pour un an |author=Ronald Martel |publisher=La Tribune (Sherbrooke) |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> was built to accommodate some displaced businesses<ref>{{cite news|last=Dougherty |first=Kevin |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/M%C3%A9gantic+gets+funds+rebuild+downtown+core/8836083/story.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic gets funds to rebuild downtown core |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]] |date=September 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> on a new site near the sports centre.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kathryn Blaze Carlson |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/how-rebuilding-plans-will-create-a-new-vision-of-lac-megantic/article13825605/?page=all |title=How rebuilding plans will create a new vision of Lac-M\u00e9gantic |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fr.canoe.ca/infos/regional/archives/2013/08/20130814-234806.html |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic: nouveau p\u00f4le commercial \u00e0 l'automne |publisher=Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia |language=French |date=August 14, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> In August 2013, consultants began surveying the site of a new bridge across the [[Chaudi\u00e8re River]] from Papineau Street to L\u00e9vis Street,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echodefrontenac.com/tragediedelacmegantic2.asp?IdNouv=2602 |title=Myst\u00e8re autour d'une pancarte |author=R\u00e9mi Tremblay |date=October 31, 2013 |publisher=Echo de Frontenac |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> to serve the new commercial district.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/08/17/003-megantic-travaux-relocalisation.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : d\u00e9but des travaux de relocalisation des commerces |publisher=Radio-Canada |language=French |date=August 17, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref><!-- when did it open? --> New rail track reconnected the local industrial park to the Montreal line in November 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2013/11/15/001-retour-trains-lac-megantic.shtml |title=Les trains pourraient commencer \u00e0 rouler \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic d'ici un mois |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=November 15, 2013 |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref> Private residences were expropriated to make way for redevelopment in Fatima.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-residents-fear-possible-expropriation-1.1928046 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic residents fear possible expropriation |publisher=CBC Montreal |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2014/06/11/005-lac-megantic-expropriation.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : des r\u00e9sidents disent faire les frais de la reconstruction |publisher=Radio-Canada |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nStudents at [[Laval University]], [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/societe/201308/17/01-4680885-50-000-livres-pour-regarnir-la-biblio-de-lac-megantic.php |title=50 000 livres pour regarnir la biblio de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |author=David R\u00e9millard |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |date=August 17, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> and [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.985fm.ca/regional/nouvelles/des-livres-pour-la-future-bibliotheque-de-lac-mega-254353.html |title=Des livres pour la future biblioth\u00e8que de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=985fm.ca |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822132610/http://www.985fm.ca/regional/nouvelles/des-livres-pour-la-future-bibliotheque-de-lac-mega-254353.html |archivedate=August 22, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> collected tens of thousands of books for a new library.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laction.com/Actualites/2013-08-14/article-3349219/Des-milliers-de-livres-pour-Lac-Megantic/1 |title=Des milliers de livres pour Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=L'Action (Joliette) |language=French |date=August 14, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> Libraries in other Quebec communities solicited book donations<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavantage.qc.ca/actualite/24-07-2013-des-partenaires-pour-la-collecte-de-livres-pour-lac-megantic |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130819031212/http://www.lavantage.qc.ca/actualite/24-07-2013-des-partenaires-pour-la-collecte-de-livres-pour-lac-megantic |url-status=dead |archivedate=August 19, 2013 |title=Des partenaires pour la collecte de livres pour Lac-M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Journal L'Avantage (Rimouski &ndash; Mont-Joli &ndash; Matane) |language=French |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavantage.qc.ca/communiques-matane/31-07-2013-a-matane-collecte-de-livres-en-solidarite-envers-lac-megantic |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130819031217/http://www.lavantage.qc.ca/communiques-matane/31-07-2013-a-matane-collecte-de-livres-en-solidarite-envers-lac-megantic |url-status=dead |archivedate=August 19, 2013 |title=\u00c0 Matane : collecte de livres en solidarit\u00e9 envers Lac M\u00e9gantic |publisher=Journal L'Avantage (Rimouski &ndash; Mont-Joli &ndash; Matane) |language=French |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> and searched local archives for information on M\u00e9gantic's history. The new library, which had received 100,000 donated volumes (some of them duplicates) by September 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ville.lac-megantic.qc.ca/publications/publication/article/message-de-la-mediatheque-nelly-arcand/ |title=Message de la Mediath\u00e8que Nelly-Arcan |publisher=Ville de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref> opened on May 5, 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mediathequenellyarcan.ca/publications/publication/article/ouverture-de-la-mediatheque/ |title=Ouverture de la M\u00e9diath\u00e8que |publisher=M\u00e9diath\u00e8que municipale Nelly Arcan &ndash; Ville Lac-M\u00e9gantic |date=October 5, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425092141/http://mediathequenellyarcan.ca/publications/publication/article/ouverture-de-la-mediatheque/ |archive-date=April 25, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/lac-m%C3%A9gantic-library-may-reopen-in-2014-thanks-to-donations-1.2478332 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic library may reopen in 2014 thanks to donations |publisher=CBC Montreal |accessdate=December 29, 2013}}</ref> as ''La M\u00e9diath\u00e8que municipale Nelly-Arcan'' in honour of [[Nelly Arcan|an author born in the town]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echodefrontenac.com/actualitedujour.asp?IdNouv=2475 |title=La M\u00e9diath\u00e8que municipale Nelly-Arcan pr\u00eate pour l'automne |publisher=\u00c9cho de Frontenac, hebdo de la r\u00e9gion de Lac-M\u00e9gantic |language=French |accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/la-tribune/estrie-et-regions/201308/12/01-4679294-place-a-la-mediatheque-nelly-arcan.php |title=Place \u00e0 la M\u00e9diath\u00e8que Nelly-Arcan |author=Ronald Martel |publisher=La Tribune (Sherbrooke) |language=French |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA temporary \"Musi-Caf\u00e9 d'\u00e9t\u00e9\"<ref name=cafeete>{{cite magazine|last=Blatchford |first=Andy |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2013/07/30/resilient-lac-megantic-bar-razed-in-rail-disaster-set-to-reopen-in-battered-town/ |title=Resilient Lac-Megantic bar razed in rail disaster set to reopen in battered town |magazine=Macleans |date=July 30, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/societe/201309/20/01-4691633-megantic-se-releve-le-contemporain-au-service-de-lurgence.php |title=M\u00e9gantic se rel\u00e8ve: le contemporain au service de l'urgence |author=Alexandra Perron |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |language=French |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref> hosted numerous Quebec musicians, including [[Marie-Mai]], [[Louis-Jean Cormier]], [[Karim Ouellet]], [[Vincent Valli\u00e8res]], [[Michel Rivard]], [[Dan Bigras]], [[Richard Desjardins]], [[Claude Dubois]], [[Paul Pich\u00e9]] and [[Fred Pellerin]], in a series of free benefit concerts in a 150-seat tent from August 2 until mid-September 2013, raising money for local rebuilding efforts.<ref name=cafeete /><ref>[http://www.lapresse.ca/arts/201307/30/01-4675368-le-musi-cafe-renait-baume-musical-pour-lac-megantic.php \"Le Musi-Caf\u00e9 rena\u00eet : baume musical pour Lac-M\u00e9gantic\"]. ''[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]]'', July 31, 2013.</ref> A new Musi-Caf\u00e9<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.echodefrontenac.com/tragediedelacmegantic2.asp?IdNouv=2812 |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic va se relever! |publisher=\u00c9cho de Frontenac, Lac-M\u00e9gantic |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> opened in a $1.6 million building<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/musi-caf%C3%A9-reopening-in-lac-m%C3%A9gantic-a-big-boost-to-town-s-recovery-1.2871511|title=Musi-Caf\u00e9 reopening in Lac-M\u00e9gantic a big boost to town's recovery|date=December 15, 2014|work=CBC News}}</ref> at the foot of the new Papineau Street bridge<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/06/10/007-musi-cafe-lac-megantic-travaux-au-ralenti.shtml |title=Musi-Caf\u00e9: le propri\u00e9taire fait une croix sur l'\u00e9t\u00e9 |publisher=Radio-Canada |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> on December 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/estrie/2014/12/08/001-ouverture-nouveau-musi-cafe-lac-megantic.shtml|title=Le nouveau Musi-Caf\u00e9 ouvre ses portes \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic|work=Radio-Canada}}</ref>\n\n[[Metro Inc.|M\u00e9tro]] opened its new M\u00e9tro Plus Lac-M\u00e9gantic grocery store on October 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L7oJgZl54ic|title=Video of M\u00e9tro store's grand re-opening in Lac-M\u00e9gantic|publisher=M\u00e9tro Inc.}}</ref> {{asof|2014}} [[Dollarama]] has not yet returned; [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] has reopened in one of the new buildings on Papineau Street<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w.subway.com/en-CA/FindAStore|title=SUBWAY store locator|work=subway.com}}</ref> and [[Jean Coutu Group|Jean Coutu]] is operating from reduced, temporary facilities until a new location can be built in Fatima.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/le-soleil/actualites/societe/201309/20/01-4691632-megantic-se-releve-repenser-la-ville.php |title=M\u00e9gantic se rel\u00e8ve: repenser la ville |author=Alexandra Perron |publisher=Le Soleil (Qu\u00e9bec) |language=French |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLocal demands to re-route the rails around the town also remain unaddressed, despite the risk that oil shipments could resume by the start of 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/societe/2014/06/13/007-lac-megantic-avenir-espoirs-reconstruction-desautels.shtml |title=Lac-M\u00e9gantic : des choix d\u00e9chirants \u00e0 faire |publisher=Radio-Canada |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Pedal'Aide, a trio from Montreal's McGill University raised $10,000 over two weeks whilst biking 1300&nbsp;km from Lac-M\u00e9gantic to Prince Edward Island<ref>{{cite web|title=Pedal'Aide|url=http://pedalaide.com|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Three students bike 1,300 km for Lac-M\u00e9gantic relief funds|url=http://www.redcross.ca/who-we-are/red-cross-stories/2013/three-students-bike-1,300-km-for-lac-megantic-relief-funds|publisher=Red Cross|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=Ryan|title=Cycling trio raising money for Lac-Megantic relief|url=http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/News/Local/2013-08-03/article-3337890/Cycling-trio-raising-money-for-Lac-Megantic-relief/1|accessdate=October 3, 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=August 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Laplante|first=Claude|title=1000 kilom\u00e8tres de v\u00e9lo pour les orphelins de Lac-M\u00e9gantic|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/la-tribune/estrie-et-regions/201308/08/01-4678298-1000-kilometres-de-velo-pour-les-orphelins-de-lac-megantic.php|accessdate=October 3, 2013|newspaper=La Presse|date=August 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McDevitt|first=Neale|title=Pedal power: Trio\u2019s epic ride to raise funds for Lac-M\u00e9gantic|url=http://publications.mcgill.ca/reporter/2013/08/pedal-power-trios-epic-ride-to-raise-funds-for-lac-megantic/|accessdate=October 3, 2013|newspaper=McGill Reporter|date=August 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McDevitt|first=Neale|title=Riding into the sunset to help Lac-M\u00e9gantic relief efforts|url=http://publications.mcgill.ca/reporter/2013/08/riding-into-the-sunset/|accessdate=October 3, 2013|newspaper=McGill Reporter|date=August 27, 2013}}</ref> -->\n\nIn 2018, writer [[Anne-Marie Saint-Cerny]] published the book ''M\u00e9gantic: Une trag\u00e9die annonc\u00e9e'',<ref>[https://www.ledevoir.com/lire/530310/de-wall-street-a-lac-megantic-anne-marie-saint-cerny-traque-les-vrais-coupables-de-la-tragedie-du-6-juillet-2013 \"De Wall Street \u00e0 Lac-M\u00e9gantic, enqu\u00eate sur la trag\u00e9die du 6 juillet 2013\"]. ''[[Le Devoir]]'', June 16, 2018.</ref> an examination of the disaster. The book was a shortlisted finalist for the [[Governor General's Award for French-language non-fiction]] at the [[2018 Governor General's Awards]].<ref>[https://www.ledevoir.com/lire/538294/lumiere-sur-les-gg \"Lumi\u00e8re sur les finalistes des Prix litt\u00e9raires du Gouverneur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral\"]. ''[[Le Devoir]]'', October 4, 2018.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Canada}}\n{{commons category|2013 Lac-M\u00e9gantic derailment}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Dark territory]]\n* [[Lists of rail accidents]]\n*Similar rail accidents:\n** [[Chester General rail crash]], UK, 1972 \u2014 brakes failed on train transporting fuel, derailed and caught fire\n** [[1989 Helena train wreck]], Montana, USA \u2013 uncoupled train with brake failure rolled {{convert|14|km|mi}} from a mountain pass into town, where it collided with another train and its flammable cargo exploded, damaging buildings and infrastructure\n** [[Nishapur train disaster]], Iran, 2004 \u2014 train with highly flammable cargo derailed, explosion destroyed village\n** [[Viareggio train derailment]], Italy, 2009 \u2014 train transporting [[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]] derailed and exploded in an urban area\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<!--\n<ref name=huffpost>{{cite web|title=Lac-Megantic Death Toll Rises To 35|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/07/14/lac-megantic-priest_n_3594517.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=July 14, 2013|accessdat