osites]]''\n| 2 seasons, 16 episodes\n| [[Justin Roiland]]<br> Mike McMahan\n| May 8, 2020\n| Hulu\n| [[20th Century Fox Television]]<br>[[Justin Roiland's Solo Vanity Card Productions!]]\n| <ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2018/08/solar-opposites-alien-animated-comedy-rick-and-morty-duo-20th-tv-hulu-series-order-justin-roliand-mike-mcmahan-1202453250/ | title = Alien Animated Comedy From 'Rick and Morty' Duo & 20th TV Gets Hulu Series Order  | accessdate = August 28, 2018 | date = August 28, 2018 | work=Deadline }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Star Trek: Lower Decks]]''\n| 2 seasons, 20 episodes\n| Mike McMahan\n| 2020\n| [[CBS All Access]]\n| [[CBS Animation|CBS Eye Animation Productions]]<br>Secret Hideout<br>Roddenberry Entertainment\n| <ref name=\"StarTrekSeriesOrder\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title='Star Trek: Lower Decks' Animated Series From 'Rick and Morty' EP & Secret Hideout Ordered By CBS All Access |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/star-trek-lower-decks-animated-series-rick-and-morty-mike-mcmahan-alex-kurtzman-cbs-all-access-1202489207/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=October 28, 2018 |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[What If...? (TV series)|What If...?]]''\n| 1 seasons, 23 episodes\n| A.C. Bradley\n| 2021\n| [[Disney+]]\n| [[Marvel Studios]]\n| <ref name=\"Disney+SeriesSep2018\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/loki-scarlet-witch-tv-series-marvel-disney-streaming-service-1202947551/ |title=Loki, Scarlet Witch, Other Marvel Heroes to Get Own TV Series on Disney Streaming Service (EXCLUSIVE) |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=September 18, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/72XWaEZfB?url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/loki-scarlet-witch-tv-series-marvel-disney-streaming-service-1202947551/ |url-status=live|archive-date=2018-09-19 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''YOLO: Crystal Fantasy''\n| 1 season, TBA episodes\n| Michael Cusack\n| August 9, 2020\n| Adult Swim\n| TBA\n| <ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/adult-swim-yolo-crystal-fantasy-michael-cusack-1203547708/ | title = Adult Swim Orders \u2018YOLO: Crystal Fantasy\u2019 From Michael Cusack (EXCLUSIVE)   | accessdate = March 30, 2020 | date = March 30, 2020 | work=Variety }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Adult animation]]\n* [[List of adult animated films]]\n* [[List of adult animated internet series]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{Lists of television programs by genre}}\n\n[[Category:Animation-related lists|Adult animated series]]\n[[Category:Adult animated television series| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of animated television series|Adult]]\n", "name_user": "Yay Dad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited States", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_adult_animated_television_series"}
{"title_page": "Nexity", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Nexity SA\n| logo             = Nexity logo.svg\n| logo_size        = 150px\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 anonyme]] \n| traded_as        = {{Euronext|isin=FR0010112524|NXY}}<br>[[CAC Mid 60|CAC Mid 60 Component]]\n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2000}} <ref group=\"note\">Date since when it used the name Nexity.</ref>\n| founder          =  \n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = [[Paris]]\n| location_country = [[France]]<ref name=\"A1\"/>\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = Europe\n| key_people       = Alain Dinin (chairman and{{wbr}}&nbsp;CEO)\n| industry         = [[Real estate development]]<br />[[Real estate services]]\n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \u20ac2.6 billion <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| operating_income = \u20ac113.53 million <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nexity.fr/ressource/pdf/1312_statutoryauditorsreportontheconsolidatedfinancialstatements2011.pdf |title=2011 Statutory Auditors\u2019 Report on the Consolidated Financial Statements |publisher=Nexity |format=PDF |accessdate=15 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702182438/http://www.nexity.fr/ressource/pdf/1312_statutoryauditorsreportontheconsolidatedfinancialstatements2011.pdf |archivedate=2 July 2013 }}</ref>\n| net_income       = \u20ac58.15 million <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| aum              =  \n| assets           = \u20ac4.27 billion <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| equity           = \u20ac1.68 billion <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|nexity.fr|Nexity.fr}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Nexity''' is a French company that focuses on real estate development and the provision of related services.<ref name=\"A1\"/><ref name=\"A2\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Beginnings: the Arnault family===\nIn 1971, [[Bernard Arnault]] started to work in his family business,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1122/fashion-bernard-arnault-lvmh-luxury-dior-master-of-brand_3.html |title=Master of the Brand: Bernard Arnault  |author1=Adams, Susan |author2=Elliott, Hannah |work=forbes.com |publisher=[[Forbes]] |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> the industrial and public works construction company Ferret-Savinel. There he began to develop real estate activities. In 1974, he convinced his father, then CEO, to change the focus of the company, sell the division of industrial construction to Quillery and use the money to enter fully into the business of real estate. Following that sale, Ferret-Savinel changed its name, becoming Ferinel, and, focused on the real estate market, began increasing its portfolio. In the 1980s, the company continued to grow, being one of the largest companies in the Paris property sector and serving as a springboard for Arnault's future endeavors, particularly with its acquisition of the textile company Groupe Boussac in 1984. In 1988, following this success, the headquarters were transferred from [[Roubaix]] to Paris and the real estate branch was renamed George V Group.<ref name=\"B2\">{{cite book |title=International Directory of Company Histories |volume=66 |date=December 2004 |publisher=St. James Press |isbn=1558625119 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/internationaldir0066unse }}</ref>\n\n===CGE steps up===\nThe ''[[Compagnie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Eaux]] (CGE)'' was established in the mid-19th century in order to provide water supply services to France's industrial cities. For the early 20th century, CGE was already one of France's largest private companies.\n\nThrough the first half of the century, CGE remained focused on its core water utilities operations. In the 1960s, however, CGE launched a new diversification strategy that led it into a variety of new markets over the next two decades, including the construction and real estate sales and development sectors. In 1979, the company increased this activity with the acquisition of Maison Phenix, a leading real state company. In 1988, CGE made another important purchase, obtaining the construction company Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale d'Entreprise (the future [[Vinci (construction)|Vinci]]). In the 90s, during the French real estate crisis, CGE gathered all its residential real estate and development activities in a new subsidiary, called MI SA, which soon begun to be the leader of the French housing market.\n\nIn 1995, CGE bought the George V real estate division from Groupe Arnault.<ref name=B2/>\n\n===CGE restructure: CGIS era===\nCGE became a giant company, with a wide range of activities (construction, telecommunications, pay television, facilities management, the operation of amusement parks, and others), but the incompatibity between its real estate and construction components led it into a crisis in the mid-1990s. CGE was restructured and the construction sector was formed into a separate company, Vinci. In 1996, the real estate branch was also reorganised into a sole subsidiary, Compagnie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale d'Immobilier et de Services (CGIS).<ref name=\"B1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/temp/2007/06/30/04011-20070630ARTFIG90855-alain_dinin_le_chti_devenu_roi_des_promoteurs.php |title=Alain Dinin, le \" chti \" devenu roi des promoteurs  |author=Lentschner, Keren |work=lefigaro.fr |publisher=[[Le Figaro]] |date=14 October 2007 |language= French |trans-title=Alain Dinin, the \"Northerner\" who became king of promoters |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> The lack of coordination between different areas, however, continued. CGIS had to sell many assets to stay afloat and CGE finally decided to separate from the real estate area, adopt the name [[Vivendi]], and refocus itself as a media and communications firm. CGIS and MI were apart soon after.<ref name=\"B2\"/>\n\n===European expansion and refocus: Nexity era===\nAs a new independent company, CGIS difficulties continued. It sold its hotels to [[Accor]] and [[Pierre & Vacances]] and a number of its [[La D\u00e9fense]] buildings to [[Unibail]]. In 2000 CGIS was sold in a management buyout backed by [[CDC Ixis Capital]], [[LBO France]], and [[Lehman Brothers]], changing its name to Nexity. In 2001, was created the [[Spain|Spanish]] subsidiary (even though operations there were made with French property since the 1990s), as well as the [[Portugal|Portuguese]]. In 2002, was established Nexity [[Belgium]]. In 2003, Nexity separate itself from its engineering services branch, Cotebo, in order to focus on property services and development. In January 2004, it strengthened its relatively weak real estate services sector with the purchase of Saggel.<ref name=\"B2\"/>\n\nIn July 2007, the Nexity shareholders approved the issuance of 19997501 shares, representing a 38.2 percent stake, for the  [[Groupe BPCE|Caisse Nationale des Caisses d'Epargne et de Pr\u00e9voyance]] (CNCE), through the [[Groupe Caisse d'Epargne]] (GCE), in exchange of a 25 percent of [[Cr\u00e9dit Foncier de France]], 31.9 percent of [[Eurosic]] and 100 percent of CGE Immobilier services division, including Lamy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.euronext.com/news/companypressrelease/companypressrelease-1721-EN.html?docid=406003&stockNews=true |title=Press Release |work=euronext.com |publisher=[[Euronext]] |date=7 July 2007 |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> Later, CNCE (currently Groupe BPCE) expanded its stake to 41.4 percent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bourse.trader-finance.fr/Nexity+la+CNCE+a+repris+1+du+capital+depuis+fin+avril+341476 |title=Nexity : la CNCE a repris 1% du capital depuis fin avril |publisher=Trader-finance.fr |date=17 July 2009 |language= French |trans-title=Nexity: CNCE took over 1% of capital since late April |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, Nexity sold its stake in Cr\u00e9dit Foncier to CNCE by 540 million euros.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.propertyeu.info/index-newsletter/nexity-sells-credit-foncier-stake-to-cnce-for-eur-540m/ |title=Nexity sells Credit Foncier stake to CNCE for EUR 540m |publisher=PropertyEU.com |date=30 January 2009 |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Activity==\nNexity operates as a real estate development company in Europe. Its working areas include residential properties, office buildings, offices, business parks, warehouses, distribution centers, office facilities, and hotels. The company also provides residential and commercial real estate, asset management, and property investment services. This is carried out through several divisions.<ref name=\"A1\"/><ref name=\"A2\"/>\n\n===Divisions===\n\n====Nexity Enterprises====\nThis division specialises in the development and renovation of skyscrapers and similar structures.\n\n====Geprim====\nGeprim centers on the development of warehouses, distribution centers and mixed-use units.\n\n====Nexity Services====\nNexity Services provides services during every stage of a project design, purchase, daily management, renovation and sale.<ref name=\"A1\">{{cite web |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/snapshot/snapshot.asp?ticker=NXI:FP |title=Company Description: Nexity S.A. |work=businessweek.com |publisher=[[BusinessWeek]] |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"A2\">{{cite web |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/03/05/bpce-nexity-idINL5E8E508J20120305?type=companyNews |title=Company Profile: Nexity S.A. |work=reuters.com |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{CAC Mid 60}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Paris]]\n[[Category:Real estate companies of France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Nexity SA\n| logo             = Nexity logo.svg\n| logo_size        = 150px\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 anonyme]] \n| traded_as        = {{Euronext|isin=FR0010112524|NXY}}<br>[[CAC Mid 60|CAC Mid 60 Component]]\n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2000}} <ref group=\"note\">Date since when it used the name Nexity.</ref>\n| founder          =  \n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = [[Paris]]\n| location_country = [[France]]<ref name=\"A1\"/>\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = Europe\n| key_people       = Alain Dinin (chairman and{{wbr}}&nbsp;CEO)\n| industry         = [[Real estate development]]<br />[[Real estate services]]\n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \u20ac2.6 billion <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| operating_income = \u20ac113.53 million <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nexity.fr/ressource/pdf/1312_statutoryauditorsreportontheconsolidatedfinancialstatements2011.pdf |title=2011 Statutory Auditors\u2019 Report on the Consolidated Financial Statements |publisher=Nexity |format=PDF |accessdate=15 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702182438/http://www.nexity.fr/ressource/pdf/1312_statutoryauditorsreportontheconsolidatedfinancialstatements2011.pdf |archivedate=2 July 2013 }}</ref>\n| net_income       = \u20ac58.15 million <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| aum              =  \n| assets           = \u20ac4.27 billion <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"AL2011\"/>\n| equity           =