e built, now A3220.<ref name=\"exclusions\">Under its charter, motorways are excluded from the remit of [[Transport for London]].  These routes had their motorway status removed to allow TfL control over them.</ref>\n|-\n| [[A18 road (England)|A18(M)]]\n| A spur from [[M18 motorway (Great Britain)|M18]]. Mostly now part of [[M180 motorway|M180]], although a section has been abandoned.\n|-\n| A36(M)\n| The Ower Spur, now the [[A36 road|A36]].\n|-\n| [[Westway (London)|A40(M)]]\n| The London Westway, now the [[A40 road|A40]].<ref name=\"exclusions\"/>\n|-\n| A41(M)\n| The [[Tring]] bypass, now the [[A41 road|A41]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/former/a41m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A46(M)\n| A spur towards [[Leicester]] from [[M1 motorway|M1]] at junction 21, now part of the [[A5460 road|A5460]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/former/a46m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[East Cross Route|A102(M)]]\n| The London [[East Cross Route]], in two sections:\n*[[Hackney Wick]] to [[Old Ford]] (now the [[A12 road (Great Britain)|A12]]);\n*[[Blackwall Tunnel]] to the [[Sun in the Sands]] roundabout (now the [[A102 road|A102]]<ref name=\"exclusions\"/>). Was the eastern section of the [[Ringway 1|London Motorway Box]].\n|-\n| [[A329(M) motorway|A329(M)]]\n| The northern third of the A329(M) from [[Winnersh]] to [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], now the A3290. Downgraded to permit Reading council to dedicate one lane for buses.\n|-\n| [[A6144(M) motorway|A6144(M)]]\n| Formerly the longest single-carriageway motorway spur in the United Kingdom from the [[M60 motorway|M60]] north of [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]] towards [[Carrington, Greater Manchester|Carrington]]. Now just a spur of the [[A6144 road|A6144]].\n|}\n\n===Motorways that have been renumbered===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=100%\n! width=\"49px\" align=\"center\" | Link\n! Route\n|-\n| [[M16 motorway|M16]]\n| Originally to be the northern section of the [[M25 motorway|M25]] but was renumbered before opening.\n|-\n| M52\n| Absorbed by the M62 when it was extended to form a cross-country route.\n|-\n| M62\n| Originally planned to be the western loop around Manchester and Salford; became part of the M63 when the western extension of the M62 was opened; now the M60 J7-J13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/m62/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[M63 motorway|M63]]\n| Merged with parts of the [[M62 motorway|M62]] and [[M66 motorway|M66]] to form the new [[M60 motorway|M60]] [[Manchester]] orbital motorway.\n|-\n| M65\n| Not considered important enough to carry a two-digit number, it was redesignated as [[M621 motorway|M621]], as it was planned to link the M62 to the M1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/m65/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| M68\n| Became a portion of the M66 when it opened north of the M62. Now [[M60 motorway|M60]] J18-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/m68/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| M85\n| Now [[M90 motorway|M90]] J10-11. Previously the [[M90 motorway|M90]] carried on along the spur into [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], leaving the main route ahead as the M85<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/m85/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| M531\n| Previously an unclassified road, later became the A5032. Now the [[M53 motorway|M53]] J5-10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/m531/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A4(M)\n| Became a portion of the [[M4 motorway|M4]] and later part of the A423(M). Now the [[A404(M) motorway]]. A small section was abandoned.<ref name=\"pathetic.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a4m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A5(M)\n| Provisional number for the Wellington Bypass, redesignated as the [[M54 motorway|M54]] before construction was complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a5m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A8(M)\n| Provisional number for the Renfrew Bypass, now part of the [[M8 motorway (Scotland)|M8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a8m/|title=Pathetic Motorways: A8(M)|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n| A20(M)\n| Now the [[M20 motorway|M20]] J5-8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a20m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A40(M)\n| Now part of the [[M40 motorway|M40]].<ref name=\"pathetic.org.uk\"/>\n|-\n| A48(M)\n| Morriston Bypass; now the M4 J44-46.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a48m_morriston_bypass/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A48(M)\n| Port Talbot Bypass; now the M4 J39-41.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a48m_port_talbot_bypass/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A50\n| Original designation of the [[M1 motorway|M1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a50_london_to_yorkshire_motorway/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A423(M)\n| Originally A4(M)<ref name=\"pathetic.org.uk\"/> and then part of the [[M4 motorway|M4]]. Now the [[A404(M) motorway|A404(M)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a423m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A446(M)\n| Now the [[M6 Toll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a446m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A638(M)\n| Now the [[M606 motorway|M606]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a638m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| A6127(M)\n| Now the [[A167(M) motorway|A167(M)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/lost/a6127m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Motorways under construction or planned===\n\nThe [[Adwick-le-Street]] to [[M62 motorway|M62]] stretch of the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] is under consideration for upgrade to motorway standard, meaning the A1 between [[Blyth, Nottinghamshire|Blyth]], south of [[Doncaster]], to [[Birtley, Tyne and Wear|Birtley]] near [[Gateshead]], would all be part of the same [[A1(M)]] stretch of motorway.\n\nIn addition, the proposal to put a tunnel under the River Thames to the east of Dartford Crossing and the revived Birmingham Western Orbital plans are both described as motorways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://highwaysengland.citizenspace.com/ltc/consultation/|title=Lower Thames Crossing Statutory Consultation - Highways England - Citizen Space|website=highwaysengland.citizenspace.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/revealed-new-bypass-plan-end-14745278|title=Revealed: New bypass plan to end M6 and M5 traffic misery|first=Neil|last=Elkes|date=6 June 2018|website=birminghammail}}</ref>\n\n===Unbuilt motorways===\nThere have been many plans for motorways in the UK that have not been built. Below is a list of plans that were not built (not exhaustive):\n* [[M12 motorway (Great Britain)|M12]] in 3 forms (although a small part was built and is not used - a stub sliproad):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m12/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n** From the London end of the [[M11 motorway|M11]] to [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]];\n** From the London end of the [[M11 motorway|M11]] to [[Maplin Sands]] Airport (also not built);\n** From the [[M25 motorway|M25]] (in the vicinity of the [[M11 motorway|M11]]) to [[Chelmsford]].\n* [[M13 motorway|M13]], from East London to [[Maplin Sands]] airport passing ''south'' of [[Southend]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m13/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* M17 [[Castle Donington]] bypass, a short spur off the [[M1 motorway|M1]];\n* [[M31 motorway|M31]], a bypass of the busiest section of the [[M25 motorway|M25]], cutting the corner for traffic from the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m31/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref> Partially built as the [[A329(M) motorway|A329(M)]] and A3290.\n* M59, [[M58 motorway|M58]] junction 2 to south of [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m59/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* [[M64 motorway|M64]], between the [[M6 motorway|M6]] south of [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and the [[M1 motorway|M1]] near [[Derby]]. Mostly built as the [[A50 road|A50]].\n* M601, which would have entered [[Manchester]] from the [[M62 motorway|M62]] (now the [[M60 motorway|M60]]) in the [[Irwell Valley]] at [[Clifton, Greater Manchester|Clifton]] near [[Pendlebury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m601/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* M650, Airedale Motorway from near [[Silsden]] to [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m650/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* A6(M) (or [[M66 motorway|M66]] extension), which would have formed an eastern bypass for [[Stockport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/a6m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref> As of March 2006, this is still under the planning stage as part of the SEMMMS (south east Manchester multi modal study) project (though not as motorway).\n* A556(M), which would have cut the corner between the M6 and M56 near [[Warrington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/a556m/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Chippenham, Wiltshire|Chippenham]] Spur, off the [[M4 motorway|M4]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/chippenham_spur/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Strensham \u2013 [[Solihull]] motorway, a link between the [[M50 motorway (Great Britain)|M50]] and [[M42 motorway|M42]] or [[M69 motorway|M69]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/siteitems/404.shtml|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Most of the [[M67 motorway|M67]] \u2013 from [[Hattersley]] to the [[M1 motorway|M1]] via the [[Hope Valley, Derbyshire|Hope Valley]] in the [[Peak District]] [[National parks of England and Wales|national park]] and [[Sheffield]]. Various routes have been proposed but have yet to come to fruition due to controversy and/or expense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pathetic.org.uk/unbuilt/m67_manchester_to_sheffield_motorway/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=www.pathetic.org.uk}}</ref> In 2014, the then [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]] MP and [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]], [[Nick Clegg]] signalled his support for improvements to the [[Woodhead pass|Woodhead Pass]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transportnorth.org.uk/north-west/transpennine-go-the-whole-way-complete-the-m67-with-a-tunnel-underneath/|title=TransPennine: \"Go the whole way, complete the M67, with a tunnel underneath\"|date=9 November 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The latest proposal to extend the M67 is to tunnel under the [[Peak District]] from [[Hattersley]] to [[Stannington, Sheffield|Stannington]] (an outer-suburb of [[Sheffield]]) and to link that tunnel to a new underground motorway providing links to the [[M1 motorway|M1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.togganet.co.uk/blog/sheffield-need-prosper/|title=Why is Sheffield Lagging Behind Leeds & Manchester?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nMany cities had urban motorway plans, most of which were not built. [[London]],<ref>[http://www.cbrd.co.uk/histories/ringways/ CBRD Histories: London Ringways] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118062808/http://www.cbrd.co.uk/histories/ringways/ |date=18 November 2012 }}</ref> [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pathetic.org.uk/features/tyneside/|title=Pathetic Motorways|website=pathetic.org.uk}}</ref> [[Liverpool]],<ref name=\"Articles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.roads.org.uk/articles|title=Articles|website=Roads.org.uk}}</ref> [[Manchester]]/[[Greater Manchester|SELNEC]] and [[Glasgow]]<ref name=\"Articles\"/> all had extensive plans.\n\nIt was proposed that the [[A14 road (England)|A14]] upgrade between Huntingdon and Cambridge would be classified as a motorway once complete, however prior to opening it was announced that the road would open as a \"best in class A road\" instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/plans-for-part-of-a14-upgrade-to-become-a-motorway|title=Plans for part of A14 upgrade to become a motorway|work=GOV.UK|access-date=2018-10-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-a14-bypass-to-open-a-year-early|title=New A14 bypass to open a year early|last=Switchboard 0300 330 3000|first=Media enquiries 020 7944 3021 Out of hours media enquiries 020 7944 4292|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Northern Ireland==\n\n===M-designated motorways===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=100%\n! width=\"49px\" align=\"center\" | Link\n! Route\n!  [[Local government in Northern Ireland|Council areas]]\n|-\n| [[M1 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M1]]\n| Linking [[Belfast]] to [[Dungannon]].\n| [[Belfast City Council|Belfast]], [[Lisburn City Council|Lisburn]], [[Craigavon Borough Council|Craigavon]], [[Dungannon and South Tyrone Borough Council|Dungannon and South Tyrone]]\n|-\n| [[M2 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M2]]\n| In two sections, one linking [[Belfast]] to [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]], and the other bypassing [[Ballymena]]. The section in between was planned, but never built.\n| [[Belfast City Council|Belfast]], [[Newtownabbey Borough Council|Newtownabbey]], [[Antrim (borough)|Antrim]], [[Ballymena (borough)|Ballymena]]\n|-\n| [[M3 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M3]]\n| Linking the [[M2 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M2]] in north [[Belfast]] to the [[A2 road (Northern Ireland)|A2 Sydenham Bypass]] in east [[Belfast]].\n| [[Belfast City Council|Belfast]]\n|-\n| [[M5 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M5]]\n| Linking the [[M2 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M2]] in north [[Belfast]] to [[Newtownabbey]].\n| [[Belfast City Council|Belfast]], [[Newtownabbey Borough Council|Newtownabbey]]\n|-\n| [[M12 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M12]]\n| A spur from the [[M1 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M1]] near [[Derrymacash]] to the north of [[Portadown]].\n| [[Craigavon Borough Council|Craigavon]]\n|-\n| [[M22 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M22]]\n| Linking the [[M2 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M2]] at [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]] to [[Randalstown]].\n| [[Antrim (borough)|Antrim]]\n|}\n\n===Upgraded A-road designations===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=100%\n! width=\"49px\" align=\"center\" | Link\n! Route\n!  [[Local government in Northern Ireland|Council areas]]\n|-\n| [[A8(M) motorway (Northern Ireland)|A8(M)]]\n| A spur from the [[M2 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M2]] near [[Glengormley]] to the A8 north-west of [[Newtownabbey]].\n| [[Newtownabbey Borough Council|Newtownabbey]]\n|}\n\n===Unbuilt motorways===\nThe following motorways were planned, but never built.\n* M11, from the [[M1 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M1]] going through [[Lisburn]] and then crossing the M1 again and ending at [[Newry]]<ref name=\"Northern Ireland Roads Site\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wesleyjohnston.com/roads/historymotorwayplans.html|title=History - Northern Ireland Motorway Plans - Northern Ireland Roads Site|website=www.wesleyjohnston.com}}</ref>\n* M23, from the [[M2 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M2]] to [[Derry]]<ref name=\"Northern Ireland Roads Site\"/>\n\nThere were also urban motorway plans for [[Belfast]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wesleyjohnston.com/roads/belfasturbanmotorway.html|title=History - Belfast Urban Motorway and A12 Westlink - Northern Ireland Roads Site|website=www.wesleyjohnston.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Northern Ireland Roads Site\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of numbered roads in the British Isles]]\n*[[Motorways in the Republic of Ireland]]\n*[[List of controlled-access highway systems]]\n*[[Evolution of motorway construction in European nations]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n\n{{UK road lists}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Motorways In The United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:Lists of roads in the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:Motorways in the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:Roads in the United Kingdom|Motorways]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Girton\u2192Girton, Cambridgeshire,M8 motorway\u2192M8 motorway (Scotland)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_motorways_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "South African art", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Culture of South Africa}}\n'''South African art''' is the [[visual art]] produced by the people inhabiting the territory occupied by the modern country of [[South Africa]]. The oldest art objects in the world were discovered in a South African cave. Archaeologists have discovered two sets of art kits thought to be 100,000 years old at a cave in South Africa. The findings provide a glimpse into how early humans produced and stored [[ochre]] \u2013 a form of paint \u2013 which pushes back our understanding of when evolved complex cognition occurred by around 20,000 \u2013 30,000 years. Also, dating from 75,000 years ago, they found small drilled snail shells could have no other function than to have been strung on a string as a necklace. South Africa was one of the cradles of the human species.\n\nThe scattered tribes of [[Khoisan]] and [[San people|San]] peoples moving into South Africa from around 10000 [[Anno Domini|BC]] had their own art styles seen today in a multitude of cave paintings.<ref name=\"South African art\">{{cite web|title=South African art|url=http://www.southafrica.info/about/arts/art.htm#.Vw5td8d6FlI|website=www.southafrica.info|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> They were superseded by [[Bantu peoples|Bantu]] and [[Nguni people|Nguni]] peoples with their own vocabularies of art forms.\n\nIn the present era, traditional tribal forms of art were scattered and re-melded by the divisive policies of [[apartheid]]. New forms of art evolved in the mines and [[townships]]: a dynamic art using everything from plastic strips to bicycle spokes. In addition to this, there also is the [[Dutch people|Dutch]]-influenced [[folk art]] of the [[Afrikaner]] Trek [[Boer]]s and the urban white artists earnestly following changing European traditions from the 1850s onwards, making for an eclectic mix which continues to evolve today.\n\n== Paleolithic Rock Art==\n[[File:Karoo sandstone with bushmen paintings.jpg|thumb|Sandstone with bushmen rock paintings, [[Karoo System]], ([[Amathole Mountains]], South Africa)]]\n\nThe pre-Bantu peoples migrating southwards from around the year 30,000 [[Anno Domini|BC]] were nomadic hunters who favoured caves as dwellings. Before the rise of the Nguni peoples along the east and southern coasts and central areas of Africa these nomadic hunters were widely distributed. It is thought they entered South Africa at least 10 years ago. They have left lots of signs of life, people toilets and rocks ('[[Bushmen|Bushman]]' paintings) depicting hunting, domestic and magic-related art.<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|title=Paleolithic Period|url=http://www.britannica.com/event/Paleolithic-Period|website=Britannica|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> There is a stylistic unity across the region and even with more ancient art in the [[Tassili n'Ajjer]] region of northern Africa, and also in what is now desert [[Chad]] but was once a lush landscape.\n\nThe figures are dynamic and elongate, and the colours (derived probably from earthen and plant pigments and possibly also from insects) combine ochreous red, white, grey, black, and many warm tones ranging from red through to primary yellow. Common subjects include hunting, often depicting with great accuracy large animals which no longer inhabit the same region in the modern era, as well as: warfare among humans, dancing, domestic scenes, multiple images of various animals, including giraffes, antelope of many kinds, and snakes. The last of these works are poignant in their representation of larger, darker people and even of white hunters on horseback, both of whom would supplant the 'Bushman' peoples.\n \nMany of the 'dancing' figures are decorated with unusual patterns and may be wearing masks and other festive clothing. Other paintings, depicting patterned quadrilaterals and other symbols, are obscure in their meaning and may be non-representational. Similar symbols are seen in [[shaman]]istic art worldwide. This art form is distributed from Angola in the west to [[Mozambique]] and [[Kenya]], throughout [[Zimbabwe]] and South Africa and throughout [[Botswana]] wherever cave conditions have favoured preservation from the elements.\n\n==Contemporary Art in South Africa==\n\nThe [[contemporary art]] scene in South Africa is as diverse and vibrant as the population and cultures in the country. Contemporary artists in South Africa have adopted new media technologies to produce varied and creative bodies of work, as seen in the work of [[Dineo Seshee Bopape]] and CUSS Group.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams-Wynn|first1=Christopher|last2=McCulloch|first2=Samantha|title=Between the Archive and the Real: Contemporary Digital Art and South Africa|journal=[[Third Text]]|year=2016|issn=0952-8822|doi=10.1080/09528822.2016.1213959}}</ref> Their art gives insight into the pressing issues of South African society. On a global scale, contemporary South African art is relevant and sought-after. A charcoal and oil on canvas work by leading South African contemporary artist [[William Kentridge]] was sold on auction for R3,5&nbsp;million in London in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Contemporary South African Artists|url=http://www.southafrica.net/za/en/articles/entry/article-southafrica.net-contemporary-south-african-artists|publisher=South Africa.net|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Art 21, Inc|url=http://www.art21.org/artists/william-kentridge|website=Art 21|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Black Art Post-Apartheid ==\nDue the Bantu Education Act of 1955, Black South Africans were barred from receiving formal art training during the years of apartheid and as a result, the artistic movements that had originated from this community have, until recently, been distinctly classified as \u201ccraft\u201d rather than \u201cart.\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marschall|first=Sabine|date=21/2001|title=Strategies of Accommodation: Toward an Inclusive Canon of South African Art|journal=Art Journal|volume=60|issue=1|pages=50\u201359|doi=10.2307/778045|jstor=778045}}</ref> Informal art centers, that were funded by European states, became one of the few avenues in which Black South Africans could receive some form of artistic development. Throughout this time period from 1947 to the mid-1990s, the first practitioners to receive this informal training began passing down their knowledge to younger generations of practitioners.<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 43635180|title = South African Art in the Global Context|journal = Pr\u00e9sence Africaine|issue = 167/168|pages = 119\u2013126|last1 = Koloane|first1 = David|year = 2003}}</ref> However, the traditional canon of African art, categorized as \u201cfine art\u201d had been formed in the 20th century by European and U.S. art audiences.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Rovine|first=Victoria L.|date=December 2004|title=South Africa from North America: Exporting Identities through Art|journal=African Arts|volume=37|issue=4|pages=48\u201395|doi=10.1162/afar.2004.37.4.48|issn=0001-9933}}</ref> South Africa\u2019s inequality gap is larger than that of other countries in the world so the audience for art is primarily the rich and not those who are subject to the artistic expression, giving these higher socio-economic groups a gatekeeper status in deciding what is classified as art.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klopper|first=Sandra|last2=Godby|first2=Michael|date=December 2004|title=Introduction|journal=African Arts|volume=37|issue=4|pages=16\u201317|doi=10.1162/afar.2004.37.4.16|issn=0001-9933}}</ref> After the Soweto Riots of 1976, a new social consciousness emerged that retaliated against the government\u2019s policy of segregation and effectively reexamined the classification of certain Black South African artworks. One of the first artistic styles to receive critic attention was Venda sculpting because it aesthetically appealed to white patrons while also maintaining its \u201cartistic manifestations of ethnic diversity.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> These sculptures would be considered \u201ctransitional art\u201d rather than \u201ccraft\u201d and would gain access into fine art galleries. Other Black artistic expressions such as beadwork, photography, and studio arts have also begun to be slowly integrated into canonical South African art forms.\n\nThe Johannesburg Biennale\u2019s ''Africus'' (1995) and ''Trade Routes'' (1997) had a significant impact on the cultural awareness of new South African art. These events were among the first exhibitions that revealed the \u201cnew South African art\u201d to the international community, but also other local South Africans.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marschall|first=Sabine|date=June 1999|title=The impact of the two Johannesburg biennales (1995 and 1997) on the formation of a 'New South African art'|journal=Social Dynamics|volume=25|issue=2|pages=119\u2013137|doi=10.1080/02533959908458678|issn=0253-3952}}</ref> This gave Black South African artists a new platform to express the effects to which apartheid had influenced society. In the post-apartheid regime, artists have now been given an apparatus to protest social issues such as inequality, sexuality, state control over the personal realm, and HIV/AIDS.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the emphasis to embody many of these social issues within Black South African art has a led to a stereotype that many young artists are now trying to escape. International pressure has been said to once again demand a level of \u2018authenticity\u2019 within South African art that portrays discourse on the topic of apartheid. Scholar Victoria Rovine goes as far as to state that \u201cthese exhibitions represent a South Africa that seeks liberation not from apartheid itself but from apartheid as an already predictable subject for artistic production.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Furthermore, although South African art is not always political, conversations stemming from its interpretation are rarely apolitical and the high demand for apartheid symbols by private collectors have raised concerns over the collection of the art for the sake of nostalgia. <ref>Ross, D. (1994). On Art and Museums in South Africa before the Elections. African Arts, 27(1), 1-13. doi:10.2307/3337165</ref>\n\n==Arts Education in South Africa==\n\nMajor universities and tertiary institutions offer Fine Art, Music, Photography and other creative disciplines:\n*[[Nelson Mandela Metropolitan University]]\n*[[Michaelis School of Fine Art]], [[University of Cape Town]]\n*[[North-West University]]\n*[http://sun025.sun.ac.za/portal/page/portal/Arts/Departments/visual-arts Stellenbosch University]\n*[http://www.unisa.ac.za/Default.asp?Cmd=ViewContent&ContentID=15909 UNISA]\n*[http://www.wits.ac.za/wsoa Wits School of Arts]\n*[http://www.tut.ac.za/Students/facultiesdepartments/art/Pages/default.aspx Tshwane University of Technology (TUT)]\n*[http://www.ruthprowse.co.za/ Ruth Prowse School of Art]\n*[http://www.cput.ac.za/academic/faculties/informaticsdesign/departments Cape Peninsula University of Technology (CPUT)]\n*[http://www.artschool.co.za/ National School of the Arts]\n*[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=1584 University of Pretoria]\n*[http://www.ufh.ac.za/faculties/ssh/schools/h/index.html University of Fort Hare]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140710205336/http://www.uj.ac.za/EN/Faculties/fada/Pages/default.aspx University of Johannesburg Faculty of ART, Design & Architecture]\n*[http://www.ru.ac.za/fineart/programmes/ Rhodes University]\n*[http://www.vut.ac.za/index.php/faculties/human-sciences/departments/department-of-visual-arts-and-design Vaal University of Technology]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Culture of South Africa]]\n*[[List of South African artists]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite news |author1=Andrew Solomon |title=The Artists of South Africa: Separate, and Equal |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1994-03-27 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/27/magazine/the-artists-of-south-africa-separate-and-equal.html |issn=0362-4331 |df=mdy-all }}\n*http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/creatology/stone-age-art-kit-found-in-south-african-cave/\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Commons category-inline|Art of South Africa}}\n*[http://www.artthrob.co.za/ Artthrob]\n*[http://www.goodman-gallery.com/ Goodman Gallery]\n*[http://www.stateoftheart-gallery.com StateoftheART]\n\n<!--Navigation boxes-->\n{{South Africa topics}}\n{{African topic|| art}}\n{{Life in South Africa}}\n\n[[Category:South African art| ]]\n[[Category:African art|South Africa]]\n[[Category:Art by country|South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Culture of South Africa}}\n'''South African art''' is the [[visual art]] produced by the people inhabiting the territory occupied by the modern country of [[South Africa]]. The oldest art objects in the world were discovered in a South African cave. Archaeologists have discovered two sets of art kits thought to be 100,000 years old at a cave in South Africa. The findings provide a glimpse into how early humans produced and stored [[ochre]] \u2013 a form of paint \u2013 which pushes back our understanding of when evolved complex cognition occurred by around 20,000 \u2013 30,000 years. Also, dating from 75,000 years ago, they found small drilled snail shells could have no other function than to have been strung on a string as a necklace. South Africa was one of the cradles of the human species.\n\nThe scattered tribes of [[Khoisan]] and [[San people|San]] peoples moving into South Africa from around 10000 [[Anno Domini|BC]] had their own art styles seen today in a multitude of cave paintings.<ref name=\"South African art\">{{cite web|title=South African art|url=http://www.southafrica.info/about/arts/art.htm#.Vw5td8d6FlI|website=www.southafrica.info|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> They were superseded by [[Bantu peoples|Bantu]] and [[Nguni people|Nguni]] peoples with their own vocabularies of art forms.\n\nIn the present era, traditional tribal forms of art were scattered and re-melded by the divisive policies of [[apartheid]]. New forms of art evolved in the mines and [[townships]]: a dynamic art using everything from plastic strips to bicycle spokes. In addition to this, there also is the [[Dutch people|Dutch]]-influenced [[folk art]] of the [[Afrikaner]] Trek [[Boer]]s and the urban white artists earnestly following changing European traditions from the 1850s onwards, making for an eclectic mix which continues to evolve today.\n\n== Paleolithic Rock Art==\n[[File:Karoo sandstone with bushmen paintings.jpg|thumb|Sandstone with bushmen rock paintings, [[Karoo System]], ([[Amathole Mountains]], South Africa)]]\n\nThe pre-Bantu peoples migrating southwards from around the year 30,000 [[Anno Domini|BC]] were nomadic hunters who favoured caves as dwellings. Before the rise of the Nguni peoples along the east and southern coasts and central areas of Africa these nomadic hunters were widely distributed. It is thought they entered South Africa at least 10 years ago. They have left lots of signs of life, people toilets and rocks ('[[Bushmen|Bushman]]' paintings) depicting hunting, domestic and magic-related art.<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|title=Paleolithic Period|url=http://www.britannica.com/event/Paleolithic-Period|website=Britannica|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> There is a stylistic unity across the region and even with more ancient art in the [[Tassili n'Ajjer]] region of northern Africa, and also in what is now desert [[Chad]] but was once a lush landscape.\n\nThe figures are dynamic and elongate, and the colours (derived probably from earthen and plant pigments and possibly also from insects) combine ochreous red, white, grey, black, and many warm tones ranging from red through to primary yellow. Common subjects include hunting, often depicting with great accuracy large animals which no longer inhabit the same region in the modern era, as well as: warfare among humans, dancing, domestic scenes, multiple images of various animals, including giraffes, antelope of many kinds, and snakes. The last of these works are poignant in their representation of larger, darker people and even of white hunters on horseback, both of whom would supplant the 'Bushman' peoples.\n \nMany of the 'dancing' figures are decorated with unusual patterns and may be wearing masks and other festive clothing. Other paintings, depicting patterned quadrilaterals and other symbols, are obscure in their meaning and may be non-representational. Similar symbols are seen in [[shaman]]istic art worldwide. This art form is distributed from Angola in the west to [[Mozambique]] and [[Kenya]], throughout [[Zimbabwe]] and South Africa and throughout [[Botswana]] wherever cave conditions have favoured preservation from the elements.\n\n==Contemporary Art in South Africa==\n\nThe [[contemporary art]] scene in South Africa is as diverse and vibrant as the population and cultures in the country. Contemporary artists in South Africa have adopted new media technologies to produce varied and creative bodies of work, as seen in the work of [[Dineo Seshee Bopape]] and CUSS Group.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams-Wynn|first1=Christopher|last2=McCulloch|first2=Samantha|title=Between the Archive and the Real: Contemporary Digital Art and South Africa|journal=[[Third Text]]|year=2016|issn=0952-8822|doi=10.1080/09528822.2016.1213959}}</ref> Their art gives insight into the pressing issues of South African society. On a global scale, contemporary South African art is relevant and sought-after. A charcoal and oil on canvas work by leading South African contemporary artist [[William Kentridge]] was sold on auction for R3,5&nbsp;million in London in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Contemporary South African Artists|url=http://www.southafrica.net/za/en/articles/entry/article-southafrica.net-contemporary-south-african-artists|publisher=South Africa.net|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Art 21, Inc|url=http://www.art21.org/artists/william-kentridge|website=Art 21|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Black Art Post-Apartheid ==\nDue the Bantu Education Act of 1955, Black South Africans were barred from receiving formal art training during the years of apartheid and as a result, the artistic movements that had originated from this community have, until recently, been distinctly classified as \u201ccraft\u201d rather than \u201cart.\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marschall|first=Sabine|date=21/2001|title=Strategies of Accommodation: Toward an Inclusive Canon of South African Art|journal=Art Journal|volume=60|issue=1|pages=50\u201359|doi=10.2307/778045|jstor=778045}}</ref> Informal art centers, that were funded by European states, became one of the few avenues in which Black South Africans could receive some form of artistic development. Throughout this time period from 1947 to the mid-90's, the first practitioners to receive this informal training began passing down their knowledge to younger generations of practitioners.<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 43635180|title = South African Art in the Global Context|journal = Pr\u00e9sence Africaine|issue = 167/168|pages = 119\u2013126|last1 = Koloane|first1 = David|year = 2003}}</ref> However, the traditional canon of African art, categorized as \u201cfine art\u201d had been formed in the 20th century by European and U.S. art audiences.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Rovine|first=Victoria L.|date=December 2004|title=South Africa from North America: Exporting Identities through Art|journal=African Arts|volume=37|issue=4|pages=48\u201395|doi=10.1162/afar.2004.37.4.48|issn=0001-9933}}</ref> South Africa\u2019s inequality gap is larger than that of other countries in the world so the audience for art is primarily the rich and not those who are subject to the artistic expression, giving these higher socio-economic groups a gatekeeper status in deciding what is classified as art.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klopper|first=Sandra|last2=Godby|first2=Michael|date=December 2004|title=Introduction|journal=African Arts|volume=37|issue=4|pages=16\u201317|doi=10.1162/afar.2004.37.4.16|issn=0001-9933}}</ref> After the Soweto Riots of 1976, a new social consciousness emerged that retaliated against the government\u2019s policy of segregation and effectively reexamined the classification of certain Black South African artworks. One of the first artistic styles to receive critic attention was Venda sculpting because it aesthetically appealed to white patrons while also maintaining its \u201cartistic manifestations of ethnic diversity.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> These sculptures would be considered \u201ctransitional art\u201d rather than \u201ccraft\u201d and would gain access into fine art galleries. Other Black artistic expressions such as beadwork, photography, and studio arts have also begun to be slowly integrated into canonical South African art forms.\n\nThe Johannesburg Biennale\u2019s ''Africus'' (1995) and ''Trade Routes'' (1997) had a significant impact on the cultural awareness of new South African art. These events were among the first exhibitions that revealed the \u201cnew South African art\u201d to the international community, but also other local South Africans.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marschall|first=Sabine|date=June 1999|title=The impact of the two Johannesburg biennales (1995 and 1997) on the formation of a 'New South African art'|journal=Social Dynamics|volume=25|issue=2|pages=119\u2013137|doi=10.1080/02533959908458678|issn=0253-3952}}</ref> This gave Black South African artists a new platform to express the effects to which apartheid had influenced society. In the post-apartheid regime, artists have now been given an apparatus to protest social issues such as inequality, sexuality, state control over the personal realm, and HIV/AIDS.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the emphasis to embody many of these social issues within Black South African art has a led to a stereotype that many young artists are now trying to escape. International pressure has been said to once again demand a level of \u2018authenticity\u2019 within South African art that portrays discourse on the topic of apartheid. Scholar Victoria Rovine goes as far as to state that \u201cthese exhibitions represent a South Africa that seeks liberation not from apartheid itself but from apartheid as an already predictable subject for artistic production.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Furthermore, although South African art is not always political, conversations stemming from its interpretation are rarely apolitical and the high demand for apartheid symbols by private collectors have raised concerns over the collection of the art for the sake of nostalgia. <ref>Ross, D. (1994). On Art and Museums in South Africa before the Elections. African Arts, 27(1), 1-13. doi:10.2307/3337165</ref>\n\n==Arts Education in South Africa==\n\nMajor universities and tertiary institutions offer Fine Art, Music, Photography and other creative disciplines:\n*[[Nelson Mandela Metropolitan University]]\n*[[Michaelis School of Fine Art]], [[University of Cape Town]]\n*[[North-West University]]\n*[http://sun025.sun.ac.za/portal/page/portal/Arts/Departments/visual-arts Stellenbosch University]\n*[http://www.unisa.ac.za/Default.asp?Cmd=ViewContent&ContentID=15909 UNISA]\n*[http://www.wits.ac.za/wsoa Wits School of Arts]\n*[http://www.tut.ac.za/Students/facultiesdepartments/art/Pages/default.aspx Tshwane University of Technology (TUT)]\n*[http://www.ruthprowse.co.za/ Ruth Prowse School of Art]\n*[http://www.cput.ac.za/academic/faculties/informaticsdesign/departments Cape Peninsula University of Technology (CPUT)]\n*[http://www.artschool.co.za/ National School of the Arts]\n*[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=1584 University of Pretoria]\n*[http://www.ufh.ac.za/faculties/ssh/schools/h/index.html University of Fort Hare]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140710205336/http://www.uj.ac.za/EN/Faculties/fada/Pages/default.aspx University of Johannesburg Faculty of ART, Design & Architecture]\n*[http://www.ru.ac.za/fineart/programmes/ Rhodes University]\n*[http://www.vut.ac.za/index.php/faculties/human-sciences/departments/department-of-visual-arts-and-design Vaal University of Technology]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Culture of South Africa]]\n*[[List of South African artists]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite news |author1=Andrew Solomon |title=The Artists of South Africa: Separate, and Equal |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1994-03-27 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/27/magazine/the-artists-of-south-africa-separate-and-equal.html |issn=0362-4331 |df=mdy-all }}\n*http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/creatology/stone-age-art-kit-found-in-south-african-cave/\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Commons category-inline|Art of South Africa}}\n*[http://www.artthrob.co.za/ Artthrob]\n*[http://www.goodman-gallery.com/ Goodman Gallery]\n*[http://www.stateoftheart-gallery.com StateoftheART]\n\n<!--Navigation boxes-->\n{{South Africa topics}}\n{{African topic|| art}}\n{{Life in South Africa}}\n\n[[Category:South African art| ]]\n[[Category:African art|South Africa]]\n[[Category:Art by country|South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_art"}
